<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate wraps up its session ... for now  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Legislation that would prohibit
telemarketers from accessing bank accounts without the written
consent of consumers was passed Wednesday by both houses of the
state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was one of numerous bills passed in the state Senate
and Assembly as legislators scrambled to iron out last-minute deals
before the 2000 session ends. Senators on Wednesday held what
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno said was the last day of his chamber's
regular session.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Bruno set Wednesday, June 14, as the deadline
for ''completion'' of the official Senate session, and his house
stuck to that self-imposed date by ending the session nine minutes
before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said he was ''very pleased'' that the deadline was met but
added that senators will be back next Thursday to take up any
unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Senate and the Assembly on Wednesday approved two bills
designed to bail wealthy Nassau County on Long Island out of its
financial troubles. One measure calls for the creation of an
interim oversight board to review the county's budgeting. The
second bill would provide state aid to Nassau County, Buffalo and
Yonkers, and allow New York City to borrow $4 billion more.
</P>
<P>
   The two chambers also unanimously passed late Wednesday night a
bill requiring only self-extinguishing cigarettes to be sold in New
York by mid-2003 and an accompanying measure that increases
penalties for bootlegging cigarettes. Legislative leaders reached
an agreement on the Fire-safe Cigarette Act earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The telemarketing bill targets deceptive practices that
lawmakers said were not addressed by the federal Telemarketing
Sales Rule of 1996. The bill would require telemarketers in New
York to be bonded and registered with the state. Telemarketers
would also have to state the purpose of the solicitation call and
the price of the goods before asking for personal and financial
information from the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the measure would require telemarketers to keep
records of calls and sales for two years and ban courier pick-ups
for payments before a person can inspect the product.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Retired Persons, which lobbied hard
for the legislation, applauded the bill. AARP's Ollie Owen said the
law has ''real teeth'' and that it would ''fill the gaps'' in the
federal regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Requiring written authorization for accessing these accounts
puts an additional step in the process which will help protect
people from impulsive decisions they can't back away from,'' Owen
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the state Office of the Aging, 85 percent of
victims of telemarketing fraud are people over age 65.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was part of a three-way agreement between the Senate,
Assembly and Gov. George Pataki's office. It now goes to the
governor for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, legislative leaders and Pataki reached a deal on
establishing automatic cost-of-living increases for the retirees of
state and local governments. The package, passed by the Senate
Wednesday night, still needed Assembly approval.
</P>
<P>
   Issues that remained unresolved Wednesday included legislation
to toughen penalties for sex assaults and school violence, to
impose more controls over the sales of guns and to toughen
penalties for so-called ''hate crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   In other legislative action Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   -The Assembly passed a bill that would renew the law which
increased the speed limit on some New York highways to 65 mph. The
current law expires on Dec. 1, and the measure would extend its
validity for another five years.
</P>
<P>
   -Both chambers of the state Legislature passed a measure
requiring pet dealers to provide consumers purchasing cats and dogs
with information concerning the animal's health, medical history
and origin. The bill also called for licensing and inspection of
all pet dealers in the state.
</P>
<P>
   -The Senate gave final legislative approval to a bill to give
people falsely accused of abusing a child a way to appeal to the
state to get their names removed from the state's sex abuse
registry. Currently, people's names remain on the registry for 10
years, even if the accusations against them are found to be
baseless.
</P>
<P>
   -The Assembly gave final legislative approval to a bill that
would allow the state Department of Correctional Services to grant
work release to victims of domestic and sexual abuse who were
convicted of assaulting or killing their abusers. Under the
measure, eligibility would be determined in a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   -The Senate passed legislation that would create a DNA Review
Committee to examine cases where convictions were set aside a s a
result of DNA evidence. The panel will also analyze the
implications of DNA technology to the state's criminal justice
system, and it will have the power to review cases and recommend
legal or procedural changes.
</P>
<P>
   -The Assembly unanimously passed legislation that would make the
46-page state constitution gender neutral. The measure was approved
by the Senate on Tuesday. In order to become law, the bill must be
passed again by both houses in the next legislative term and
ratified by New York voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
