<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stanley Cup champions get tailgate party celebration  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) - So it's not Broadway with ticker
tape cascading from towering office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   This is New Jersey: A tailgate party in the parking lot was just
fine, as it was before and after home games.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of more than 40,000 New Jersey Devils fans turned out
Wednesday in a parking lot at the Meadowlands Sports Complex to
celebrate the team's second Stanley Cup championship in six
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman, who was booed loudly by the crowd when
she appeared on the podium wearing a Devils jersey, praised the
team's tenacity when she arrived at the celebration earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are tough and they are gritty,'' Whitman said. ''They
hang together.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor also defended the location of the event.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anybody can have a parade anywhere,'' she said. ''This kind of
celebration is more interactive for the fans. It's better than the
fans standing around to see the team for 10 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Light rain and cool temperatures did not deter fans from
saluting their team. They cheered wildly as captain Scott Stevens
came out with the Cup against a backdrop of fireworks and ticker
tape.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Daneyko summed up the team's feelings as he looked out at
the big crowd, with marshy reeds bobbing in the background as cars
whizzed by in the distance on Route 3 and the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the most gratifying feeling in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Robinson, who hasn't officially decided whether he will
coach the team next season, was greeted with chants of ''One more
year'' as he got up to speak. Robinson later indicated he would
return behind the bench as long as general manager Lou Lamoriello
also comes back under the team's new owners.
</P>
<P>
   The team is about to change hands: Devils owner John McMullen
sold the team to YankeeNets for $175 million and will surrender
control July 12. The team is expected to move to Newark after that.
</P>
<P>
   ''In another month I'm going to join you as a fan,'' McMullen
told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''This team is going to be a model for every other team in the
NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans waving Devils flags and carrying homemade Stanley Cups and
pitchforks formed a sea of red and white as they arrived in the
afternoon for the start of a free Fan Fest with games, food and
music.
</P>
<P>
   State Police reported there were no arrests or incidents at the
celebration. Meadowlands spokeswoman Helen Strus estimated the
crowd at 40,000 to 45,000, based on a count of vehicles in the
parking lot an ''an educated guess'' about how many passengers each
was likely to hold.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters played roller hockey near two giant video screens
bearing the Devils logo as adults quaffed beer and enjoyed tailgate
food. Many wore red and white Devils jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Partley, 13, of Glen Ridge, said he had no problem with the
parking lot venue. ''It's more their home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Schaeffer, 25, of Berlin, dressed his dog, Kylie, in a
Devils T-shirt for the occasion
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Roepke, 35, of Pompton Plains, wore a hat with two Stanley
Cups she made out of casino coin cups and tin foil.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is awesome,'' she said. ''I'm so excited. The finals were
nerve-racking, but they played great.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebration also featured a laser light show and video
highlights of the team's championship season.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils beat the Dallas Stars 2-1 in double overtime
Saturday, propelling them to their first Stanley Cup championship
since 1995, when they swept the Detroit Red Wings in the final
round.
</P>
<P>
   More than 25,000 fans turned out for a victory celebration after
that Stanley Cup, though their enthusiasm was somewhat clouded by
the team's threatened move to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ''Devils Stay! Please!'' read one sign at the 1995 rally,
reflecting the prevailing fan sentiment. That celebration, too, was
held in the parking lots outside the Devils' home building, now
called Continental Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   This time McMullen refused an offer from Newark city officials
to have a ticker-tape parade in downtown Newark, where the team
will go unless a new arena is built in the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Bayonne and West Orange also offered to host the parade, but
McMullen - calling the Meadowlands home - declined.
</P>
<P>
   Devils advocates weren't the only ones celebrating, either: The
author of a ''New Jersey Devils Hate Page'' on the Internet tipped
a hat to the champions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite the fact this is an anti-NJ Devils site, I
congratulate the Devils on their Cup victory,'' the site said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
