<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Cendant executives admit inflating revenues before merger  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Three former executives blame their
superiors at CUC International for perpetrating years of accounting
fraud that brought a stock meltdown after it merged with
franchising giant HFS Inc. to become Cendant Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal led to the largest-ever settlement in a shareholder
class-action suit.
</P>
<P>
   Under oath, the three said their manipulations were done at the
behest of their bosses and that they will cooperate in a continuing
investigation that involves the FBI and the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a culture that had been developed over a period of
years. It was ingrained ... ingrained in us by our superiors,''
said one of those pleading guilty Wednesday, Cosmo Corigliano,
CUC's former chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure of the irregularities two years ago led to a
one-day, $14 billion meltdown in Cendant's market value, making it
''the largest financial fraud case we've ever brought,'' said
Thomas C. Newkirk, associate director of the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   All three held senior financial posts at CUC of Stamford, Conn.
The company merged with HFS of Parsippany, N.J., to create Cendant
in December 1997. Cendant is now based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants said CUC's quarterly earnings were inflated in
the two years leading up to the merger through improper accounting
methods, including underfunding a reserve on membership
cancellations and drawing money from a merger account in efforts to
boost revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't we call that 'cooking the books?''' U.S. District Judge
William H. Walls asked Casper Sabatino, a CUC accountant in charge
of external reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, sir,'' Sabatino replied. ''Honestly, your honor, I
thought I was doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Also pleading guilty was Anne Pember, CUC's former controller.
</P>
<P>
   The three admitted that their actions led CUC to overstate its
operating income by $116 million in the two years before the
merger, and Cendant to overstate its operating income by $170
million for 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Newkirk said Cendant is cooperating and that he is confident
that HFS was unaware of the fraud when it merged with CUC.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant consented to a finding that it violated reporting,
corporate record-keeping and other provisions of federal securities
laws, but that imposed no penalty in recognition of ''remedial acts
promptly undertaken by Cendant'' and its cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   In civil charges filed Wednesday, the SEC accused Corigliano and
Pember of avoiding $15 million in losses by selling CUC and Cendant
stock before the fraud was disclosed. They are contesting the
action.
</P>
<P>
   Sabatino and Kevin Kearney, who was CUC's director of financial
reporting, agreed to settle related SEC charges without admitting
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Three other former CUC officials settled SEC administrative
charges they violated corporate record-keeping provisions of
federal securities laws, with two agreeing to pay penalties of
$25,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   In the criminal case, Corigliano, 40, of Old Saybrook, Conn.,
who became Cendant executive vice president for international
operations after the merger, pleaded guilty to conspiracy and wire
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Pember, 40, of Madison, Conn., who became Cendant's senior vice
president for accounting, pleaded guilty to conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Sabatino, 47, of Sherman, Conn., who became Cendant's vice
president for business development, pleaded guilty to aiding and
abetting wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   All remain free on $100,000 bond pending sentencing Sept. 12,
when each faces a term of up to several years in prison, but could
get probation because of their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant also said the 12-year duration of the fraud supports its
contention ''it could not have occurred without the gross
negligence, if not more, of CUC's auditors.''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1999, the accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young LLP agreed
to pay Cendant shareholders $335 million to settle a lawsuit
brought against it for its work at CUC.
</P>
<P>
   Also that month, Cendant said it would pay its shareholders
$2.83 billion to settle similar allegations. Lawyers for the
shareholders say the settlement was the largest ever achieved in a
securities class-action lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The settlements are pending before Walls.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Cendant closed at $35.625 on April 15, 1998. After
disclosing the accounting problems, shares of Cendant finished the
next day at $19.063, causing the company's market value to fall by
$14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant was trading up 18.875 cents to $12.438 Wednesday on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant is the franchiser of brand names such as Ramada, Avis
and Century 21. CUC was a direct marketing firm that sold
memberships in discount buying clubs.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. attorney's office in Newark:
http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
<P>
   Cendant: http://www.cendant.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
