<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonfire Collapse Inquiry Suggested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) -- A state engineering board voted
Wednesday to launch an investigation into last year's deadly
bonfire celebration at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Board of Professional Engineers said the construction
of the 55-foot-tall log stack being built for the bonfire may have
violated state engineering laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a complex structure that should have had engineering
controls,'' board member Dave Dorchester said. ''That gives the
board jurisdiction over the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, a public structure costing more than $8,000 and
requiring structural, electrical or mechanical engineering
expertise must be designed and supervised by a licensed
professional engineer.
</P>
<P>
   The board could impose fines of up to $3,000 per violation.
</P>
<P>
   On May 2, a commission appointed by A&AMP;M blamed flawed
construction and a lack of adequate supervision of students
assembling the 2 million-pound log stack for the Nov. 18 collapse
that killed 12 students and injured 27 others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
