<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Students will be allowed to graduate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MANLIUS, N.Y. (AP) - Sixteen students arrested earlier this week
after a water balloon fight got out of hand will be allowed to
graduate in June.
</P>
<P>
   Fayetteville-Manlius High School Principal James Chupaila said
the event is a tradition that has soured in recent years after
students began filling the balloons with paint or urine instead of
water.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't see what purpose not participating would serve,''
Chupaila said. ''They were arrested, so we felt it would be a
sufficient penalty in itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Two youths were charged with inciting a riot and one with
attempted assault for trying to punch a police officer. Other
students were charged with a variety of crimes including
trespassing, unlawful assembly and disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   No police officers were injured in Monday's fracas, which
included as many as 100 students who pelted police with water
balloons and ignored repeated requests to leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
