<DOCNO> APW20000615.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Convicted Killer's Appeal Rejected  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- For the second time, a judge has denied a new
trial for a man blamed in the deaths of 24 young Atlanta blacks two
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Hal Craig once again dismissed Wayne
Williams' claims that prosecutors were guilty of misconduct and
that his attorneys failed to effectively represent him during his
1982 trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''It totally was not unexpected on our part, because he had
already shown bias to the facts,'' Williams' attorney, Lynn
Whatley, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 42, is serving a life sentence for the murders of
Nathaniel Cater, 27, and Jimmy Ray Payne, 21. They were among 29
blacks, mostly children, whose slayings between 1979 and 1981 led
to one of the most intensive investigations of the century.
</P>
<P>
   After his conviction, authorities blamed Williams for 22 other
slayings but never charged him. Five of the 29 murders investigated
by a special task force remain officially open.
</P>
<P>
   Whatley said he will appeal the judge's latest decision to the
Georgia Supreme Court. Defense attorneys contends prosecutors
suppressed evidence, violating U.S. Supreme Court rulings that
evidence must be turned over to a defendant before going to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Craig previously denied Williams' request for a new trial in
1998. But the Georgia Supreme Court ruled last year that Craig
wrongly dismissed two grounds raised by Williams and ordered the
judge to reconsider them. The latest ruling was issued Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
