<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Probed About Russian Arrest  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin begins his visit
to Europe's richest country, Germany, with hopes of winning
concessions on debts and attracting new investments, but haunted by
questions about Moscow's commitment to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Spain on Wednesday, Putin denied the arrest a day
earlier of media tycoon Vladimir Gusinsky -- widely criticized as a
step backward to Soviet-style repression -- was punishment for
critical reporting about the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the arrest was likely to be among the issues raised when
Putin meets Thursday morning with Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder,
government spokesman Uwe-Karsten Heye said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We follow with great interest internal political developments
in Russia,'' Heye said.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky, owner of the Media-Most holding company that includes
the independent NTV television channel and several other media
outlets, is being held in Moscow's Butyra jail on suspicion of
taking part in the theft of $10 million in state funds in a
privatization deal.
</P>
<P>
   One of Russia's so-called oligarchs, Gusinsky helped engineer
Boris Yeltsin's re-election in 1996. But his NTV station has turned
increasingly critical of the government as the war in Chechnya
re-erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya was also to be an issue during Putin's meeting with
Schroeder in his temporary chancellery, the building formerly used
by communist East German leaders that is serving as Schroeder's
office until a new one is finished.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has loudly criticized human rights abuses by the Russian
military in the breakaway republic, and officials say Schroeder
will push a policy of ''change through dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's return to Germany marks a return to his old stomping
grounds: He served as a KGB agent in Dresden for five years and is
said to speak fluent German.
</P>
<P>
   His intelligence background and easy March election victory
after Yeltsin's surprise resignation has caused many to question
Putin's commitment to democracy -- fears raised anew after
Gusinsky's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Former Soviet dissident Natan Sharansky urged Russia to consider
releasing Gusinsky at least until formal charges are brought or a
trial begins.
</P>
<P>
   ''As soon as a person like that is arrested, it raises all kinds
of fears,'' Sharansky, now Israel's interior minister, said in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The European Jewish Congress on Wednesday also asked for the
immediate release of Gusinsky, who is Jewish and the chairman of
the group's council of economic and diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said it did not have enough information to
assess whether the arrest was politically motivated. But spokesman
Joe Lockhart said President Clinton had raised the issue of a free
press when he met with Putin in Moscow earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think for our purposes, we'll continue to make the case that
a free and open press is an essential part of a democracy, and
that, in this particular case, this gentleman should not be
prosecuted for any reason relating to his position in the media,''
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said in Spain that he had not known about the arrest and
promised to look into the case on his return. If the law was
violated, he said he would take action against those responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sincerely worried,'' Putin said during a joint news
conference with Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the arrest, Putin was likely to leave home empty
handed in his quest to win any debt relief.
</P>
<P>
   Germany was Russia's top Western trading partner and biggest
financial backer in the 1990s, supporting the transformation from
communism to capitalism with some $67 billion in loans, grants,
credits and other guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   But German interest in Russia has waned since 1998, when banks
and other investors were forced to swallow major losses following
the collapse of the ruble. German direct investment in Russia
peaked at $347 million that year, but tumbled in 1999 to only $221
million.
</P>
<P>
   German government officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Russia is looking to have at least some of the $24 billion to
$29 billion it owes Germany written off. The officials insist that
is not going to happen, and that they will only entertain talks on
debt restructuring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 0049 </TRAILER>
