<DOCNO> APW20000615.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Soldiers Buried in Calif.  </HEADLINE>
By CHELSEA J. CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTMINSTER, Calif. (AP) -- When her mother died, Michelle Ngo
sought to carry out the woman's final request to be buried next to
her husband, a soldier killed and laid to rest in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Ngo carried out her mother's wish, but she did not have to
travel to Vietnam. It was fulfilled in Orange County at the first
military cemetery for South Vietnamese soldiers and their spouses
outside their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went to Vietnam and brought him back,'' she said. ''We
chose this because it's Little Saigon, part of our culture, our
heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Vietnam War ended in 1975, more than 8,000 South
Vietnamese soldiers who fought against North Vietnamese communist
soldiers have settled in Southern California. Many are in the
bustling Westminster neighborhood known as Little Saigon, a place
full of restaurants and businesses catering to some 200,000
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The cemetery -- the latest addition to the largest community of
Vietnamese outside their native country -- is a poignant symbol of a
homeland lost and gained.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a national cemetery in Saigon, but it was dug up by the
North Vietnamese when they took over,'' said Hoa Pham, a former
South Vietnamese army officer. ''Some families were able to get the
remains of their relatives, but most graves were leveled.''
</P>
<P>
   Vietnamese traditionally believe soldiers must be buried
together, rather than with their families.
</P>
<P>
   Since many soldiers cannot be buried in Vietnam because of the
high cost and bureaucracy, there was a push to create a cemetery
similar to one that existed in Saigon, Westminster City Councilman
Tony Lam said.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two decades of discussion and planning, the
Vietnamese Veteran Cemetery opened last year in Westminster
Memorial Park, a grass field nestled between a busy intersection
and strawberry patch. A replica of a statue of a soldier that once
stood at a cemetery in Bien Hua, Vietnam, is expected to be erected
this year.
</P>
<P>
   There are 300 plots, costing about $4,800 each, and nearly 200
have been sold. They are owned by a group formed two years ago by
former soldiers representing 19 military organizations in Little
Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first buried were Khanh Nhi Tran, 68, and Tuan A. Ngo,
46, both of whom served in the war. Their graves sit side by side
in the shadow of a granite marker bearing the inscription ''To Quoc
Ghi On'' -- a nation in gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ''My dad had two families, his own and that of the veterans,''
Tran's son, Allen Ahn Duc, said at the burial.
</P>
<P>
   To date, more than a dozen people have been buried in the
military cemetery. The plots adjoin the Asian Garden of Peaceful
Eternity marked by a pagoda and reflecting ponds.
</P>
<P>
   The group also created a financial assistance program for
veterans and their spouses who could not afford to pay for funeral
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The veterans' group also wants to build in the cemetery a
similar version of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington,
listing the names of South Vietnamese veterans who died in the war.
</P>
<P>
   ''We fought battles together; we should die in peace together,''
said Dang Thanh Long, who oversaw the project.
</P>
<P>
   Ngo's father, Phung Quoc Ngo, died May 27, 1966, at Long Khan,
Vietnam. He was buried near Saigon. To bring his remains to the
United States, she had to have him cremated.
</P>
<P>
   Ngo visits her parents burial plot about five times a week,
placing yellow flowers and incense on the graves in the traditional
Buddhist fashion of honoring the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe you stay together in death ... like in life,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 0055 </TRAILER>
