<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solomon Islands To Go Back To Police  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- Easing tensions in the
strife-torn Solomon Islands, rebels who seized the capital last
week agreed on Thursday to let the police regain control.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came after Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu,
held last week at gunpoint by the rebels, resigned Wednesday and
unveiled a plan to negotiate a permanent cease-fire between warring
islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope a deal will be reached within the next two weeks,
paving the way for parliament to select a new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ''As from today, the regular police will start to resume control
of law and order enforcement in Honiara City,'' said a joint
statement Thursday by the police and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was signed by Malaitan rebel spokesman Andrew Nori
and the deputy police commissioner, Wilfred Akao.
</P>
<P>
   Akao agreed to continue consultations with the rebels to
''ensure a smooth transition to normal policing.'' But the Malaitan
rebels did not agree to lay down their weapons, seized from an
armory in Honiara last week.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels would disarm only after a comprehensive peace
agreement had been reached and the issue of compensation for land
lost by Malaitans addressed, Nori told Australian Broadcasting
Corp. radio in Honiara on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Malaitan rebels seized control of the capital,
driving their outgunned rivals, the Isatabus, into the surrounding
hills. Both sides have honored an unwritten truce since late last
week. The Malaitans have since been policing the city.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes were growing Thursday that the warring parties will meet
with a committee made up of government and opposition lawmakers to
broker a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-member committee met for the first time Thursday, but was
not yet ready to announce when talks between the rebel factions
might take place, said committee member Fred Fono, Solomons'
minister of development planning.
</P>
<P>
   An Australian warship has moved closer to Solomons' coast and
may be used as a neutral venue for the peace talks or for
parliament, the Australian Defense Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The amphibious landing ship HMAS Manoora, carrying about 200
troops and two Black Hawk helicopters, had previously been anchored
out of sight of the Solomons, overseeing the evacuation of
expatriate Australians fleeing unrest in the South Pacific nation.
</P>
<P>
   It had now entered Solomons' territorial waters about two hours
sailing time from Honiara, a department spokesman said on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Ulufa'alu has criticized Australia and New Zealand, the two
regional powers, for being too passive in their response to the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries rejected his government's appeals to send in
troops to bring order to the Solomons, saying local leaders must
reach a peace agreement first.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict revolves around a land dispute. Isatabus, the
indigenous residents of the Solomons' main island of Guadalcanal,
have forced out migrants from the nearby island of Malaita. About
20,000 Malaitans have been expelled over the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Ulufa'alu, who is now acting as caretaker leader, has warned
that the conflict risks splintering the Solomons, which has been
self-governing since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Malaitan spokesman Nori said Ulufa'alu's action had put the
Solomons on a fast track to peace.
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth foreign ministers, including from Australia and New
Zealand, had talked about giving financial support to compensate
for land losses, but no firm offer was made, Nori said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Tee, a leader for the Isatabu rebels, expressed
disappointment Ulufa'alu had been forced out of office.
</P>
<P>
   But Tee said the Isatabu forces would keep the peace even after
a 14-day cease-fire ends next Saturday, as long as the Malaitans
do.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they fight, we fight. If they sit down, we sit down,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Ulufa'alu urged the Malaitan rebels -- who number
about 500 fighters inside the capital -- to return their weapons so
lawmakers won't be intimidated when parliament reconvenes.
</P>
<P>
   The joint statement by the police and the Malaitan rebels said
arrangements were underway for the rebels to return police vehicles
so that normal patrols could resume.
</P>
<P>
   A curfew will remain in place until police have the capacity to
take full control of security, it said.
</P>
<P>
   The Solomon Islands lie 1,600 miles northeast of Sydney,
Australia, and were the scene of battles between the United States
and Japan during World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 0102 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nassau Bailout Package OK'd  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state Legislature has voted to bail out
one of the wealthiest counties in America, approving a measure
expected to be signed by Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The Nassau County aid package is designed to get the Long Island
county out from under a shortfall of more than $100 million that is
projected to grow to more than $300 million by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The county counts some of the wealthiest residents in New York
among the 1.3 million people in its boundaries just east of New
York City. Its median annual income of $58,155 is among the highest
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County is facing an ultimatum from Wall Street: correct
its finances by June 30 or face a devaluation of its bond rating to
junk status.
</P>
<P>
   There are also strong political overtones to the issue.
Republicans have lost control to Democrats of the state Legislature
in Nassau County, apparently due to the financial morass, for the
first time since World War I. Republicans in the Senate need to
return several members from the county to their chamber this
November to maintain the GOP's majority in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal approved Wednesday, the county has agreed to make
about $200 million in spending cuts over the next four years while
state taxpayers will contribute $105 million to the county.
</P>
<P>
   A seven-member, state-appointed board will oversee county
finances and take direct budget control if local officials fail to
take a fiscally prudent course.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say county administrators and officials got into fiscal
trouble by going eight of the past 10 years without raising
property taxes. In the meantime, county expenses and the cost of
labor contracts continued to go up.
</P>
</TEXT>
