<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alligator Attacks Puppy in Fla.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEMINOLE, Fla. (AP) -- Three young sisters whose family had just
moved here from Virginia could do nothing but watch as their
Dalmatian puppy bounded out into a lake and was killed by an
alligator.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are devastated,'' said Valerie Callaway, the girls' mother.
''We don't have alligators in Virginia.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls tried to call the 46-pound dog back when they spotted
the alligator, but the dog was too interested in some ducks
swimming nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The family moved to a lakeside apartment in March from Dale
City, Va., while they waited for a new home to be built. Sandi had
been a Christmas present for the family's youngest daughter,
4-year-old Rebecca, a fan of the Disney movie ''101 Dalmatians.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca and her two older sisters, Cassandra, 15, and Madison,
8, watched Monday as Sandi darted through an open screen door to
the lake. The girls then spotted the alligator slowly swimming
toward the dog before it suddenly sped up.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Morse, a spokesman for the Florida Fish and Wildlife
Conservation Commission, said the alligator has been a problem
before and will be removed from the area and destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may have lost its fear of people and that's a chance we
don't take,'' he said. ''Other dogs or small children might become
prey items because of their relative size.''
</P>
<P>
   The Callaways said they will seek grief counseling for their
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The alligator attack was one of dozens involving pets every year
in Florida, according to the Conservation Commission. The state
only records attacks against humans. In 52 years alligators have
attacked 265 people. Nine victims have died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 0111 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
