<DOCNO> APW20000615.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Booming in Japan  </HEADLINE>
By GARY SCHAEFER
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Zero-interest Japan is where a lot of interest is
these days for multinational companies looking to sell corporate
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In March last year, Japan's central bank cut a key interest rate
almost to zero in an effort to jump-start its economy.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen months later, the economy is still sputtering.
</P>
<P>
   But sales of foreign corporate bonds in yen are booming thanks
to the Bank of Japan's near-zero interest rate policy, which has
allowed U.S. and European companies to raise money cheaper in Japan
then they can at home.
</P>
<P>
   For Japanese money managers, the yen-denominated bonds recently
sold by the likes of IBM and Xerox Corp. offer a low-risk way out
of their low-return doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   ''Japanese investors have money but no place to invest it,''
said Yoshihara Matsushima, deputy general manager of the
international finance department at Daiwa Securities SB Capital
Markets Co.
</P>
<P>
   Daiwa helped underwrite $1.31 billion worth of yen-denominated
bonds issued Wednesday by IBM.
</P>
<P>
   It was the biggest-ever sale of yen-denominated bonds, or
''samurai bonds,'' by a foreign company, topping the $1.22 billion
worth floated last month by Xerox's finance unit.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year IBM bond pays 0.62 percent interest -- 21.5 basis
points higher than Japanese government bonds with similar maturity.
One hundred basis points are equal to 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That's cheap from the U.S. computer-maker's perspective but
looks attractive to investors in this country, said Yoshio Shima,
director of credit research at Credit Suisse First Boston
Securities (Japan).
</P>
<P>
   Low-risk Japanese corporate bonds such as utilities pay only
around 18 basis points more than the yield on government bonds, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Postal savings accounts, run by the government, were once
extremely popular with savers here. But they are no longer anything
to write home about with interest rates at less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More than $938.4 billion now in 10-year postal saving accounts
is set to mature over the next two years, and a lot of that money
will probably find its way into stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign companies are lining up to cash in.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. nonbank lender Household International and Italian
automaker Fiat are among the big names getting ready to float
yen-denominated bonds.
</P>
<P>
   And they're anxious to get in while the getting is good,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan is expected to begin guiding interest rates
back up as soon as the nation starts to crawl out of its deepest
slump in decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''So there is a big incentive for the debt issuer to issue right
now,'' said Credit Suisse's Shima.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan has kept its overnight loan rate at about 0.02
percent to 0.03 percent since March of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Another incentive for some foreign companies to raise money in
Japan is the need to spend it here.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economic woes have given overseas multinationals
unprecedented opportunities to acquire Japanese assets on the cheap
and to expand their presence in this hard-to-crack market.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners invested a record $13.1 billion in Japan in 1999,
more than triple the previous year -- a trend symbolized by French
automaker Renault SA's purchase of a controlling stake in Nissan
Motor Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 0111 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Mob on Wall Street, Bjt,910  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The mob will not be allowed to settle down on
Wall Street, authorities insisted after revealing that organized
crime had a central role in crimes resulting in charges against
more than 100 people in the country's largest crackdown yet on
securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''The public should be assured that the FBI has and will remain
vigilant against the mob's use of our financial markets as their
playground,'' said Barry W. Mawn, FBI assistant director in charge
of the New York office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's actions are not an indication that the tentacles of
organized crime have reached anywhere beyond the seamy underbelly''
of the penny stock market, said Richard Walker, director of
enforcement of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White announced at a Wednesday news
conference the unsealing in U.S. District Court in Manhattan of 16
indictments and seven criminal complaints detailing various stock
rip-off schemes, many of which had the strongarm of mobsters behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   White said guilty verdicts could lead to prison terms of between
five and 80 years for defendants including a former New York police
detective, a West Coast investment adviser, stock promoters,
brokers, and officers, directors and other insiders of several
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The participants allegedly engaged in racketeering, conspiring
to use bribery, extortion and even soliciting murder to further
frauds reaping more than $50 million in illegal profits. Many more
millions of dollars would have been lost if the arrests had not
been made, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 120 people named in court papers were members of all
five New York crime families, he said.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, 98 suspects had been arrested in New Jersey, New
York, Connecticut, Pennsylvania, Maryland, Virginia, Georgia,
Florida, Alabama, Texas, Illinois, Utah and California, and more
arrests were expected.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments accuse them of engaging in racketeering,
conspiring to use bribery, extortion and even soliciting murder to
further frauds reaping more than $50 million in illegal profits.
Authorities said no one was killed.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, stock brokers were bribed to push worthless
stocks, often through cold calling, in an effort to bid up prices
for their own gain, Walker said. He said the 120 suspects
''otherwise lied, cheated or stole from innocent investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who reneged on a deal was subjected to beatings,
intimidation and threats, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Mawn said the mob's tactics were nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ''No matter what market the mob tries to infiltrate, from the
fish market to the stock market, the methods it uses are always the
same: violence and the threat of violence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the overall scheme, the Internet was sometimes used
to promote stocks, and companies were falsely touted as dot.com
companies to induce investors to capitalize on the Internet boom,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Trading in two companies Walker described as ''the latest
e-commerce wonders'' was suspended Wednesday by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, prosecutors said the FBI learned about the
illegal schemes by secretly recordings about 1,000 hours of
conversations at a DMN Capital Investments Inc., a company White
described as an ''investment banker to the crooked and the
corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the company offered ''its services to anyone and any
deal as long as it was illicit.''
</P>
<P>
   The company allegedly was a New York launchpad for a variety of
schemes involving alleged mobsters who sought to secretly control
or infiltrate various New York City brokerage firms, White said.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone call to DMN seeking comment Wednesday was not
answered.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, Cary F. Cimino, a New York stock
promoter, arranged for secret bribes to be paid to corrupt brokers
and last year allegedly solicited the murder of a person he
believed to be a cooperating witness.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the racketeering machine allegedly tried to
defraud union pension funds by employing corrupt securities
industry professionals to manage union pension funds and taking
kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme recruited an allegedly corrupt money manager, William
P. Stephens, the chief investment officer of Husic Capital
Management, a San Francisco investment adviser, who allegedly
agreed to manage up to $300 million in union pension funds so that
some could be kicked back illegally, prosecutors alleged.
</P>
<P>
   It also recruited a former New York City detective, Stephen E.
Gardell, so it could gain illegal kickbacks from the Detectives'
Endowment Association, which serves New York City detectives,
prosecutors alleged.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Gardell leaked confidential law enforcement
information concerning organized crime investigations to members
and associates of organized crime and provided New York City law
enforcement parking permits to alleged mobsters.
</P>
<P>
   In return, prosecutors said, Gardell receive cash and property,
including $8,000 to build at swimming pool at his home, trips to
Las Vegas and Atlantic City and a fur coat.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, Gardell was released on $500,000 bail after his
lawyer, Joseph Tacopina, told a U.S. magistrate judge that his
client ''maintains his innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardell, greeted by friends and family as he left court,
declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-15-00 0114 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
