<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Seeks To Conserve Airwaves  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The burgeoning popularity of mobile phones, pagers
and wireless
devices has put a squeeze on the nation's airwaves. Now,
communications regulators are looking for new ways to get the most
mileage out of existing frequencies.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ultra-wideband technology offers one solution since it can
operate over a wide swath of the airwaves and in areas occupied by
other radio services.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also is looking at:
</P>
<P>
   --Software defined radio, a technology that enables devices to
seek out pockets of airwaves that are not being used locally and
adapt to those frequencies.
</P>
<P>
   --Creating a secondary market so that slices of the airwaves will
be treated like other commodities that flow in the marketplace. The
Federal Communications Commission wants to move to a system in
which companies that have unused frequencies can sell them to those
who need them at the moment. This would create a spot market akin
to those that exist for petroleum or pork bellies. The commission
recently held its first forum on how to make such a transition.
</P>
<P>
   --Developing a new class of commercial licensees called ''guard
band managers.'' These managers would receive their licenses
through the normal bidding process. But they could then turn around
and lease slices of the airwaves to commercial service providers or
third parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
