<DOCNO> APW20000615.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Koreans Elated at Summit Accord  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The inter-Korean summit turned out
better than many had imagined, ending in clasped hands, champagne
toasts and a historic accord to work toward eventual reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Once the euphoria fades, however, the lengthy, tortuous peace
process begins.
</P>
<P>
   The deal signed in Pyongyang by South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung and North Korean leader Kim Jong Il was the biggest step
toward reconciliation since the 1950-53 Korean War, which ended in
an uneasy armistice.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, South Korean officials said the two leaders
confirmed that their countries have no intention of invading each
other and would not make any threatening moves. The North launched
the Korean War by invading the South, which for years feared
another invasion. The North, in turn, accused the U.S.-backed South
of plotting its downfall.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials who had studiously tried to downplay
summit expectations, saying they would be happy with only a photo
opportunity, prepared to return home in triumph. Kim Dae-jung
lunched with Kim Jong Il on Thursday before his departure for Seoul
later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day summit was steeped in symbolism, a critical
quality because leaders of the two countries had not met since the
peninsula was divided at the end of World War II. Although the text
of Wednesday's agreement did not mention several key disputes, many
South Koreans were elated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't expect to see such a result so soon. I watched
television the whole time. There was nothing I could do to
contribute, but I am happy,'' said Kim Woon-soon, 65, a housewife
who came to pray at a Buddhist temple in downtown Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   The North's media, normally given to diatribes against South
Korea, Japan and the United States, was also upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   The summit ''marked an important occasion of opening a bright
prospect of removing distrust and confrontation between the North
and the South,'' said KCNA, Pyongyang's foreign news outlet. It
said North Korean papers printed news of the accord on their front
pages with photos of the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement provided for reunions this summer of families that
have been separated for 50 years by the closed and heavily
fortified border, a summit meeting in Seoul and the promotion of
South Korean investment that the North's failing economy
desperately needs.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea also agreed to repatriate an unspecified number of
convicted North Korean spies who have completed their jail terms.
</P>
<P>
   The accord did not deal with two major strategic concerns: the
North's demand that the United States withdraw its 37,000 troops
from South Korea, and the North's nuclear and long-range missile
programs that led Washington to label it a dangerous ''rogue''
state.
</P>
<P>
   Han Jai-bong, a political theory professor at Yonsei University
in the South Korean capital, warned that the military standoff on
the Korean peninsula will remain for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we're quite in the mood to think about this
rationally,'' Han said. ''Korean intellectuals are being very quiet
and don't want to rain on the parade.''
</P>
<P>
   The United State wants to develop a missile defense system to
deal with the threat from countries like North Korea, a proposal
Russia has warned could lead to a new nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's deliberations on whether to deploy
a national missile defense will not be influenced by rapprochement
on the Korean peninsula, the State Department said. Washington
considers other states such as Iraq and Iran, as well as
terrorists, to be threats that justify such a system.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting Wednesday, North Korea's ceremonial head of state,
Kim Yong Nam, questioned the South Korean president about another
source of conflict: the South's National Security Law, which
outlaws pro-communist activities. Kim Dae-jung said the South
Korean parliament was considering changes to the law, which human
rights activists say has been used to harass government opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Reunification itself is an enormous task that some observers say
could take decades. Impoverished North Korea, which has long feared
the rich South might try to absorb it in any unification scheme,
has advocated a confederacy of the two states.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul's ambassador in Washington, Lee Hong-koo, said South Korea
has advocated a similar alliance of ''two systems under one roof''
as a step toward reunification. However, the totalitarian North and
the democratic South would have to reconcile their opposing
political systems.
</P>
<P>
   The summit agreement is more detailed than similar ones reached
by lower-ranking officials in 1972 and 1991. Those deals, which
also called for reconciliation and reunification, quickly gave way
to renewed hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   South Koreans were surprised by the warmth and spontaneity
displayed by Kim Jong Il, who rules by decree and who has been
widely condemned for human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Some South Koreans focused on the great costs they are likely to
incur if they end up providing large amounts of economic aid to the
North. The financial burden on West Germany when it unified with
East Germany a decade ago is often scrutinized in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess the issue is now how much tax money we should pay. But
it's OK. It's worth it,'' said 44-year-old storeowner Kwon
Seung-ryong. ''Both Kims deserve a Nobel peace prize.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 0211 </TRAILER>
