<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United, US Airways Merger Mulled  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Days of Capitol Hill hearings on the proposed
marriage of United Airlines and US Airways have yielded few
defenders of the largest airline merger ever.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan skeptism from politicians, as well as outside
analysts, consumer groups, local officials and other airlines,
leaves the chiefs of the two airlines in a lonely spot arguing
their deal would be good for travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ''If US Airways is swallowed by United, I worry that
constituents will face few choices, wretched service and a pricing
structure that would make a mafia Don blush,'' Rep. Louis
Slaughter, D-N.Y., told the House Judiciary Committee on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, also speaking at the Senate Judiciary Committee's
antitrust panel Wednesday, worried aloud that the merger would mean
rising airfares, lost airline employee jobs and suffering
communities. The possibility that the deal would spark others in
the industry only worsened those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Already, since the $4.3 billion deal was announced last month,
there have been news reports of merger talks between Northwest
Airlines and American Airlines. Industry analysts have also
suggested that Delta would fit well with Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses complained to the House panel that increasing
concentration of airline hubs has already driven up costs for
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The National Business Travel Association surveyed corporate
travel managers last week and found that 82 percent believe
industry consolidation would lead to even higher fares, less choice
and poorer service.
</P>
<P>
   ''The prospect of further concentrating market share in the
hands of a small but elite group of corporate giants represents the
worst possible scenario for commercial avation and for the American
consumer,'' said Mike Gordon, the mayor of El Segundo, Calif.,
which borders Los Angeles International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The deal faces for more scrutiny Thursday at the House
Transportation Committee's second hearing this week on the subject.
Still more are to follow next week.
</P>
<P>
   Congress does not have authority to approve or reject the
proposed merger, but the issues raised by lawmakers likely will be
considered by the Justice and Transportation departments, which
will rule on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on what I've heard so far, the competitive implications
of this merger are troubling and I believe it deserves rigorous
scrutiny, '' said House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Wednesday, Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, the chairman of
the Senate antitrust subcommittee, and Sen. Herb Kohl of Wisconsin,
the subcommittee's senior Democrat, urged Joel Klein, head of the
Justice Department's antitrust division, ''to examine this deal
with appropriate care and scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before the Senate committee, the two airlines' chief
executives -- along with Robert Johnson, the Black Entertainment
Television head who wants to launch a new Washington-based airline
as part of the deal -- promised it won't stifle competition.
</P>
<P>
   James Goodwin, the chairman and chief executive of Elk Grove
Village, Ill.-based UAL Corp., United's parent, said the deal would
create ''the first truly efficient nationwide network that will
provide consumers with unparalleled travel convenience and
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also raised questions about the proposed launch of DC
Air, Johnson's planned airline. It would rely on United and US
Airways for some of its equipment and employees and would lease
jets -- an expense which critics say could make it tough for DC Air
to be a low-cost airline.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson assured the Senate panel his airline would provide
''safe, reliable, high-quality service at competitive prices'' and
would be ''a viable and totally independent competitor from day
one.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.united.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.usair.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 0429 </TRAILER>
