<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 04:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Battles Over Land Programs  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans are pushing a $14.6 billion
measure that finances federal land and cultural programs toward
House approval -- and a potential election-year veto battle with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders were hoping to complete the fiscal 2001
legislation on Thursday as part of their rush to finish Congress'
13 annual spending bills early to give lawmakers more time for
their re-election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But though the measure would boost spending over this year's
levels for national parks operations and national wildlife refuges,
it slices some Clinton intiatives.
</P>
<P>
   That includes giving Clinton just $186 million of the $620
million he wants for his ''lands legacy'' program for acquiring
federal, state and local land for parks. The bill would also forbid
the government from managing any of the eight national monuments he
has designated this year, which comprise more than 1 million acres
in five Western states, and cut his requests for clean water and
energy efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   It would also give the National Endowment for the Arts $98
million in 2001, about the same as this year but $52 million less
than Clinton wants.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill fails to address the critical needs of the American
people,'' White House officials wrote to congressional leaders
recently in a policy statement that threatened a Clinton veto.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, a subcommittee of the House Appropriations
Committee planned to vote on a roughly $13.3 billion foreign aid
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Subcommittee Chairman Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., has already said
he will propose abandoning the usual process of giving Israel its
$2.8 billion in aid in the first month of the new fiscal year,
which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The delay is aimed at protesting Israel's planned sale of the
PHALCON early warning radar system to China, a system that costs
$250 million.
</P>
<P>
   As lawmakers debated the Interior bill on Wednesday, they voted
214-211 to cut $126.5 million, or about half the budget, from a
program that provides federal subsidies for auto makers and others
who perform research on more efficient car engines.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was a defeat for Clinton, who started the program early
in his administration, and for Vice President Al Gore, a strong
supporter of the initiative and the likely Democratic presidential
nominee. Two-thirds of Republicans and more than one-third of
Democrats voted to cut the program.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton administration, the auto industry and Michigan
lawmakers lobbied to defend the program, they were opposed by a
coalition of fiscal conservatives and environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the program said it would improve the country's
energy efficiency, strengthen its economy, help consumers and lead
to a cleaner environment.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's ironic that so many House members who complain about high
gasoline prices have cut the heart out of a program designed to
save American motorists millions of dollars in energy costs in the
future,'' said White House spokesman Jim Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents called it corporate welfare for the auto companies,
and said it focused too much on finding cleaner diesel engines,
which they said would still be dirty. Opponents ranged from
consumer advocate Ralph Nader to the pro-environment Sierra Club to
the conservative Citizens Against Government Waste.
</P>
<P>
   ''There shouldn't be corporate welfare subsidies to an industry
that's very profitable,'' said Rep. John Sununu, R-N.H., who
sponsored the amendment with Rep. Robert Andrews, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the House by 217-214 approved the $339.5 billion
measure financing the Departments of Labor, Education, and Health
and Human Services. That bill, the biggest and most controversial
of the spending measures, faces a Clinton veto threat because it
would provide less than he wants for some education and other
social programs.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee also used a voice vote to
approve a $35.5 billion measure for the Commerce, Justice and State
departments.
</P>
<P>
   It, too, faces a veto threat because it ignores Clinton's
request for $150 million to hire 1,000 local prosecutors to handle
gun-related crimes. The measure also cuts his proposals for legal
aid for the poor and for U.S. contributions for U.N. peacekeeping
missions, and would limit the money available to the Justice
Department to pursue the federal lawsuit against the tobacco
industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 0449 </TRAILER>
