<DOCNO> APW20000615.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 04:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Los Alamos Probe Said Sensitive  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With nuclear scientists at the Los Alamos
weapons lab in New Mexico taking polygraph tests, the investigation
into the loss of computer files containing nuclear weapons secrets
is ''at a very sensitive stage,'' an Energy Department official
says.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers who were briefed on the security lapse Wednesday said
the investigation became more difficult because senior officials
were not told for three weeks of the loss of two computer hard
drives that held the materials. Further, there was no system in
place requiring tracking of the missing devices when they were
being used.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have the answers we need on this issue,'' President
Clinton remarked to reporters when asked by the latest security
controversy hitting the Energy Department. ''It's a serious matter,
and I don't think any of us need to be characterizing anything
until we know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Energy Department security and counterespionage experts
told separate House and Senate hearings that 26 people -- members of
a nuclear emergency response team at Los Alamos -- had access to the
highly secure vault in which the two computer hard drives were
kept.
</P>
<P>
   But no system was in place that required individuals to sign out
the devices, or even to track the use of the missing hard drives
which were part of a ''kit'' to be used to dismantle a nuclear
warhead in an emergency or terrorist act, lawmakers were told.
</P>
<P>
   ''That sounds like a real bonehead security procedure to me,''
Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., said during a Senate hearing at which
senior DOE security officials and the director of the Los Alamos
lab testified.
</P>
<P>
   John Browne, the lab director, said the missing computer drives
were classified as ''secret'' -- not top secret -- and therefore were
not required under an easing of security standards in the early
1990s to be signed out when used or tracked. He said lab officials
at the time opposed the change.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have declined publicly to go into details as to what
the drives contained or how their loss might affect national
security. Officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, have said
the disks had an array of technical data used to help dismantle
U.S. and other countries' nuclear warheads should the need arise in
an accident or terrorist act.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA is conducting a ''damage assessment'' in the event the
two hard drives, which contain identical information, are not
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our focus is to find out what happened to these disks,'' said
Edward Curran, the Energy Department's counterintelligence
director. ''If it had been reported sooner, we'd be an a lot better
position.'' Curren said the investigation was now at ''a very
sensitive stage.'' He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, which has assumed control of what is now a criminal
investigation, began polygraph tests of some Los Alamos scientists
on Wednesday. The focus has been on the 26 members of an emergency
nuclear response team, known as the NEST team.
</P>
<P>
   Browne said a member of the team told investigators he recalled
seeing the two drives in the vault on April 7 and another team
member said he examined the containers on April 27 and would
remember if the drives had been missing.
</P>
<P>
   On May 7, team members again went into the vault because they
wanted to safeguard the emergency response kits from possibly being
destroyed by a wildfire that was threatening to engulf the lab.
They found the two drives missing from one of the kits, but did not
report the finding to superiors.
</P>
<P>
   The next day the laboratory was evacuated. NEST team members
began searching for the drives on May 24 when normal operations
resumed at the lab, but still told no one, said Browne, who added
he did not become aware of any problems until May 31. He notified
the Energy Department the next day.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony Wednesday, Browne disclosed that ''several'' of
the six Los Alamos managers, who were suspended with pay pending
further investigations, had in fact known of the vanishing hard
drives as early as May 7. None of the senior officials in the chain
of command were aware of the security breach, however, said Browne.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who is facing sharp criticism
from congressional Republicans -- and some Democrats -- for the
latest security flap, said he was angry about what appears to be
clear violations of security and at the failure to report the
incident promptly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want accountability. There is going to be disciplinary
action,'' Richardson told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Armed Services Committee
http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)armed--services/
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos National Laboratory http://www.lanl.gov/external
</P>
