<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AMA To Vote on Reproductive Measure  </HEADLINE>
By LINDSEY TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A resolution that asks the American Medical
Association to support action ensuring certain reproductive
services when religious hospitals merge with or acquire other
hospitals has been amended amid opposition from the Catholic
church.
</P>
<P>
   The original measure wanted the AMA to support efforts to force
Catholic hospitals to provide reproductive services such as
sterilization.
</P>
<P>
   The softened version asks the nation's largest doctors group to
''support action to ensure continued patient access to pregnancy
prevention services'' including tubal ligation and vasectomy at
such hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The new measure was drafted at the AMA's annual meeting this
week. Dr. Delmar Tonge, a gynecologist and chairman of the AMA's
California delegation, said he would submit it Thursday when the
AMA's policy-making House of Delegates scheduled a vote on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want to force anybody to do anything,'' Tonge said.
However, he said patients ''should not be denied care or access to
care just because of an acquisition.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution said the AMA should support existing law
requiring health plans to provide access to reproductive services
when they are a covered benefit. But it also said the AMA should
affirm its policy that doctors should not be required to perform
any act that violates their moral principles.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders said the original resolution would have changed
that policy, forcing doctors at certain hospitals to perform
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The California delegation amended the measure after strong
criticism earlier this week from Cardinal Francis George, head of
the Chicago archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   The issue arose because Catholic health care networks are
aggressively acquiring non-Catholic hospitals in California and
elsewhere. In some rural areas that means a Catholic hospital
becomes the only choice for health care.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wednesday at the convention, the group:
</P>
<P>
   --Agreed to urge the government to step up regulation of
anti-bacterial soaps, lotions and other household products.
</P>
<P>
   --Rejected a resolution seeking a moratorium on gene patenting,
referring it to the AMA board of trustees for review.
</P>
<P>
   --Agreed to support the prescription of syringes for addicted
patients, in conjunction with addiction counseling, to help prevent
the transmission of blood-borne diseases such as AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   --Agreed to notify the Consumer Product Safety Commission about
the potential risk of eye injury from bungee cords. Doctors
testified about patients being blinded when the cords unexpectedly
recoiled.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   American Medical Association: http://www.ama-assn.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 0642 </TRAILER>
