<HEADLINE> Handel Society Names New Director  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Starting next season, a Welsh conductor known for
performing modern music will hold aloft the baton of the storied
Handel &AMP; Haydn Society.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston-based society Wednesday named 39-year-old Grant
Llewellyn as artistic director. The society, known casually to
admirers as the H &AMP; H Society, bills itself as the oldest
continuously performing musical society in America.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's more and more like a homecoming. Boston appears to be
part of my destiny,'' said Llewellyn, who was the assistant
director of the Boston Symphony Orchestra from 1990 to 1993. ''I've
probably been wined and dined by every member of the board at least
twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Llewellyn, a cellist and pianist, most recently has been the
conductor-in-residence of the BBC National Orchestra of Wales. He
will replace conductor Christopher Hogwood, 58, on July 1, 2001,
when Hogwood leaves the society after almost 15 years at the
podium.
</P>
</TEXT>
