<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many Senators Ride Tech Stock Wave  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The wealth of senators is riding the tech
stock roller coaster, invested in more traditional stocks, bonds
and real estate, or tucked away in safe and simple bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   At least one senator, Jeff Bingaman, holds margin trading
accounts. Some have a second career, including songwriter Orrin
Hatch and authors Joseph Lieberman and John McCain, their financial
reports covering 1999 show.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John D. Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va., listed three blind trusts
together worth a minimum of $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   The annual financial reports are designed to disclose the types
of investments and liabilities lawmakers have, not their net worth,
so holdings are only reported within broad ranges. The largest
category, inhabited by one of Rockefeller's trusts, is $50 million
and up.
</P>
<P>
   Another wealthy senator, Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill., owns Bank of
Montreal stock inherited from his father. It was valued at between
$25 million and $50 million, although the senator sold shares worth
$250,000 to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the major asset of Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., was a
$50,000-$100,000 account in the Senate credit union that earned
between $2,500 and $5,000 in interest last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden Jr., D-Del., lists only a Senate credit union
account worth less than $1,000 and debts including $15,000-$50,000
to Mastercard and a loan in the same range from the Senate credit
union.
</P>
<P>
   One senator, Christopher Bond, R-Mo., may have less money than
his son. Bond reported retirement accounts worth between $252,000
and $655,000. His son, Sam, a Princeton University student, had an
investment portfolio with assets worth between $388,000 and
$920,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, whose family money came from brick making, sued his
investment manager and PaineWebber in 1993, alleging his $1.3
million trust fund had been drained. Bond settled with PaineWebber
in 1996 for $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Bond's investments, including a trust from his grandparents'
will, were unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the investors favoring computer, Internet, and
telecommunications stocks was Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.,
chairman of the Senate Democratic campaign organization. He owned
stock in Amazon.com, CompUSA, Global Crossing Ltd., and Egghead.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli was an active trader who bought and sold stocks the
same day.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Majority Leader Don Nickles, R-Okla., reported owning
shares of America Online, Cisco, Compaq, Dell and Oracle last year.
He sold shares of chip maker Intel as well as Microsoft, which a
federal judge recently ordered split into two companies.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, his Democratic counterpart, Assistant Minority
Leader Harry Reid of Nevada, concentrated on real estate. He has a
property investment partnership with holdings throughout the
Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   His major assets include an office building in Las Vegas, worth
$500,000-$1 million; 100 acres of land in Bullhead City, Ariz., in
the same range; and mining claims worth $200,000-$400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., owned several tech
stocks in an individual retirement account valued at $28,025:
America Online, Intel, Lucent Technologies and Microsoft. He also
holds a brokerage account worth between $3,000 and $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has a half interest in a rental real estate partnership
that owns property in Hattiesburg, Miss., worth $50,000-$100,000,
and also owns a 161-acre lot in Carroll County, Miss., in the same
asset range.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota listed ownership
in 22 investment funds and bank accounts worth between $197,000 and
$730,000. Daschle owned six apartments, but sold three of them last
year -- two in Arlington, Va., and one in Sioux Falls, S.D. --
bringing in between $45,000 and $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bingaman, D-N.M., appears willing to take some investment
risks; he has two margin accounts worth between $250,000 and
$500,000 each, allowing trades on borrowed funds.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, R-Utah, writes inspirational songs for performers such as
Gladys Knight. The Senate Judiciary Committee chairman earned
$6,125 in ''composing income'' for Prime Recordings Inc. of Provo,
Utah, and royalties including $500 from MTV.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, R-Ariz., received $144,579 in royalties for his book
''Faith of My Fathers'' and donated the amount to charity. He also
signed an agreement with USA Films for rights to the book.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, D-Conn., earned a $45,000 advance from publisher
Simon &AMP; Schuster for his book, ''In Praise of Public Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's wife, Hadassah, owns stock in CBS and Fox
Entertainment Group. Both networks have been recipients of
Lieberman's ''Silver Sewer'' awards, aimed at embarrassing networks
that show sexually explicit or violent programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., received $12,499 for regular
appearances on the ''Face Off'' radio program and donated the
payments to charity. He is the beneficiary of trusts worth more
than $2 million, plus four trusts of unreported value.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chris Dodd, D-Conn., married last year and reported several
wedding gifts, a sculpture of a torso among them. Its value was not
listed.
</P>
</TEXT>
