<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 54; Nasdaq Climbs 14  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher Thursday despite two
government reports showing some surprising strength in the U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the start of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 54.54 at 10,742.49.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 1.90 at 1,472.44, and the Nasdaq composite index was
up 14.07 at 3,811.48.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department reported that 296,000 Americans filed for
unemployment benefits for the week ended June 10, down by 16,000
from the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   Economists consider claims below 300,000 an indication of a
tight labor market, suggesting that businesses continue to scramble
for workers.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Federal Reserve said production at the nation's
factories, mines and utilities posted a surprising increase in May.
Output rose 0.4 percent, while analysts were forecasting a 0.3
percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies Inc. was up $3.563 at $60.188 in early
trading on reports it is considering plans to spin off its
microelectronics unit in a deal analysts say could be valued at
more than $50 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
