<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Midwest Wants New Gas Rules Delayed  </HEADLINE>
By MARIO FOX
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- With gasoline selling for more than $2 a gallon
in their states, the governors of Illinois and Wisconsin have asked
the Environmental Protection Agency to suspend new fuel regulations
they blame for soaring prices.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois Gov. George Ryan said the higher prices coincided with
the June 1 deadline the EPA set for oil companies to begin
producing cleaner-burning reformulated fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ''The current craziness doesn't make any sense,'' the Republican
governor told reporters Wednesday. ''Something just isn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, prices have risen nationwide, but they have
skyrocketed in the Midwest, particularly in Chicago and Milwaukee.
The average cost of regular gasoline on Wednesday was $2.11 a
gallon in Chicago, $2 in Milwaukee and $1.60 nationwide, according
to the American Automobile Association.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson demanded that the EPA
waive the reformulated gas requirement, telling a crowd: ''We
should fight like hell.''
</P>
<P>
   EPA spokesman Dave Ryan said Wednesday the agency was reviewing
the request. ''We are keeping all of our options open,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The price increases exceed the extra 5 to 8 cents a gallon it
costs to make the new gasoline, according to Robert Perciasepe, the
federal EPA's assistant administrator for air and pollution
programs. Federal officials met this week with refiners, asking
them to explain the price increases.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission agreed Wednesday to investigate
whether price-fixing or collusion was driving up prices.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA said Milwaukee, Chicago and 15 other metropolitan areas
have some of the nation's worst air pollution. The agency has
mandated the cleaner, but more costly reformulated fuel since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the EPA ordered retailers to start selling a new
brand of reformulated gas -- designed to further preserve air
quality -- by June 1, though most service stations began offering
the fuel in May.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline price increases have hit the Midwest harder because of
unexpected refinery shutdowns in the region and delays in supplies
from European refiners. In addition, Midwest refineries have been
using corn-based ethanol in the reformulated gas. Ethanol -- popular
in the farm belt -- is more expensive to process than other
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said he agrees with the goal of the federal program to
clean the air, but the EPA implemented the new rules too quickly
and without regard for consumer impact.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has written five letters -- without response --
requesting an EPA rollback on its rules, although not all the way
back to the dirtier fuels of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan also joined others in requesting the possible tapping of
the nation's strategic oil reserves and to call on foreign oil
countries to increase production. In addition, he said he has asked
state Attorney General Jim Ryan to look into the oil companies'
pricing policies for antitrust violations or consumer fraud.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Energy Information Administration -- http://www.eia.doe.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
