<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Today  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) -- Nearly every day for 30 years, John
Greco would close his law practice in the mid-afternoon and make
his way up a rocky hill overlooking the city.
</P>
<P>
   A diminutive man who once considered himself too frail for the
priesthood, Greco would cart concrete, scrap metal, discarded
church statues and department store mannequins to his plot of land.
</P>
<P>
   At an age when his peers were retiring, Greco began his life's
work: a miniature representation of Jerusalem and walk-through
catechism he called Holy Land USA. Busloads of church groups -- an
estimated 40,000 people annually -- visited Holy Land after it
opened in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   But when Greco died in 1986 at the age of 90, no one knew how to
tend his labor of love. The 17-acre site, willed to an order of
nuns, has been battered by weather, vandals and neglect and is
slowly being destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Its loss is mourned by admirers of American folk art, who
consider it a treasure, and by others inspired spiritually by
Greco's creation.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a service to the people,'' said the Rev. Stanley
Smolenski, who once celebrated Mass in makeshift chapels at Holy
Land. ''I don't think it should just be relegated to the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The most enduring piece of Holy Land remaining is a 50-foot
cross still lights the night over this city of 106,000, a
struggling industrial center once known for the number of priests
it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, Holy Land contained 150 buildings. A cave-like
grotto, 8 feet high by 18 feet wide and housing a Nativity scene,
was the centerpiece. On the hill rising behind it were crammed
dozens of structures representing Bethlehem and Jerusalem. Beyond
that stood a rudimentary Egypt, complete with tiny pyramids and a
sphinx.
</P>
<P>
   A Roman Catholic Stations of the Cross wound through the site,
ending with a life-size hilltop representation of Jesus'
crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could be standing up to your knees in Jerusalem and the
buildings out in Waterbury looked like toy houses,'' said Sandy
Maineri, who as a child watched Holy Land develop.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibits were far from orthodox. In the 200-foot-long
catacombs, stories of martyrs were told using headless mannequins
laid in makeshift tombs. The inn in Bethlehem where Mary and Joseph
were turned away in the story of Jesus' birth had a No Vacancy sign
in motel-style lettering.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden of Eden was a trailer with its side removed; wigged
mannequins represented Adam and Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Mingled with the materials rescued from the trash were
factory-made church statues, including the contents of the Vatican
booth at the 1964 World's Fair. The pieces considered most valuable
were protected from vandals with chicken wire.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything John Greco did at Holy Land was the opposite of
what is recommended for liturgical art,'' said Marek Czarnecki, an
iconographer who admires the site. ''But he did it with divine
inspiration. He just wanted to bring the experience of Holy Land to
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   As Greco's health faded, so did Holy Land's. Plywood and
plaster, the main ingredients of many displays, became warped with
exposure. The Grotto and other structures became shelter for the
homeless as the neighborhood grew poorer.
</P>
<P>
   The site was closed for renovations in 1984 and never reopened.
</P>
<P>
   A few years before his death, Greco turned over the property to
the Religious Teachers Filippini. The nuns, who cared for Greco in
his small shingled home outside Holy Land's gates, have often been
blamed for its demise.
</P>
<P>
   ''They did nothing to protect it and didn't have the vision to
have a plan,'' said Salvatore Scalora, a University of Connecticut
art professor whose classes in the early 1980s often received
guided tours from Greco.
</P>
<P>
   Others say it is unfair to criticize the nuns, whose priorities
are caring for their aging sisters and the poor. They have restored
the Holy Land chapel, where Masses are sometimes held, but don't
have the resources for an all-out restoration, said Czarnecki.
</P>
<P>
   The nuns have mainly shunned outside input and decline to
comment on the charges of neglecting the site. Sister Christine
Spirito, the leader of the order, said the site would reopen later
this year as a ''center for spirituality.'' She would not give
details.
</P>
<P>
   For a few years, a loosely organized group tried to save Holy
Land. A $100-a-plate gala raised funds, and a million-dollar
restoration plan was proposed. It went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''Response from officials was, 'Yeah, this is great,' but no one
ever took hold of it and moved forward,'' said Frank Davino, a
retired city planner who still pushes for the revitalization of
Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   Today Holy Land stands eerily deserted. Some displays, including
the catacombs, have been dismantled for safety. The gates are
chained shut. A sign still proclaims ''Welcome to Holy Land.''
</P>
<P>
   The site enters the news now and then. In 1993 an independent
candidate for mayor included in his platform a vow to restore the
site. The region's tourism center still gets several calls a month.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit, Czarnecki said sadly, ''This was John Greco's
personal project and no one knew what to do with it when he was
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   A description of Holy Land --
http://www.roadsideamerica.com/holy/
</P>
<P>
   Information on the American Museum of Folk Art --
http://www.folkartmuse.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
