<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 3; Nasdaq Sheds 17  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were narrowly mixed Thursday as
investors, unsettled by the latest economic figures, grew uneasy
about the effect that slower growth would have on corporate
profits.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 3.18 at 10,691.13.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators fell. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was down 1.99 at 1,468.55, and the Nasdaq composite index was off
17.36 at 3,780.05.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks seesawed through most of the morning as investors tried
to digest new data on unemployment benefits claims and industrial
production.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve said production at the nation's factories,
mines and utilities rose a bigger-than-expected 0.4 percent in May.
Analysts were forecasting a 0.3 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   But operating capacity stood at 82.1 percent in May, the same
rate as in April. That rate was below levels usually associated
with a pickup in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In another report, the Labor Department said 296,000 Americans
filed for unemployment benefits for the week ended June 10, down by
16,000 from the previous week. Economists consider claims below
300,000 an indication of a tight labor market, suggesting that
businesses continue to scramble for workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times since
last June to slow the economy and keep inflation under control. In
recent weeks, there has been a spate of data -- including home
sales, retail sales, factory orders and unemployment -- showing a
moderation in economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   While most economists believe the central bank will leave rates
unchanged when it meets later this month, they continue to seek out
signs hinting at the direction of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   While Wall Street has been hoping for a cooling off of the
economy, market watchers warn that a slowdown will likely have an
effect on corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   That has added some pressure to stock prices in recent days,
with investors trying to figure out the best way to play the market
now. Technology stocks have been particularly hard hit as people
move their money into more stable industrial names.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm was down $8.688 at $61.813 after Chase H&AMP;Q cut its
earnings and revenue estimates for the fourth quarter and next
year. That came just one day after Bear Stearns &AMP; Co. reduced its
expectations for the maker of cell-phone chips and wireless
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors' concerns about the Fed raising interest rates is
being replaced by concerns that maybe the Fed overdid it and now
corporate earnings will not be as positive as most people had
hoped,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, director of market analysis at
A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies was the most active stock on the New York
Stock Exchange, rising $3.563 at $60.188 on reports it is
considering plans to spin off its microelectronics unit in a deal
analysts say could be valued at more than $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Coca Cola gained $1.813 to $54.813 after the company said it
reached a tentative deal to settle a race-discrimination lawsuit
from current and former employees. In addition, Salomon Smith
Barney upgraded its shares because efforts to localize the
soft-drink giant's business are beginning to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 439.24 million
shares, up from 425.96 million shares on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 4.44 at 505.23.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
