<HEADLINE> Finance Reports of House Leaders  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., speaker of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Earned income: $175,400.
</P>
<P>
   Honoraria, all donated to charity: None.
</P>
<P>
   Major assets: A 270-acre farm in Shipman, Ill., worth $100,000
to $250,000. Townhouse in Washington, D.C., worth
$100,000-$250,000. Opera House building in Illinois worth
$100,000-$250,000. Inherited half interest in North Aurora, Ill.,
property worth $50,000-$100,000. Inherited Bank One stock worth
$15,000-$50,000. Two mutual funds, one his wife's, each worth
$1,000-$15,000. Three bank accounts, each worth $1,000-$15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Major sources of unearned income: $27,625 in pension from the
state of Illinois for serving in the General Assembly. Rental
income from farm and Opera House, $15,000-$50,000 each.
$2,500-$5,000 in rent income from Washington house.
</P>
<P>
   Major liabilities: Mortgage on farm, mortgage on Opera House
property, mortgage on Washington townhouse, and co-signed loan with
a relative, each $50,000-$100,000. Co-signed loan with a relative
for home repair, $10,000- $15,000. Another co-signed loan with
relative, $15,000-$50,000. Co-signed restaurant loan with a
relative, $100,000-$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts: None.
</P>
<P>
   Narrative: In 1999, Hastert's salary rose because of his new
position as speaker. He inherited the Bank One stock and the half
interest in the North Aurora property, which he sold on an
installment sale contract. The speaker also purchased the Opera
House property last year, and listed a 75 percent partnership in
that holding. Hastert reported no privately funded travel for 1999.
His wife earns a salary as a teacher.
