<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Leftists Are Divided  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Carlos Martinez Renteria, a self-described
leftist, publishes a counterculture magazine that celebrates sex,
drugs and rock 'n' roll. He's also supporting a conservative
candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   The candidacy of Vicente Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive with
perhaps the best chance ever to end the 71-year reign of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, has put many Mexican leftists in
a dilemma: Any vote that does not go to Fox may help keep the PRI
in power.
</P>
<P>
   ''Supporting Fox is the riskiest, most vanguard, perhaps the
most leftist position one can take at this moment,'' Martinez said
at the office of his magazine, Generacion.
</P>
<P>
   Only three years ago, Martinez wrote newspaper columns
criticizing Fox's National Action Party for its prim line on risque
art.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is one of dozens of leftist intellectuals and
activists who have won Fox's promise to support at least some of
their positions and who have published a declaration supporting
him: ''Not One Vote for the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   That infuriates some supporters of Cuauhtemoc Cardenas and his
Democratic Revolution Party, which was created in 1989 out of old
Marxist factions and breakaway leftists from the PRI, the acronym
of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the left has demonized the PRI for rigging elections,
stifling dissent at farms and factories and using violence to crush
leftist challenges -- as when soldiers gunned down hundreds of
pro-democracy student demonstrators in the 1968 Tlatelolco
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas' party accuses the PRI -- at least on local levels -- of
killing 600 of its activists over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some on the left now argue that Fox might be even worse.
They deeply distrust the pro-business outlook of his party, known
as the PAN.
</P>
<P>
   The PAN's ideology reminds many Mexican leftists of the
religious conservatives who struggled against secular government in
Mexico from independence in the 1820s until the bloody Cristero War
of the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Some PAN state governments tried to dictate skirt lengths in
public offices and to ban sexually explicit art. One PAN state
recently pressured a teen-ager who had been raped to give birth to
the resulting child.
</P>
<P>
   In a May 9 letter to the newspaper La Jornada, novelist Fernando
del Pasos argued that a vote for Fox ''is a vote in favor of the
fascism that churns in the belly of the PAN.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Never,'' he wrote, ''did we Mexicans think that we would
confront a terrible, unthinkable paradox: Expelling the PRI from
power could be the equivalent at this moment of handing over the
country to the most obscene reactionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would vote for the hated PRI to keep National Action
from power.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anguish,'' was what novelist Guadalupe Loaeza called the
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I vote for Fox, I would betray myself. ... It would be like
tossing everything I have personally fought for into the garbage,''
she wrote in the newspaper Reforma this week.
</P>
<P>
   But to let the PRI win? ''Even thinking of that possibility
chokes my throat,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has tried to dispel such fears. Among his chief advisers are
two prominent leftists who once advised Cardenas: Jorge Castaneda
and Adolfo Aguilar Zinser.
</P>
<P>
   While Fox has displayed a banner of the Virgin of Guadalupe at
his rallies, he is generally seen as a pragmatist. He promises to
support secular education, shun censorship and avoid privatizing
the state oil company.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's quirky individualism also calms some.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fox is crazy. That saves him,'' said a grinning Martinez, who
wore a T-shirt depicting skid row novelist Charles Bukowski, jeans
and a beeper.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, polls show a left-right vote split: Fox has a
strong lead for president while a leftist ally of Cardenas leads
for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts argue that overall, Cardenas might take as many
votes from the PRI as he does from Fox. Roger Bartra of the
National Autonomous University noted that Cardenas and the PRI both
appeal to the same rural and working-class voters.
</P>
<P>
   But on an individual basis, the choice ''is arithmetic,'' said
Joel Ortega, a former Communist who organized the pro-Fox
declaration. ''A vote given to another candidate (other than Fox)
favors the official candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortega said that for generations, the PRI has meddled in ''all
aspects of daily life,'' noting that millions of Mexicans are
forced to belong to unions, business, farm or professional groups
formally linked to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most important task,'' he said, ''is to free ourselves
from that domination by the PRI.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 1437 </TRAILER>
