<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hostage Crisis Forces Fiji Cuts  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE CORDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Fiji's military rulers ordered civil servants
on Thursday to cut government spending to lessen the economic
impact of the 28-day hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji's economy has ground to a near standstill since armed
rebels led by failed businessman George Speight stormed parliament
on May 19 and took most of the Cabinet hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Speight has demanded more rights for the country's indigenous
Fijian majority and that ethnic Indians -- who led the now-deposed
government -- be stripped of power.
</P>
<P>
   The military declared martial law and seized executive power 10
days after Speight began the standoff, holding 31 officials
captive.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say Fiji stands to lose $100 million in government
revenue as a result of the crisis on the Pacific island nation,
2,250 miles northeast of Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Since the government's overthrow, ethnic Indian farmers have
halted the harvest of the nation's cash crop, sugar, and tourist
bookings also vital to Fiji's economy have plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   Another mainstay, garment making, has been hit by the refusal of
Australian labor unions to deal with Fijian imports or exports.
Clothes makers are running out of raw materials and have been cut
off from their main market, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The finance ministry, which is still functioning despite the
coup, will now draw up a mini budget covering spending from August
to December, military spokesman Lt. Col. Filipo Tarakinikini said.
</P>
<P>
   It will mandate government spending cuts of at least $91 million
and measures to ensure the budget deficit does not rise above 3.5
percent of gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Government spending will be concentrated on essential services
such as law and order, health, education and social welfare, as
well as supporting tourism and agriculture, Tarakinikini said.
</P>
<P>
   The finance ministry says that if spending is not slashed, the
budget deficit could balloon to 8 percent of GDP, or $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our economy cannot sustain this very high level of deficit,''
Tarakinikini said.
</P>
<P>
   The military says it wants to guide Fiji back to democracy, but
has warned it could take years before elections are held again.
</P>
<P>
   The military leader, Commander Frank Bainimarama, and Speight
are split over whether the rebels should be allowed in a new
civilian government. They also differ on the extent of an amnesty
to Speight's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, foreign ministers from Australia and New Zealand,
the two regional powers, as well as envoys from Malaysia and
Botswana arrived in the capital, Suva, seeking a way out of the
monthlong crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sooner the hostages are released and the sooner there is a
process put in place for the return to democratic government in
Fiji, the better,'' Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Downer and his New Zealand counterpart, Phil Goff, ruled out
meeting Speight, whom they have called a terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not our intention to legitimize Mr. Speight by talking
to him,'' Goff said.
</P>
<P>
   Downer said the delegation would not seek a direct role in
mediating the hostages' release, which ''has to be handled by the
Fijians themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the delegation would be ''urging Mr. Speight to
release the hostages.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the rebels briefly released one of their
hostages, former Foreign Minister Ului Kauvadra, for a medical
checkup. Kauvadra left parliament in a Red Cross ambulance and
returned about 30 minutes later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 1444 </TRAILER>
