<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discounts Boost Expo's Attendance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, Germany (AP) -- Cut-rate evening tickets have led to a
surge in visitors at the World's Fair in Hanover as organizers seek
to combat complaints about pricey bratwurst and other costs too
dear for the average pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the Expo 2000 said 101,000 people visited the
156-nation exhibit Wednesday, far more than the 60,000 daily
average since it opened June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 13,000 people snapped up discounted evening tickets for
$5, down from $12 during the day, fair spokesman Andreas
Lampersbach said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fair visitors have complained of admission prices ranging up to
$43 and budget-breaking food prices, such as a lowly bratwurst that
normally goes for $1.50 costing $4.50.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting dignitaries Thursday included the wife of Russian
President Vladimir Putin, Lyudmila Putina, accompanied by
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's wife, Doris Koepf-Schroeder, and
Christina Rau, German President Johannes Rau's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Also touring the fair were Prince Rainier of Monaco and two of
his grown children, Prince Albert and Princess Caroline, as well as
his son-in-law, Prince Ernst-August of Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is playing host to the fair for the first time, taking
up a tradition begun in 1851.
</P>
<P>
   Officials had once projected up to 150,000 visitors daily at the
$1.8 billion event. But critics say the five-month fair could lose
more than $500 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
