<HEADLINE> Stocks Gain; Dow Up 53; Nasdaq Up 38  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tech stocks came back to life on Wall Street
Thursday as shares of Lucent Technologies jumped on a report that
the company was considering spinning off its microelectronics unit.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 53.48 at 10,741.43.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also rose. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index rose 6.50 to 1,477.04, and the Nasdaq composite index was up
37.64 at 3,835.05.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent was the second-most actively traded stock on the New York
Stock Exchange, rising $4.188 at $60.813 on reports it is
considering plans to spin off its microelectronics unit in a deal
analysts say could be valued at more than $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard shares also rose, gaining $4.563 to $118.563
after the company announced plans to start an online commerce
venture in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks had been mixed earlier in the day as investors tried to
digest new data on unemployment benefits claims and industrial
production.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve said production at the nation's factories,
mines and utilities rose a bigger-than-expected 0.4 percent in May.
Analysts were forecasting a 0.3 percent drop. But operating
capacity stood at 82.1 percent in May, the same rate as in April.
That rate was below levels usually associated with a pickup in
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In another report, the Labor Department said 296,000 Americans
filed for unemployment benefits for the week ended June 10, down by
16,000 from the previous week. Economists consider claims below
300,000 an indication of a tight labor market, suggesting that
businesses continue to scramble for workers.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading, shares of Qualcomm fell $9.438 to $61.063
after Chase H&AMP;Q cut its earnings and revenue estimates for the
fourth quarter and next year. That came just one day after Bear
Stearns &AMP; Co. reduced its expectations for the maker of cell-phone
chips and wireless technology.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola gained $3.063 to $56.063 after the company said it
reached a tentative deal to settle a race-discrimination lawsuit
from current and former employees. In addition, Salomon Smith
Barney upgraded its shares because efforts to localize the
soft-drink giant's business are beginning to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues edged out advancing issues 10-to-9 on the NYSE,
where volume came to 771.77 million shares, up from 725.78 million
shares on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.79 at 508.88.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
