<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN's Lebanon-Israel Mission Halted  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH PANOSSIAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABBASSIYEH GATE, Lebanon (AP) -- Israeli soldiers fired warning
shots Thursday into the ground near the feet of a U.N. team heading
their way to inspect the newly drawn international border.
</P>
<P>
   There were no injuries. Israel apologized to the United Nations,
and said it was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting forced the suspension of the verification of the
Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon, as the Lebanese army
officials accompanying the U.N. team withdrew from the mission and
returned to Beirut. The U.N. officials were summoned to their base
in Naqoura.
</P>
<P>
   While underscoring the volatility of the frontier, the shooting
also was a reminder of the difficulties faced by U.N. officials in
demarcating the border, which they had hoped to complete within
days of the abrupt Israeli pullout May 24.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. peacekeepers will be deployed at the border after the
United Nations completes verification of the Israeli withdrawal.
Until then, anti-Israeli guerrillas, will remain the only real
authority on the Lebanese side of the border zone.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's incident also cast a pall on plans by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to visit Lebanon on Monday. U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard said the timing of Annan's trip was ''linked
to the final confirmation of Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard said the Israelis ''admitted it happened. They said it
was a stupid mistake and let's get on with the verification
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   He said four shots passed over the heads of the verification
team and one hit the ground in front of the deputy force commander.
But journalists who were with the team -- including an Associated
Press reporter -- said three bullets hit the ground about 10 feet
from the team.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting began after eight U.N. and four Lebanese officers
got out of U.N.-marked vehicles and walked about 150 yards toward a
barbed wire fence. The shots rang out as the officials unchained a
gate on the fence and were about to step through to go toward the
village of Abbassiyeh.
</P>
<P>
   The firing came from the remnants of a vacated post about 50
yards away on the U.N.-drawn border that the team wanted to
inspect. The U.N. spokesman in Lebanon, Timur Goksel, said the
fence was inside Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli army northern front commander Maj. Gen. Gabi Ashkenazi
apologized to the U.N. commander in Lebanon, Israeli officials
said. They quoted Ashkenazi as saying the soldiers opened fire
after they saw a group of civilians and journalists try to cut
through the fence.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. officers were wearing the trademark blue berets of
peacekeeping missions and U.N. vehicles were parked nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Israeli forces abandoned a position 1.2 miles
west of Abbassiyeh Gate and pulled back about 200 yards to inside
Ghajar. The village has been sliced in two by the U.N.-drawn
border. One part is in Lebanon and the other in the
Israeli-occupied Golan Heights, which was captured from Syria in
1967.
</P>
<P>
   Ghajar residents have been protesting the division of their
community.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have nothing against the Lebanese brethren,'' said Suleiman
Khatib, who identified himself as Ghajar mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we want is that the village does not get divided. Do not
separate fathers from sons and mothers from their children,'' he
said, speaking through a loudspeaker when the U.N. and Lebanese
team inspected the border in their village.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
