<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Coli Probed in 3 Canada Deaths  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- The Ontario coroner's office said Thursday that
three more deaths were being investigated for links to an E. coli
contamination that has killed at least seven people and sickened
hundreds more.
</P>
<P>
   The three deaths under investigation occurred between May 5 and
May 19, before authorities issued a warning and told residents of
Walkerton to boil their water. Some 14 deaths are now being
studied.
</P>
<P>
   The three additional victims were an 81-year-old woman who died
in Walkerton on May 5; a 27-year-old woman who died in Kitchener on
May 18; and a 93-year-old woman who died in Walkerton on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   On May 21, health officials issued a boil order for Walkerton
water, several days after the local utility knew that wells were
contaminated in the town, 90 miles west of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Six adults and a 2-year-old child previously were identified as
fatal victims of the E. coli contamination. All seven of the other
deaths under investigation were adults.
</P>
<P>
   The contamination was the worst known E. coli outbreak in North
America, and officials have yet to determine what caused it. Health
and environment officials are focusing on two wells that supplied
water to Walkerton, one of which had a malfunctioning chlorination
system before the E. coli outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   E. coli is an intestinal bacteria often spread through animal or
human feces that gets into water supplies. It causes nausea,
diarrhea, cramps and in severe cases, kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   Four separate investigations of the contamination have been
announced -- by Ontario Provincial Police, health and environment
officials, the Ontario coroner's office, and a public inquiry
expected to begin in upcoming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A boil order for town water was likely to continue for at least
six more weeks as all water pipes and supplies get flushed and
tested. The Ontario Clean Water Agency has taken over control of
the town's water system from the local utility.
</P>
<P>
   In Walkerton, residents depend on bottled water donated by other
communities, businesses and charities, and also either bleach or
boil the water to treat it. Some have left town, or visit friends
and relatives in other communities for a bath or shower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
