<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Invites Homeless to Lunch  </HEADLINE>
By ELLEN KNICKMEYER
<TEXT>
<P>
   VATICAN CITY (AP) -- The invitation came on crisp white paper,
with a picture of the host on the front: ''The Holy Father John
Paul II, on the occasion of the Grand Holy Year of 2000, invites
Mr. Antonio Buoniconti to share in a friendly gathering.''
</P>
<P>
   Buoniconti, receiving the invitation at a Rome soup kitchen,
since no mail delivery is possible at the doorway that is his fixed
address, gratefully accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Donning his best jeans and only windbreaker, the 39-year-old
Neapolitan joined 199 of Rome's homeless at the Vatican on Thursday
for lunch with the pope.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best thing is to see the pope close up,'' Buoniconti said,
milling with fidgeting fellow guests among the rose bouquets,
damask tablecloths and stainless-steel place settings while waiting
for their host.
</P>
<P>
   Extending his invitation via Rome's soup kitchens and homeless
shelters, John Paul sought and found guests from all the world's
continents, who had drifted to Rome in hopes of jobs, or just
drifted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Among all my Holy Year appointments, this for me is certainly
one of the most felt and most significant,'' the white-robed
pontiff told his guests.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to meet them, I wanted to share this meal with you,
to say that you are in the heart of the pope. I embrace each one of
you with great affection, my very dear friends,'' John Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine homeless people froze to death in what was an
unusually cruel winter for them in Rome, throwing the city's
services for them in sharp contrast with its lavish spending for
Holy Year preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Charities said some of the deaths came because Holy Year
reconstruction projects had thrown street people out of their usual
haunts. One woman froze to death a few hundred yards from St.
Peter's.
</P>
<P>
   The church, which has said it wants even the poor to be able to
make Holy Year pilgrimages here, as of this summer is providing 500
meals daily in soup kitchens at St. Peter's and three other Rome
basilicas.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's menu was a little fancier than what the soup kitchens
normally serve, paying all due Roman reverence to a good meal:
ravioli, roast veal with potatoes, salad, fruit salad with ice
cream, with wine and spumante, and coffee to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thanks again for your presence,'' John Paul said, adding
thanks also for an orchestra of performing priests playing
selections -- ''La Bamba,'' ''O Sole Mio'' and the African ''Jambo
Jambo'' meant to make both Italian and international guests feel at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Seminary students circulated among the tables, waiting on
families with squirming children, near-toothless men with grizzled
beards, women in their 70s and in their best dresses for the pope.
</P>
<P>
   Vatican officials ate alongside the guests. John Paul, flanked
by eight of the poor, started the meal by clasping the hands of a
frail, white-haired woman on his right, sipped espresso while some
guests danced, and stayed long enough afterward to pat children
carried up to his table by a line of beaming parents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
