<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Sens. Hold Up Plant's Coal Switch  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ZUCKERBROD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two senators from major coal-producing states
are holding up a plan to use cleaner fuel in a power plant that
heats and cools the U.S. Capitol. The coal-burning plant is among
the city's worst polluters.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., and Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., sent a
letter to Capitol architect Alan Hantman last month after Hantman's
office gave Congress a plan to upgrade the plant.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were troubled to learn that the proposed master plan would
require the elimination of coal as a fuel for the Capitol steam
plant and instead rely exclusively on fuel oil and natural gas,''
the senators said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers ended the letter by urging Hantman to ''carefully
evaluate several options to preserve coal as a primary fuel for the
Capitol power plant.''
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia and Kentucky are the second- and third-ranked coal
producing states, trailing only Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Hantman said the architect's office is reviewing
its plan for the plant, which heats and cools the Capitol, Library
of Congress, Union Station and congressional buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question, based on the issues raised by Byrd and
McConnell, we're re-examining it,'' Bruce Milhans said.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly century-old plant, a few blocks from the Capitol,
uses coal to heat the buildings in the winter. In the summer, it
uses a combination of natural gas and electricity to cool the
structures.
</P>
<P>
   The plant is one of the city's single biggest emitters of
nitrogen oxide, a component of smog, said Theodore Gordon, senior
deputy director for public health assurance in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The city and its suburbs consistently violate smog standards, so
Gordon would like it if the plant stopped burning coal, which
produces more pollution than natural gas or fuel oil.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter, McConnell and Byrd urged Hantman to ''consider
existing and emerging coal technologies that are currently
available, which would increase the efficiency and reduce the
environmental impact of the existing coal boilers.''
</P>
<P>
   They say it would save taxpayers' money because coal is cheaper
than natural gas or fuel oil. The country also has a larger reserve
of coal.
</P>
<P>
   Don Wambsgans, program manager of the city's air quality
division, agrees there are cleaner ways to burn coal. He said they
sometimes involve converting coal to a gas or mixing it with
limestone to produce less pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   Milhans said the architect's office was evaluating the cost of
those kinds of technologies.
</P>
<P>
   He said Hantman would report back to the House and Senate
appropriations committees with a new range of options by the fall.
McConnell and Byrd are on the Senate Appropriations Committee,
which approves government spending.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is up to Congress to ultimately decide what course they
want to take,'' Milhans said. ''The architect of the Capitol works
for Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell's spokesman, Robert Steurer, said it was too soon to
say whether the senators would try to block funds for the upgrades
if coal were not included in the plan. The estimated cost for the
original plan was $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
