<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Lashes Out at Barak  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Yasser Arafat lashed out at Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak on Thursday, saying the man he once described
as his peace partner ''lacks the desire to work with us in order to
achieve a comprehensive peace in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian leader denounced Barak in the White House
driveway after meeting for more than three hours with President
Clinton in a bid for help to achieve his goals. First among them: A
state with its capital in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations sputtered along here, partly broken off by the
Palestinians to protest Israel's refusal to release 250 prisoners
and to agree to Arafat's terms for an Israeli pullback this month
on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is prepared to declare statehood without Israel's
approval if a settlement is not concluded by the Sept. 13 deadline
the two sides have set.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and State Department voiced tepid support for
Barak, whose willingness to yield territory on all fronts to the
Arabs had been from them a pleasant contrast to the grudging line
taken by his predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we are satisfied that both leaders are very serious in
their efforts to reach an agreement,'' P.J. Crowley, spokesman for
the National Security Council, said.
</P>
<P>
   In a similarly low key statement when pressed by reporters,
State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said ''both remain
committed to achieving a peace agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meanwhile, kept his distance from the angry Palestinian
rhetoric. He responded to a few questions at a picture-taking
session in the Oval Office at the start of his meeting with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we are going to make peace we are going to have to deal
with the difficult issues,'' he said as he sat side-by-side with
Arafat. ''The less we say now about it, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, at a joint news conference with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright in Ramallah, a Palestinian town on the West
Bank, Arafat bristled when a reporter asked whether he still
considered Barak a partner for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Refusing to respond, Arafat said the question was designed to
disrupt the peacemaking process.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations resumed at two air force bases here Tuesday
after a two-week break and immediately drifted into disagreement.
American mediators Dennis B. Ross and Aaron D. Miller conferred
with the two delegations, and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
invited Arafat to lunch at her home in the Georgetown area of the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I should characterize what is going on,''
Clinton said of the slow-paced discussions. ''The only thing I can
tell you is I want to finish the job, and I'd like to see it
finished on time.''
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's meeting, Arafat praised Clinton for trying to
keep the peace negotiations alive ''at this difficult time and in
the face of the obstacles we're facing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton last year voiced his support for Palestinian
''aspirations'' on a trip to Gaza. But any suggestion he would prod
Israel or the Palestinians to make concessions was dismissed
Thursday by his spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not in the position to pressure them,'' Crowley said.
''They understand that time is not on their side. ... I don't think
we have any quarrel with the firmness by which the leaders and
their negotiating teams are working hard to see what can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   A settlement is Clinton's highest foreign policy priority in the
little more than seven months he has remaining in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton talked to Barak on the telephone for 40 minutes
Wednesday and said the two sides were not ready for a Camp
David-style three-way meeting with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we need to get the parties a little closer before we
can go there,'' Clinton said. ''We don't have a lot of time. We're
down to all the hard issues now, and we're working on it. I'm
hopeful, but I don't want to hold out false hopes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
