<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Resists U.S. Supervision  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The United States pressed Thursday for greater
U.S. supervision of Israeli weapons exports and sought to persuade
Israel to cancel the sale of a spy plane to China, but Israel was
unreceptive.
</P>
<P>
   The Haaretz daily said the United States has drawn up a list of
27 countries it considers problematic destinations for Israeli
weapons, including China and India, two major Israeli clients.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials reject the idea of U.S. monitoring, but
refused to comment directly Thursday, fearing diplomatic
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, most Israeli weapons systems included U.S.
components, and since the United States bans re-export of its
technology without its agreement, Washington had automatic
supervision over most deals.
</P>
<P>
   But Israel's weapons manufacturers now can build sophisticated
arms without using American technology, forcing the United States
to look for new ways to monitor Israel's exports.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is concerned that Israeli military high-tech
will end up in the wrong hands and endanger U.S. troops, said a
U.S. official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the U.S. State Department and the Pentagon raised
the issue Thursday with the director general of the Israeli Defense
Ministry, Amos Yaron.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, disagreement erupted over Israel's contract
to sell a plane equipped with the PHALCON early warning system to
China.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is building one now, and China has an option to buy at
least three more. The U.S. is trying to force cancellation of the
sale, pointing to renewed tensions between China and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have said the dispute is over business, not
security, and that the U.S. government is trying to shield its own
arms manufacturers from Israeli competition. Israel says the system
has no American components.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is an element of superpower bullying here,'' said Efraim
Inbar of Bar Ilan University's Begin-Sadat Center for Strategic
Studies. He said American supervision would lead to the
cancellation of some deals, and that this could destroy Israel's
arms industry and endanger Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of policy, Israel does not comment on arms exports
or release official sales figures. Inbar estimated that Israeli
arms manufacturers sell $2 billion worth of arms a year, 75 percent
to foreign countries and 25 percent to the Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh told Israel's parliament
Wednesday that Israel needs to keep exporting on a large scale to
finance the development of new weapons systems and stay a step
ahead of its enemies.
</P>
<P>
   An example of Israel's homegrown sophistication is the Merkava
tank, in use here since the 1980s, replacing U.S.-made models. For
the first time, the Merkava will be on display next week at
Eurosatory, a weapons exhibition in Paris. The Israelis are
showcasing its locally developed high-tech features, including
optical devices.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli arms have shown up all over the world, sometimes after
shady third-party deals, but also when Israel has acted as an agent
for the United States in touchy political circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Israel transferred TOW anti-tank missiles and
other weapons to Iran in a four-sided deal that involved the United
States and Nicaragua. The sales were part of a Washington scandal
that became known as Irangate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do their dirty work,'' said Inbar, referring to the United
States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 1612 </TRAILER>
