<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Chiefs of Staff Trade Advice  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former White House Chief of Staff James Baker
III says the job is the second toughest in Washington, right after
the presidency. Jack Watson Jr., who had the job under President
Carter, likens it to shortstop. And Leon Panetta, who served
President Clinton, says, ''You've got to be a battlefield
commander.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten former White House chiefs of staff who served the past five
presidents traded stories Thursday and offered tips to future
members of their club.
</P>
<P>
   Some advice:
</P>
<P>
   --Don't let the president's agenda drift off course.
</P>
<P>
   --Remember that everything on your desk might be subpoenaed.
</P>
<P>
   --Be tough enough to tell the president he is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   --Step softly on egos on Capitol Hill, but find opportune moments
to roll the opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't be too visible.
</P>
<P>
   --Stay grounded in reality.
</P>
<P>
   --Have a good nose because a lot smells fishy.
</P>
<P>
   --And don't hang up on the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shortly after the elections this November, somebody is going
to wake up and realize that in a very, very few weeks, he or she
will lead a team into the literal nerve center of the world. Today,
as we all know, White House mistakes reverberate loud and long,''
Baker, chief of staff for Presidents Reagan and Bush, told the
gathering at the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was the only person in history dumb enough to take it
twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs of staff handle crises and scandals, politics and policy.
They influence who sees the president and what he reads. He is
gatekeeper to the Oval Office. Nevertheless, Baker cautioned: ''The
chief of staff is very powerful, but he's not a king.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson said he often felt like a shortstop. ''You're cutting
short the balls to keep them from getting ... all the way to the
president,'' he said. ''You're making a lot of decisions that the
president never knows about.''
</P>
<P>
   In that role, it helps to have a good nose, says Kenneth
Duberstein, a chief of staff for Reagan, because a lot of things in
Washington ''smell a little fishy.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs of staff are also charged with smoothing relationships
with interest groups, political bigshots, Congress and news-hungry
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I probably did the lousiest job of dealing with the press that
any chief of staff has ever done,'' said former Bush chief of staff
John Sununu, who was forced out in 1991 amid controversy over his
acerbic style and personal travel at government expense. Sununu
said he favored on-the-record interviews in deference to a
president who loathed leaks, but now feels he should have spoken
privately to reporters more often to weave the president's message
into their stories.
</P>
<P>
   Panetta, hired to reorganize the Clinton White House in
mid-1994, said when he took the post, one staff member compared the
situation to a grammar school soccer game where players were out of
position -- all running after the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, the ball is always in the Oval Office,'' said Panetta,
whose response was to set up a clear chain of command, focus
Clinton's energies to prevent 10 competing messages from coming out
of the White House on the same day and control access to the chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who wanted to see Reagan had to get through the Howard
Baker blockade first.
</P>
<P>
   ''They weren't going in unless I was along so that we knew
exactly what had happened and the president would never be caught
in a cross fire,'' said Baker, who joined the Reagan White House to
reshape the president's image after the Iran-contra scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Erskine Bowles, one of Clinton's four chiefs of staff, said one
goal of being a president's chief of staff is surviving the White
House stint, which he says runs faster than the dot-com world. One
minute, it's health care. The next minute, it's Kosovo, Iraq,
welfare reform, the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''And, oh, on the side, you deal with a little thing called
impeachment,'' Bowles said. ''I found that the only way I could
manage in this 'gotcha' environment in Washington is not to allow
myself to float up with the highs because the lows came too quickly
thereafter and I wasn't able to keep the White House moving forward
on a steady course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 1614 </TRAILER>
