<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Intends To Remain in S. Korea  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- North and South Korea have broken the ice on
their decades-old cold war, but the Pentagon is not warming to the
idea that a unified Korea would neither need nor want U.S. troops
on its soil.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to be very clear that we intend to remain a force for
stability in that area as long as we are needed,'' Kenneth Bacon,
spokesman for Defense Secretary William Cohen, said Thursday. Bacon
said the South Korean government has made clear that it expects
U.S. troops to remain ''for a long time to come.''
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point, we don't envision any change in the U.S. troop
status,'' said P.J. Crowley, spokesman for the National Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it appears inevitable that if the North and South take
concrete steps toward reunification, including the conclusion of a
peace treaty, public pressure to bring some U.S. troops home from
Korea will grow.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what will happen almost overnight,'' said Robert
Riscassi, a retired Army general who was commander in chief of U.S.
forces in Korea from 1990-93. ''Clearly there will be a debate.
It's inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 37,000 American troops in South Korea, mainly
soldiers of the Eighth Army, headquartered at Yongsan Army Garrison
in Seoul, and airmen of the 7th Air Force, based at Osan Air base.
The United States has maintained a continuous military presence in
South Korea since the 1950-53 Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   In comments at the White House, President Clinton called the
summit ''an initial, hopeful step toward peace and reconciliation
in the Korean Peninsula. I welcome the agreements the two leaders
reached on humanitarian and economic cooperation and on a future
summit in Seoul, and hope that both sides will continue down this
promising path.''
</P>
<P>
   The suddenly brighter prospect of a Korean peace also has
sparked speculation that the Pentagon's push to build a national
defense against missile attack could be slowed. That's because the
potential attacker most prominently mentioned by the Pentagon is
North Korea; if the Koreas combined peacefully, the argument for
rushing to build a $60 billion missile defense system could be
seriously undermined.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the administration welcomes diplomatic progress
toward reducing the ballistic missile threat from North Korea, but
he added that a U.S. missile defense system would be useful against
other countries, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''North Korea is not the only country we worry about,'' Bacon
said. ''We worry about Iraq. We worry about Iran, and we worry
about other countries that are working on long-range missiles or
that already have chemical or biological weapons and would like to
have ways to deliver them with long-range missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon acknowledged, however, that the Pentagon's self-imposed
deadline for fielding a missile defense by 2005 is based mainly on
intelligence estimates that North Korea could have a missile
capable of reaching U.S. soil by that time. The CIA has said it
believes Iranian and Iraqi missile threats are farther in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it remains far from clear whether the agreement on
Wednesday by South Korean President Kim Dae-jung and North Korean
leader Kim Jong Il to work toward a peaceful reunification of the
divided peninsula will bear fruit. The two sides have been at each
other's throats for half a century.
</P>
<P>
   When the North invaded the South on June 25, 1950, the United
States came to the South's aid and led a United Nations force that
fought against North Korean, Chinese and Russian forces until an
armistice took effect July 27, 1953. No peace treaty was ever
signed.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton administration's view, if the threat of a North
Korean attack on the South disappeared there would still be reason
to keep U.S. troops on the peninsula -- as a stabilizing influence
in the greater Asia-Pacific region. That is the same reasoning
behind keeping U.S. troops permanently in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Many South Koreans, however, might not see it that way if their
country were reunified with the North. Already there is a push --
small but sometimes forceful -- among South Korean youth to demand a
U.S. withdrawal. For example, about 2,000 people clashed with riot
police in a village outside of Seoul last week in demanding closure
of Koon-Ni Range, where villagers claim U.S. practice bombs
recently injured six people.
</P>
<P>
   Senior administration officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Thursday there already is considerable concern
within the Pentagon that the Korea summit has over-inflated
expectations for peace and prematurely raised the question of
reducing the size of the American military presence in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the matter Wednesday, Army Gen. Henry H. Shelton
said, ''I think that at this point we should wait and see'' what
follows from the summit talks. He warned against an impulse to
''leap to any conclusions'' and said he was not aware that the
future of U.S. troops in Korea was a subject of the summit.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, however, the South Korean president said upon his
return to Seoul that the presence of U.S. troops in the South was
discussed. He did not elaborate but said the exchange was ''very
useful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 1626 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Corrects Campus Security Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Associated Press reported erroneously on
June 12 that universities would be required under a bill passed by
the House to notify parents of the presence on campus of students
or workers convicted of sexual crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The bill says information on sexual predators should be made
available to the campus community, but does not state that parents
must be notified. A House Republican leadership summary of the
legislation erroneously said that it requires parental
notification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
