<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, Russia Pledge Closer Ties  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin on Thursday urged
Germany not to isolate his nation from Europe, emphasizing that
Moscow is eager to cooperate economically and strategically.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to business leaders during his first state visit to
Germany, Putin said he didn't understand why some NATO partners
want to exclude Russia from the alliance when ''NATO is moving
forward to our borders,'' by absorbing former Soviet allies.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is open to cooperation with NATO, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Russia will view it as a provocation if Europe
allows a U.S. missile defense system to be placed in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Russia faces a threat, it goes to destabilize not just
Europe but the entire world,'' he said. ''Some elements (of the
missile defense system) would be stationed in Europe. What should
Russia then think?''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is to decide later this year whether to go
ahead with a proposed missile defense system designed to protect
the United States from nuclear attack by rogue nations or
terrorists. Details on basing the system, with some interceptors
planned for Alaska, would come later.
</P>
<P>
   Economics are Putin's primary concerns in Germany, Europe's
richest nation and Russia's biggest creditor. He hopes during the
two-day visit to win concessions on debts and attract new
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Bilateral ties have been strained in recent years by issues
ranging from the war in Chechnya to NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''Germany is the core nation for European integration,'' Putin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting for the first time, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and
Putin appeared to have gotten along well, thanks in part to Putin's
familiarity with Germany, where he served for five years as a
Soviet spy during the Cold War. Schroeder said he was impressed
with Putin, describing him as ''knowledgeable and open-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to make a truly substantial new beginning in bilateral
relations,'' Schroeder said. ''Germany has an interest in a truly
strategic partnership with Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders continued discussions about Russia's debt during a
private dinner at Schroeder's residence and were taking the topic
up again Friday, although German officials have indicated they
would not forgive the debt outright. Putin also was accompanied by
members of his Cabinet, including the foreign, economic and culture
ministers, who were meeting separately with their counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Germany was Russia's top Western trading partner and biggest
financial backer in the 1990s, supporting the transformation from
communism with some $67 billion in loans, grants, credits and other
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Putin told business leaders Thursday that Russia's historic
economic ties to the former East Germany were not being adequately
utilized, and called on them to take advantage of the new stability
in the Moscow following recent presidential and parliamentary
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this chance isn't used it would be a great mistake,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
