<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 27; Nasdaq Gains 48  </HEADLINE>
By SETH SUTEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tech stocks came back to life on Wall Street
Thursday as shares of Lucent Technologies jumped on a report that
the company was considering spinning off its microelectronics unit.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 26.87 to close at
10,714.82, according to preliminary calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also rose. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index rose 8.06 to 1,478.60, and the Nasdaq composite index was up
48.23 at 3,845.64.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent was among the most actively traded stocks on the New York
Stock Exchange, rising $2.875 to $59.50 on reports it is
considering plans to spin off its microelectronics unit in a deal
analysts say could be valued at more than $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard shares also rose, gaining $3 to $117 after the
company announced plans to start an online commerce venture in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasm in the tech sector was muted, however, by a steep
dropoff in wireless equipment maker Qualcomm, which fell $9.062 to
$61.438. Chase H&AMP;Q cut its earnings and revenue estimates for
Qualcomm for the fourth quarter and next year. Bear Stearns &AMP; Co.
had cut its outlook for the company a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Financial sector stocks took a hit after Wachovia Corp., a
respected bank company based in North Carolina, warned investors
that its profits would be hurt by the effect of rising interest
rates. Wachovia shares tumbled $13.125 to $57.063.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a bank that people have a lot of respect for, and
that's got the banking stocks down on the day,'' said Charles
White, president and portfolio manager at Avatar Associates, a New
York-based money management firm.
</P>
<P>
   But outside of the specific factors driving tech stocks higher
and financial shares lower, White said the rest of the market was
struggling in the wake of mixed data on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's still a market looking for a sense of direction,'' White
said. ''My sense is that it's going to take more convincing news on
the economy before we can see any kind of volume in the market.
With earnings pre-announcement season here, there's even more
uncertainty ladled on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks had waffled earlier in the session as traders digested
data on unemployment benefits claims and industrial production.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve said production at the nation's factories,
mines and utilities rose a bigger-than-expected 0.4 percent in May,
but operating capacity was unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Labor Department said 296,000 Americans filed
for unemployment benefits last week, a decline of 16,000.
Economists consider claims below 300,000 an indication of a tight
labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola gained $2.688 to $55.688 after the company said it
reached a tentative deal to settle a race-discrimination lawsuit
from current and former employees. In addition, Salomon Smith
Barney upgraded its shares because efforts to localize the
soft-drink giant's business are beginning to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues barely edged out advancing issues on the NYSE,
where volume came to 988.73 million shares, up from 925.04 million
shares on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 3.78 at 509.98.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
