<DOCNO> APW20000615.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno: Defendants Need Better Access  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defendants who face the death penalty should
have better lawyers and access to genetic and other scientific
tests before they are convicted, Attorney General Janet Reno said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As debate over the death penalty heats up, Reno said, ''There
are too many people in this country who do not have competent
counsel to represent them in capital cases.''
</P>
<P>
   ''People should not be prosecuted for a capital crime until they
have a lawyer who can properly represent them and they have the
investigative and other resources necessary to properly investigate
the charges against them,'' she told her weekly news conference.
</P>
<P>
   This week, a 10-year Columbia University study found that
two-thirds of death sentences nationally are overturned on appeal,
often because of an incompetent defense or an overreaching
prosecution. The likely presidential nominees, Democrat Al Gore and
Republican George Bush, both support the death penalty but have
proposed wider access to DNA testing for the accused or condemned
to minimize the chances of a wrongful execution.
</P>
<P>
   Reno personally opposes the death penalty but has promised to
enforce it as long as it is law. She has authorized federal
prosecutors to seek it 149 times, more than any other attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   Two bills in Congress would provide genetic DNA testing for
inmates already on death row. Such genetic testing of evidence
found at crime scenes has on occasion ruled out a defendant as the
culprit.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said those bills don't address the most important problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is very important, critically important, that not only do
they have access to DNA testing before they get to the point of
being on death row, but that they have access to other forensic and
investigatory resources that will permit them to properly explore
their claim of innocence,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled the case of James Joseph Richardson which, as a
Florida prosecutor, she delved into as a special assignment from
the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will never forget turning around and looking over my
shoulder at that man who walked out of the courthouse free for the
first time in 21 years, and to think that he could have gone to the
electric chair for a crime I did not think he committed,'' Reno
said. ''We just can't do that. We cannot let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Illinois Gov. George Ryan, a Republican,
declared a moratorium on the death penalty to examine improvements
because 13 death row inmates in his state have had their
convictions overturned since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   At Reno's request, Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder has been
reviewing the fairness of federal penalty procedures. On Aug. 5,
convicted killer Juan Raul Garza is scheduled to become the first
federal prisoner put to death in almost four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Reno did not endorse a national moratorium on the death penalty.
''I think that the states bear a responsibility ... to make sure
that the person being prosecuted has competent counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   She said in federal capital cases, each of which she personally
reviews, she has been impressed ''by the quality of the counsel
being appointed by the federal judges. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 1711 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBS Books Its Second 'Survivor'  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- As the ''Survivor'' audience continues to grow,
CBS has already settled on a second, considerably drier, location
for the sequel: the Australian outback.
</P>
<P>
   The network has begun accepting applications for ''Survivor 2,''
which will be filmed in October and November for broadcast starting
January. CBS expects considerably more than the 6,100 applicants it
received for the first installment.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 23.2 million people watched the third installment
of the 13-week series Wednesday night, a 28 percent increase over
the previous week, Nielsen Media Research said on Thursday. It was
CBS's biggest audience with regular programming for that time slot
since at least 1987.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time ''Survivor'' did not go head-to-head
against ABC's ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' But it did compete
against the NBA Finals in about one-fifth of the country, including
Los Angeles and Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The soggy stowaways voted out a third person, 27-year-old San
Francisco lawyer Stacey Stillman, sending her away in a torrential
downpour.
</P>
<P>
   The rugged outback won't be nearly as wet as the tropical island
where the series is now set. The sun-baked, desolate territory has
its share of kangaroos, crocodiles, huge spiders and lizards,
however. The filming will take place late in the Australian
springtime.
</P>
<P>
   CBS knew after the first week's ratings that ''Survivor'' would
return, but wanted to make sure the interest built, said CBS
President Leslie Moonves. Casting for the second edition will be
just as important as the location, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The relatability of these people is one of the chords that is
striking people,'' he said. ''Everyone imagines what they would do
because they are seeing people like themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Stillman, appearing Thursday on CBS's ''The Early Show,'' said
she expected she would be voted out because she was the weakest
physically in her group and her personality clashed with some of
her fellow islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did get cranky,'' she said. ''We hadn't eaten in nine
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' last August, ''Survivor''
is enlivening the normally dull summer rerun season. And it's been
a bonanza for CBS's often futile effort to reach a younger
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''Survivor'' alone drew a bigger audience than ABC, NBC, Fox,
UPN and the WB combined Wednesday night among viewers aged 18-34,
Nielsen said. Normally, CBS's typical viewer tops age 50.
</P>
<P>
   That is already affecting the rest of the network, Moonves said.
The Wednesday movie that follows ''Survivor'' has reached a younger
audience over the past three weeks than it has all year.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of shows on our schedule that do have a
younger appeal but people don't know to go there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The little-watched CBS ''Early Show,'' where each ''Survivor''
contestant voted out the previous night appears for a Thursday
morning interview, has even benefited. Last week its Thursday
ratings were higher than they'd been since February.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Survivor'' audience is likely to get even bigger, since
next week there won't be an NBA playoff game or ''Millionaire''
edition to compete with.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it still has some room go grow,'' Moonves said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 1713 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heidelberger buying part of Kodak's old manufacturing hub  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - The digital division of German printing
giant Heidelberger Druckmaschinen AG, which bought Eastman Kodak
Co.'s office-imaging unit last spring, is purchasing a big chunk of
Kodak's Elmgrove industrial hub.
</P>
<P>
   The 770-acre, 17-building manufacturing, office and warehouse
site in the Rochester suburb of Gates was put up for sale last
summer as part of restructuring plan to cut up to 2,500 jobs at the
photography company.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak said Thursday that Heidelberg Digital has agreed to buy
760,000 square feet, or about one-fifth, of the plant for an
undisclosed price. Some 3,100 of the digital division's 24,000
employees work in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak said the agreement will not affect its plan to turn over
the Elmgrove site to Cohen Asset Management Inc., a developer in
Beverly Hills, Calif. Appraisers have estimated that the plant
could fetch between $30 million and $50 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
