<HEADLINE> Clinton Targets Hispanic Students  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton challenged educators and
Congress on Thursday to double the number of Hispanic students who
graduate from college, and again threatened to veto an education
spending bill he said shortchanges his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are still a lot of gaps that we all want to close,''
Clinton said at a White House conference on Hispanic education. The
one-day session focused on ways to close long-standing gaps in
academic performance, high school graduation and college attendance
between Hispanic youngsters and their peers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first step to closing that gap is to believe, as I do,
that high expectations are for all students,'' Clinton said. ''I
believe intelligence is equally distributed throughout the world
but opportunity is not, and the same is true within our own
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The president listed five national goals for Hispanic education
that he said Americans should accomplish over the next decade:
Increase Hispanic participation in early childhood education;
ensure proficiency in English; eliminate the gap in achievement
test scores; increase the rate of high school graduation and
increase the rate of college graduation.
</P>
<P>
   The White House notes Hispanic enrollment in the Head Start
education program for young children has increased by 60,000 since
Clinton took office, and Clinton pointed to other gains he said
prove his approach is working.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, that progress is threatened,'' by the $339.4
billion education, health and labor spending package passed in the
House on Wednesday, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an earlier veto threat by Clinton, Republicans rammed
the huge fiscal 2001 measure through the House by a near party-line
217-214 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Though the bill would boost spending for the Education
Department and many other programs above this year's levels, it
ignores or cuts many Clinton proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ''If that bill were to come to my desk, I would have to veto it
but I hope we can work with Congress on a bipartisan education
bill,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
