<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spitzer: Some stores routinely selling smokes to minors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - An undercover investigation found that some
stores in upstate New York routinely sell cigarettes to minors, and
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said Thursday that proves retailers
and the state aren't doing enough to enforce the law.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation targeted 11 retail chains that have been
sanctioned in the past for selling tobacco products to people under
18 years old. It found during the past three months that these
stores sold cigarettes to underage teens 47 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ''The results are horrendous,'' Spitzer said. ''There was proven
data that they were violators of the law, but have they changed
their behavior? No.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst violator of the state's Adolescent Tobacco Use
Prevention Act according to the attorney general's investigation,
was Walgreen's which sold to teens in 92 percent of the attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly there's a tremendous diversity in the sincerity with
which retailers are upholding the law,'' Spitzer said, comparing
Walgreen's results to a previous study that found downstate
retailer Waldbaum's selling to teens in only 3 percent of the
attorney general office's attempts.
</P>
<P>
   A call for comment left at Walgreen's corporate headquarters in
Deerfield, Ill., was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   The stores targeted by the investigation were: A Plus Mini
Marts, Convenient, Eckerd Drugs, Hannaford Supermarkets, Kinney
Drugs, Mobil Convenience Stores (including Mobil ''On the Run''
Stores), Seven-Eleven, Stewart's, Sunoco, Walgreen's and Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   This ''should reinforce the fact that New York state must do
much more to keep cigarettes out of the reach of children,'' said
Elizabeth Miller, CEO of the American Lung Association of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The stores that violated the state's law by selling to minors
are expected to face stiff civil penalties and heavy fines if they
do not make a commitment to curbing teen smoking, Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the attorney general's office unveiled a public
education campaign Thursday that will put more than 31,000 TV spots
on cable stations such as MTV, VH-1, Nickelodeon and ESPN during
peak child and teen viewership hours.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials are paid for with $300,000 in funds collected
fines against stores and by matching funds from cable companies as
a public service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
