<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police must kill 436 pound black bear  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A black bear's five-hour jaunt through city
streets and parks ended early Thursday when police shot the animal
seven times, killing it.
</P>
<P>
   The 436-pound black bear, estimated to be 3 to 4 years old, was
first spotted about 1:30 a.m. on a city street but quickly slipped
into a wooded area, said police spokesman Det. James Miller. For
the next five hours, police tracked the bear over residential
streets, through parks and commercial areas.
</P>
<P>
   By 5:30 a.m., the city was beginning to wake up and police
worried how the bear would react as people emerged to get their
newspapers, walk their dogs or go to school. They contacted the
state Department of Environmental Conservation to see about
tranquilizing the bear.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now an issue that weighed on us is that he was in a heavily
residential area and how dangerous could this situation be for the
general public,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   When the bear approached a person walking a dog then went toward
an officer, the officer shot it twice with a shotgun. The bear took
off, tracked by one of the city's police dogs.
</P>
<P>
   By this point, DEC had notified police the bear was too big to
tranquilize, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Around 6 a.m., police cornered the bear behind a residence and
shot it three more times. The bear bolted across the street where
an officer shot it again. The bear stood up and tore down a section
of stockade fence. A seventh shot finally put the bear down.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unfortunate the bear had to be killed but that was far
outweighed by the possibility that the bear could harm someone,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The bear, which had an identification tag that showed it came up
from Pennsylvania, was taken to a state laboratory for a necropsy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
