<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trooper boss chooses former FBI colleague as internal affairs chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A former FBI agent has been chosen to direct
the internal affairs unit of the State Police by trooper
Superintendent Col. Carson J. Dunbar Jr., himself a retired FBI
agent, a State Police spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Richard J. Dorn Jr. would become the first outsider to head the
unit, which reportedly has upset some troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar told The Trenton Times in Thursday editions that he
picked Dorn because someone not personally acquainted with troopers
under investigation would be better able to review cases fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar was unavailable for comment Thursday, spokesman John
Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   Dorn, a lawyer, retired from the FBI June 2 after a 21-year
career in which he supervised agents combatting foreign spies.
</P>
<P>
   He is to start Monday at the State Police with a captain's
salary of about $83,200, Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Lennon, president of the state's largest troopers union, said
Dorn's hiring rankled officers already reeling from two years of
turmoil centered on findings of racial profiling, which included
the sacking of one superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's another smack in the face to sworn members who have been
there, who have come up the ranks and who are capable of doing the
job,'' Lennon told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The State Police has been under scrutiny regarding its treatment
of minorities, both within the ranks and in the general population.
</P>
<P>
   Two troopers are awaiting trial on charges of attempted murder
for the wounding of three minority men during a turnpike traffic
stop in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That stop raised questions on whether troopers improperly used
race as a reason to stop motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Reports issued in 1999 by the state Attorney General's Office
documented the practice and also detailed racial discrimination in
hiring and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Dorn will be a civilian, but will fill one of two captain's
slots in the Office of Professional Standards, which has been
expanded to 37 troopers, all with the rank of sergeant or above,
Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   Dorn will oversee the daily management of the office and report
to Maj. Joseph Brennan, who is in charge of the office, Hagerty
said. Brennan will review completed investigations and forward them
to the superintendent for review, hearings and disciplinary
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The office is now based in Freehold. Dunbar has said the central
location would make it easier for members to investigate complaints
and to visit the citizens who file them.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar took over in November from Col. Carl Williams, who was
fired Feb. 28, 1999, after published remarks appeared in which he
linked minorities to drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Dorn is a lifelong New Jersey resident, Dunbar told The Trenton
Times. The superintendent declined to say where he lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
