<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Slump Solution Sought  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Education officials want to fight the
''who-cares syndrome'' plaguing America's high school seniors who
increasingly are showing up late for classes or skipping them
entirely -- even students needing to prepare for college.
</P>
<P>
   ''The senior year is too often a lost opportunity that we need
to reclaim,'' Education Secretary Richard Riley told a conference
of more than 1,400 high school educators Thursday. ''Too many of
our high school graduates are falling off the ladder of success
just when they should be climbing upward.''
</P>
<P>
   A record number of high school graduates are going to college,
department statistics show. But teachers report that high school
seniors accepted into college by December spend the rest of the
year concentrating on getting a summer job or having a great prom.
</P>
<P>
   Students not bound for college also lose interest in earning
good grades as they collect credits needed for graduation.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Riley said, one-third of college students require
remedial classes, the college dropout rate stands at 25 percent and
thousands of other students are ill-prepared to work.
</P>
<P>
   ''These young people really do have a serious case of the
'who-cares' syndrome,''' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   The department announced it will put at least $250,000 toward
creating a special panel to study the problem and help teachers and
principals keep students engaged.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit foundations will help cover the cost of members
meeting with students and teachers across the country. The panel
will report its findings to the public and recommend programs for
high schools.
</P>
<P>
   Growing enrollment is focusing more attention than ever on high
schools, educators say. In the next 10 years, an additional 1.3
million students will be in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't do what we did 30 years ago,'' said Kentucky Gov.
Paul Patton, who will direct the group's work. ''We live in a
different world. The opportunities our young people have are
infinitely greater, but the challenges are likewise.''
</P>
<P>
   Educators such as Karen Gray, a high school official from Coos
Bay, Ore., recommended steering high school seniors toward
internships and community service learning.
</P>
<P>
   At Marshfield High School in her town, seniors can earn academic
credits -- for high school and, sometimes, college -- for work they
do on nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not where you go and clean up the beach,'' Gray said.
''It's where you actually learn about beach ecology and then do
something with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley recommended rigorous pre-college courses for seniors. He
also suggested that districts test eighth-graders and that more
states require students to pass a test before earning a diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the exit exams, required in 19 states, are an unfair
burden on poor and minority students whose schools have not done a
good job.
</P>
<P>
   ''Years ago, I opposed high stakes exit exams,'' Riley said.
''Today, I believe high school exit exams can help stimulate new
efforts to raise minority achievement if we give every student the
individual support needed to pass the exam.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For more information:
http://www.ed.gov/offices/OVAE/nahs/reinvent.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 1745 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bronx DA clears cop in killing of unarmed man  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The Bronx district attorney's office has cleared
a narcotics officer who shot an unarmed man in the head only blocks
from where Amadou Diallo was slain. Prosecutors concluded the
killing was an accident.
</P>
<P>
   In an 18-page report issued Thursday, prosecutors said an
''exhaustive investigation'' found no evidence to support criminal
charges against Officer Louis Rivera in the death of Malcolm
Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rather, on balance, the evidence supports (Rivera's) statement
that the death of Malcolm Ferguson occurred accidentally, in the
course of a struggle,'' the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera himself ''stated that he has no recollection of pulling
the trigger and was surprised when the gun fired,'' the report
added.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson's parents have contended their son was ''executed''
while he lay face down and helpless in a stairwell, comparing the
incident to the controversial police slayings of two other unarmed
black men - Diallo in February 1999 and Patrick Dorismond a year
later.
</P>
<P>
   Bronx prosecutors charged the four officers who fired 41 bullets
at Diallo with murder; they were acquitted earlier this year. The
Dorismond shooting remains under investigation by Manhattan
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Ferguson family attorney Andrew Miller said the
parents - who have filed a $300 million wrongful death claim
against the city - were ''outraged'' by District Attorney Robert
Johnson's decision not to put the case before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ''This shooting was totally unjustifiable and it is
inconceivable that the shooter will go unpunished in criminal
court,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, 23, was killed March 1 during a confrontation with
plainclothes narcotics officers in a Bronx apartment building
plagued by drug dealing.
</P>
<P>
   Police alleged that Ferguson - a parolee who was carrying heroin
- was killed after he and other drug suspects were stopped by the
officers. When he broke away and tried to flee, Rivera caught him
in the stairwell. A struggle ensued and the officer's 9 mm Smith &AMP;
Wesson discharged once, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from Johnson's office said they found civilian
witnesses who confirmed Rivera's claims that he had identified
himself as a police officer and that during the struggle he
implored, ''Stop resisting. Why are you resisting?''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera described both men tumbling to the ground as he grabbed
Ferguson's shoulder with his left hand and drew his gun with his
right. Amid the scuffle, he tried ''to improve his grip on the
gun,'' which ''may have caused his index finger to slip and make
contact with the trigger,'' he told investigators.
</P>
<P>
   A consensus of civilian and police witnesses said that Rivera
emerged from the building saying, ''I shot him. Call a boss and a
bus'' - police parlance for a supervisor and an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   The report also concluded that there was no forensic or medical
evidence to support accusations by Ferguson's family that he was
shot while his head was pressed against a hard surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-15-00 1747 </TRAILER>
