<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court: Offender entitled to sex registry hearing  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A man was entitled to a hearing before being
classified as a sexually violent predator under the state's
sex-offender registry, New York's highest court ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The sex offender's right to due process under both the state and
federal constitutions was violated in the case, the state Court of
Appeals decided in a 7-0 ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The decision continues the process by state courts of
interpreting New York's version of ''Megan's Law.'' The 1996
statute set up a mandatory registry for convicted sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling Thursday in another case involving a sex offender, the
Court of Appeals said a man who pleaded guilty to an August 1995
sex offense in the Bronx is not entitled to court review of his
classification in the registry.
</P>
<P>
   Those judged to be at the highest risk of committing another sex
crime upon their release from prison or jail - so-called Level 3
offenders in the registry - face reporting requirements with
authorities, the release of their names, pictures and addresses to
the public and other steps designed to alert the community to their
presence.
</P>
<P>
   A man identified in court papers only as ''David W.'' was
sentenced to one year in jail for refusing to sign a registration
form which classified him as a Level 3 offender.
</P>
<P>
   David W., of Southampton in Suffolk County, was convicted in
1995 of sodomizing and sexually abusing two boys. He argued that
since his crimes were committed before the state's sex registry was
set up, he was being denied his constitutional due process rights
by the way he was classified.
</P>
<P>
   Those convicted after 1996 are assigned risk classifications by
judges and have a right to be heard on those decisions at that
time. But sex offenders prior to 1996 who had served time and been
released get classified by parole or probation officers without a
hearing. David W.'s lawyers argued that is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals agreed Thursday. The way David W. was
classified, the judges said, ''did not provide defendant with any
meaningful way to voice his objections.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Due process requires that the state bear the burden of
proving, at some meaningful time, that a defendant deserves the
classification assigned,'' the court said in a decision written by
Carmen Beauchamp Ciparick. ''Here, the state did not bear the
burden of proof at any proceeding before a neutral fact finder.''
</P>
<P>
   William Ferris, an assistant district attorney for Suffolk
County, said Thursday's ruling is ''narrowly framed'' and will have
a ''limited'' effect in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''This change and other recent legislative amendments to the
(Megan's Law) statute will give police and prosecutors clear
constitutional guidelines to track all violent sexual predators in
the future,'' Ferris said.
</P>
<P>
   David W.'s lawyer Charles Newell did not return a telephone call
for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the other Megan's Law-related case, the court rejected the
contention of Ian Kearns that he had the right to challenge his
classification as a Level 3 offender after he pleaded guilty to a
sexual abuse charge involving a 16-year-old girl in the Bronx in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The court noted that the state Legislature has amended Megan's
Law to provide for appeals of classification rulings made after
Jan. 1, 2000. But the judges declined to extend that privilege
retroactively to cases like Kearns'.
</P>
<P>
   In another ruling Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   -The Court of Appeals said it has decided against hearing a
challenge to New York City's policy of seizing the vehicles of
drivers caught driving while intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Civil Liberties Union had filed the suit on behalf
of Pavel Grinberg, a 28-year-old Staten Island man whose 1988 Acura
was seized by authorities when he was allegedly caught driving
while drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Two lower courts affirmed that the city's application of a
56-year-old seizure ordinance to DWI cases is legal.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals did not detail why it was refusing to hear
the Grinberg case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-15-00 1758 </TRAILER>
