<HEADLINE> GOP Seeks New Disclosure Rules  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several congressional Republicans proposed
legislation Thursday to bring labor unions and business groups
under the same financial disclosure rules as the Senate recently
approved for a growing number of secretive groups seeking to sway
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''The public has the right to know the identity of those trying
to influence our elections,'' said Sen. Gordon Smith of Oregon as
he and some fellow GOP senators previewed their plan to require
disclosure of donors and expenditures for political activity.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was greeted warily by supporters of comprehensive
campaign finance overhaul legislation, some of whom noted that
Smith and his group consistently opposed their legislation to curb
the influence of money in campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   An aide said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., was ''cautiously
interested and exploring details.'' Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis.,
noted that Smith and his group had effectively reversed course from
last week, when they opposed a disclosure proposal in a Senate
vote. Still, he said, ''We want to make sure they don't love it to
death.''
</P>
<P>
   The developments came as both houses moved toward votes on
disclosure legislation, the remnants of a broader, failed effort to
reduce the role of money in campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, Feingold and Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., won a
surprise victory last week in the Senate when they succeeded in
winning approval for a proposal to impose disclosure requirements
on a secretive group of organizations. These groups, known as 527s
for the section of the tax code that governs them, have become more
prominent in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Within a day of the Senate vote, moderate Republicans in the
House won a promise from their leadership that the issue would be
brought to the floor by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., and others challenged
Democrats to support their effort to bring unions under greater
disclosure rules.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anytime on the floor of the Senate anything affects labor
unions, Democrats say it is a poison pill,'' said McConnell.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would apply to unions and business groups such as
the Chamber of Commerce. It would not require disclosure of
memberships lists, but would mandate public disclosure of anyone
donating $200 or more to political activity, as well as spending in
excess of $500.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would not affect diverse other groups which engage
in political activity, ranging from the National Right to Life
Committee to the American Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell told reporters he believes the proposal is of dubious
constitutionality and he expects a court test if it is approved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
