<HEADLINE> Sentence in Auschwitz Case Cut  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- A Polish court on Thursday wiped out the
sentence of a Roman Catholic leader convicted of inciting hatred of
Jews by urging people to erect crosses outside the former Nazi
death camp at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling on an appeal by Kazimierz Switon, the provincial court in
southern Bielsko-Biala upheld his conviction but reduced a
six-month suspended prison term imposed in January to a fine of
$313, court spokesman Jaroslaw Sablik said.
</P>
<P>
   The court then forgave the fine, saying Switon paid more than
its equivalent when he unnecessarily spent one month in prison in
1999 on other charges that were never confirmed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Switon, who said last month he wants to run for president this
fall, was initially convicted by a regional court in Oswiecim, the
site of the Auschwitz museum.
</P>
<P>
   Switon was charged after residents complained about statements
he made at the site in 1998, where followers erected more than 300
crosses surrounding a large cross used as a backdrop for a 1979
papal mass at nearby Birkenau.
</P>
<P>
   The action was taken to prevent removal of the papal cross,
placed at the site near Auschwitz in 1988 and visible from inside
the camp. The presence of the cross drew protests from
international Jewish groups and the Israeli government for
insulting the memory of Jews killed at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Urging followers to put up crosses, Switon said in leaflets
''the time has come for us Poles to wage merciless war on
Jewish-communist-masonry, the biggest enemies of the Polish
state.''
</P>
<P>
   The government had army troops remove the crosses in May 1999,
right before John Paul II made his eighth pilgrimage to his
homeland. The larger cross remained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
