<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate votes to name new rail station after retiring Lautenberg  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - The Senate voted Thursday to honor retiring
Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., in a manner reflecting one of his
political passions: public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with a unanimous voice, the Senate approved a proposal
to attach Lautenberg's name to the Secaucus Transfer Station, a
transit hub under construction in Hudson County.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the proposal is approved by the House, the station will
be called the Frank R. Lautenberg Transfer Station.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg, who is leaving the Senate at the end of the year
after three terms, is a longtime advocate of mass transit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to see Senator Lautenberg honored in an
appropriate way as he departs his service to the Senate and to the
nation's transportation system,'' said Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala.,
as he proposed to name the station after his colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby is chairman of the Senate Transportation Appropriations
Subcommittee. Lautenberg is the highest-ranking Democrat on the
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Several people in Washington and New Jersey said Thursday that
Shelby initially tossed out a much more dramatic idea: renaming
Newark International Airport after Lautenberg. But that idea did
not go far.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued by his office, Lautenberg said he was
''truly surprised and humbled'' that Shelby even proposed naming
the airport after him.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg said the Secaucus transfer station ''will mean more
comfortable, more efficient travel for thousands of state
residents.''
</P>
<P>
   The transfer station is slated to open in May 2002, and is being
financed by federal funds. In 1994, the Federal Transit
Administration pledged to provide full funding for the project,
which carried an estimated price tag of $444 million.
</P>
<P>
   The station will provide a central connection point, for the
first time, for most of New Jersey's rail lines. Lautenberg's
office said the station will cut commuting times for an estimated
2,700 rail riders by an average of 15 minutes per trip.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to name the station for Lautenberg was adopted as
an amendment to the Senate's fiscal year 2001 transportation
spending bill. The Senate endorsed the amendment by voice vote
shortly before voting, 99-0, to approve the overall bill.
</P>
<P>
   During the brief debate over the amendment, Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass., called Lautenberg ''an extraordinary champion for public
transportation (and) for aviation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not easy to champion the rail system in a country that
has been so dominated by automobiles,'' Kerry said. ''For all his
years here, Frank Lautenberg has been the single strongest advocate
in making certain we have an alternative form of transportation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
