<HEADLINE> Nader: Cut Benefits To Mortgage Cos  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ralph Nader, warning of a potential taxpayer
bailout similar to the savings and loan crisis, urged lawmakers to
cut government benefits to mortgage-market giants Fannie Mae and
Freddie Mac -- which he called ''poster children for corporate
welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   But some lawmakers said Thursday that acting hastily could raise
the cost of buying a home by increasing borrowing costs for Fannie
Mae and Freddie Mac, which are called government-sponsored
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Nader in criticizing the two mortgage companies at a
House subcommittee hearing was the head of the National Community
Reinvestment Coalition. Officials of the National Taxpayers Union,
Citizens Against Government Waste and the Competitive Enterprise
Institute made criticisms in written testimony they submitted.
</P>
<P>
   They added to recent criticism from lawmakers and regulators
against the two publicly traded companies, which Congress created
to buy home loans from banks and other lenders to supply ready cash
to the mortgage market.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics believe there is an inherent conflict between the
companies' government mandate and their duty to their shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ''For too long, the Congress has played the role of an indulgent
parent to'' Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, which ''have long since
grown beyond adolescence,'' Nader testified. ''It is time for (the
two companies) to give up ties to the federal government that have
made them poster children for corporate welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader, taking a break from campaign as the Green Party's
presidential candidate, warned that an S&AMP;L-style bailout, costing
taxpayers billions, could occur if Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were
to collapse in rougher economic times.
</P>
<P>
   David Jeffers, a spokesman for Fannie Mae, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that Fannie Mae is one of the best managers of risk
in the world,'' he said in a telephone interview after the hearing.
''There are a variety of advantages and benefits that Fannie Mae
has ... that demonstrate the partnership between Congress and
Fannie Mae.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Freddie Mac had no immediate comment on the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Nader endorsed a bill proposed by Rep. Richard Baker, R-La.,
chairman of the House Banking subcommittee on capital markets,
securities and government-sponsored enterprises, that would strip
away some of the companies' key benefits, such as their ability to
borrow directly from the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Paul Kanjorski of Pennsylvania, the subcommittee's
senior Democrat, cautioned: ''We must ... ensure that we do not
accidentally raise homeownership costs. ... We should not move
precipitously.''
</P>
<P>
   John Taylor, president and CEO of the National Community
Reinvestment Coalition, said his group had found that Fannie Mae
and Freddie Mac lag behind banks in the percentage of home
mortgages they finance that go to members of minorities and
low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   He said access to a never-used, emergency $2.25 billion line of
credit at the Treasury Department should come with a condition that
they meet their goals for making affordable housing available.
</P>
<P>
   In March, officials of the Department of Housing and Urban
Development said figures showed that Fannie Mae's policies have
increased costs and may have reduced the availability of home
mortgages for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.freddiemac.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.fanniemae.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 1828 </TRAILER>
