<HEADLINE> Boeing Awarded Naval Contract  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Navy announced Thursday it signed a $8.9
billion contract with Boeing Co. for production of 222 F/A-18 Super
Hornet fighter aircraft, its new version of the existing F/A-18
Hornet.
</P>
<P>
   The work is to be done over a five-year period at Boeing plants
in St. Louis and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Although some members of Congress have criticized the Super
Hornet program as an inefficient way of giving the Navy and Marine
Corps a more modern fighter aircraft, Navy leaders insist it is
vital to their future.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will provide twice the sorties, a third the combat losses
and 40 percent greater range,'' said Adm. Jay Johnson, the chief of
naval operations. ''We can't wait to get it to the fleet.''
</P>
<P>
   Strike Fighter Squadron 115 from Naval Air Station Lemoore,
Calif., is scheduled to be the first squadron with operational
Super Hornets. It is scheduled to make its first deployment with
Super Hornets in June 2002 aboard the USS Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
</TEXT>
