<HEADLINE> Report: Funds Split Unfairly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fourteen states and the District of Columbia
get 80 percent of the money the federal government spends on
research and development, according to a White House report
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Federal research and development totals about $80 billion
annually spent by 24 different government agencies. Every state,
plus the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico, gets something.
</P>
<P>
   California is by far the leader among states, with a research
take of $14.4 billion. Much of that money goes to universities and
other institutions involved in high technology and biomedical
research.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only by supporting research where the returns are not
guaranteed can we ensure the steady, gradual progress that
underpins front-page news stories that accompany each new
success,'' said White House science adviser Neal Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taking a risk on open-ended research, whose cost-effectiveness
is often difficult to guarantee, sometimes generates the greatest
economic returns,'' Lane said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   The top recipients of research dollars are: California;
Maryland; Virginia; Georgia; Texas; Massachusetts; Florida; New
York; Ohio; the District of Columbia; Alabama; Pennsylvania; New
Mexico; New Jersey and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The report was prepared by a federally funded research and
development center within the RAND Corp.
</P>
<P>
