<HEADLINE> AMA Passes Reproductive Measure  </HEADLINE>
By LINDSEY TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Under the watchful eye of the Roman Catholic
church, the American Medical Association steered a cautious path
Thursday through the minefield of pregnancy prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA passed a measure aimed at ensuring patient access to
reproductive services, including tubal ligation and vasectomy, when
church-owned hospitals merge with or acquire other hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But as the nation's largest doctors group closed its annual
meeting, members also affirmed a policy that physicians should not
be forced to do anything that violates their moral principles.
</P>
<P>
   The 247-184 vote by the AMA's House of Delegates followed
testimony and heated debate this week. Among those testifying was
Cardinal Francis George, head of the Chicago archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   The pregnancy prevention measure was a softened version of a
resolution drafted by the AMA's California delegation.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation was motivated by concern that hospital
acquisitions by Catholic health-care networks have deprived some
communities of pregnancy prevention facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents said the first resolution would have forced
Catholic hospitals to provide pregnancy services in violation of
church doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   Nora O'Callaghan, a spokeswoman for the Chicago archdiocese,
said Catholics' main concern with the first measure ''was the idea
that there was going to be a coercive attempt to force Catholic
hospitals to violate their Catholic teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   The California delegation helped amend the resolution after an
AMA committee recommended that it be softened.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to give patients access and still respect the
individual moral teachings of all concerned,'' said Dr. Delmar
Tonge, the delegation's chairman, after Thursday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   Tonge said the AMA will now work with Catholic hospitals to help
steer patients to facilities that offer reproductive services when
there are mergers in their community.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Health Association, which represents more than
2,000 not-for-profit Catholic health-care systems nationwide,
called Thursday's vote a victory.
</P>
<P>
   The vote upheld patients' and doctors' constitutional rights to
religious freedom, the association said.
</P>
<P>
   In other action, the AMA agreed to oppose psychiatric therapies
that assume homosexuality is a mental disorder and therapists who
suggest patients change their sexual orientation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
