<HEADLINE> Albright Headed Back to Middle East  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will
return to the Mideast East in about 10 days for another attempt at
turning Israeli-Palestinian discord into settlement by
mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   Albright will ''assess whether a summit would be useful at this
point or whether more work needs to be done,'' State Department
spokesman Richard Boucher said Thursday. The decision by President
Clinton to dispatch Albright underscores his push for a deal in his
final months in office.
</P>
<P>
   Slow-moving negotiations between the two sides in Washington
will continue for a few more days before U.S. mediator Dennis B.
Ross travels to the Middle East, ahead of Albright, said Boucher.
</P>
<P>
   Already twice this month, Albright has visited the Middle East --
for talks with Barak and Arafat, and for Syrian President Hafez
Assad's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, after meeting Thursday with
Clinton at the White House, lashed out at Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, whom he once described as his peace partner. The
Israeli ''lacks the desire to work with us in order to achieve a
comprehensive peace in the region,'' Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat sought Clinton's help in achieving his goals, foremost of
which is a state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
   A top Arafat aide, Nabil Abourdeneh, said talk of a three-way
summit was premature. ''The gap between the two positions is still
wide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From Jerusalem, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy fired back
at the Palestinians, saying their goal is ''to arrive at a point
where these talks will not produce any results.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations in Washington have sputtered, partly broken off by
the Palestinians to protest Israel's refusal to release 250
prisoners and to agree to Arafat's terms for an Israeli pullback
this month on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is prepared to declare statehood without Israel's
approval if a settlement is not concluded by Sept. 13, the deadline
the two sides have set.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration expressed tepid support for Barak,
whose willingness to yield territory on all fronts to the Arabs
contrasts with the hard line stance of his predecessor, Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we are satisfied that both leaders are very serious in
their efforts to reach an agreement,'' said P.J. Crowley, spokesman
for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Added Boucher, ''Both remain committed to achieving a peace
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton kept his distance from the rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we are going to make peace we are going to have to deal
with the difficult issues,'' he said before meeting Arafat. ''The
less we say now about it, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks resumed Tuesday, after a two-week break, at two
Washington-area Air Force bases. They immediately drifted into
disagreement
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I should characterize what is going on,''
Clinton said. ''The only thing I can tell you is I want to finish
the job, and I'd like to see it finished on time.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Arafat praised Clinton for trying to keep
negotiations alive ''at this difficult time and in the face of the
obstacles we're facing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton last year expressed support for Palestinian
''aspirations'' during a trip to Gaza. But NSC spokesman Crowley
dismissed any suggestion the president would prod Israel or the
Palestinians to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not in the position to pressure them,'' Crowley said.
''They understand that time is not on their side. ... I don't think
we have any quarrel with the firmness by which the leaders and
their negotiating teams are working hard to see what can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   A settlement is Clinton's highest foreign policy priority before
he leaves office in January.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke with Barak by telephone for 40 minutes Wednesday
and said the two sides were not ready for a Camp David-style
three-way meeting with him. Albright called Barak on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we need to get the parties a little closer before we
can go there,'' Clinton said. ''We don't have a lot of time. We're
down to all the hard issues now, and we're working on it. I'm
hopeful, but I don't want to hold out false hopes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
