<HEADLINE> Marine Corps Faults Crew in Crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP PENDLETON, Calif. (AP) -- A Marine Corps helicopter crash
off San Diego that killed seven men was caused primarily by crew
mistakes while approaching a Navy ship, military officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The helicopter simply came in too low and too fast,'' Marine
Lt. Col. Carol McBride said in announcing results of an
investigation into the Dec. 9 accident.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Capt. James Lukehart, had more than 1,650 hours of
flight time and was not considered a ''hot-dog'' pilot, according
to a 29-page report.
</P>
<P>
   Six Marines and a Navy corpsman died and 11 others were rescued
after the rear landing gear of their CH-46E Sea Knight helicopter
snagged a safety net during a training exercise and plunged into
the sea 15 miles off Point Loma.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps plans to change its training and equipment
based on the report's findings, but McBride stressed that military
exercises are ''inherently dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
