<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Fast, Unfeeling 'Macbeth'  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Lady Macbeth isn't the only one sleepwalking on
stage at Broadway's Music Box Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Macbeth, in the person of television star Kelsey Grammer, seems
to be in a bit of a trance himself. But then, this misguided
revival of Shakespeare's great study of evil would induce
drowsiness in just about anyone, even its actors.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the producers have not spent a fortune on
lighting. This is the dimmest, darkest ''Macbeth'' in quite a
while, a minimalist rendition that seems to be painted entirely in
black and with its actors dressed in dark duds, too. Trendy, but
hard to see.
</P>
<P>
   For another, Grammer, best known from TV's ''Frasier'' and the
prime mover behind this production, is a curiously muted villain.
His detached demeanor gives the show a feeling of a recital, not a
full-fledged retelling of a bloody struggle for the Scottish crown.
</P>
<P>
   The production, which opened Thursday for a limited run through
July 30, flounders with him. A bearded Grammer doesn't get the
ambition and anguish that haunt this most possessed of
Shakespeare's title characters. He stands back, almost stepping
outside the play as the story of Macbeth's bloody rise to power
swiftly unfolds. The horror that should permeate the evening is
only perfunctorily portrayed, even in the murders of Macduff's wife
and children, one of the tragedy's more terrifying moments.
</P>
<P>
   Director Terry Hands doesn't offer much help. ''Macbeth'' is
Shakespeare's shortest play, but this cast races through it so fast
they should be wearing sneakers. It's a quick evening, two hours
and no intermission, which is wise, considering the end results.
</P>
<P>
   Hands has made some odd directorial choices. The banquet scene
with Banquo's ghost, one of the drama's more potent moments,
fizzles because the spirit never materializes. Here, Macbeth
shrieks at an empty chair. Less is definitely less.
</P>
<P>
   The three witches are of the bag-lady variety, loud yet often
unintelligible. They open the drama as if they are scavengers on a
field of battle as they rob and then murder a wounded soldier.
These vengeful harpies also assist in Macbeth's death, wounding him
as Macduff closes in for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   As Lady Macbeth, Diane Verona gives an empathic, almost hammy
performance. The actress underlines every speech with such
intensity that she vocally dwarfs Grammer. She even bellows during
the famous sleepwalking scene.
</P>
<P>
   Macbeth's helpmate is supposed to push her husband into murder,
but here, the acting styles of the two leads are so different that
the relationship between husband and wife doesn't get its due. The
twosome are never quite believable as companions in crime.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the large supporting cast is on stage so briefly
that most make little impression. Two exceptions: Peter Michael
Goetz, as the kindly yet doomed Duncan, and Peter Gerety, as the
bawdy Porter, who provides the play's brief moment of comic relief.
Gerety gets his laughs, no small accomplishment in this morose
production.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfeeling'' may be an even better word to describe what
happens on stage. And a production of ''Macbeth'' devoid of any
emotion is not much of a ''Macbeth'' at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 1842 </TRAILER>
