<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yale school teaches women the basics of politics  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - Linda Graham's practice stump speech is
going on too long and needs a better focus.
</P>
<P>
   She's trying to get across her family values platform for a
potential election in Michigan. Other women like her, many
newcomers to politics, are trying to help.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to protect the freedom families have in the United
States,'' Graham says.
</P>
<P>
   What's your point?
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe our families are in sad shape,'' she replies.
</P>
<P>
   Say it!
</P>
<P>
   ''Our families are in sad shape!'' Graham says, to applause.
</P>
<P>
   Graham and 30 other women in politics from around the country
are studying public speaking, fund raising, polling and other ins
and outs of political life at The Women's Campaign School at Yale
University.
</P>
<P>
   The school counts political leaders from around the world among
its graduates.
</P>
<P>
   While more women around the country are becoming political
leaders, the class of 2000 comes at a time when fewer women are
running for top offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for American Women and Politics at Rutgers University
reports that women serve in the U.S. Senate and House of
Representatives in record numbers. More women are in top state
elected offices than ever before, and more than one-fifth of state
legislators are women.
</P>
<P>
   Women also are shaping up to be a big force in the presidential
election. Vice president Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush are
trying to attract female voters, and women's names are brought up
as potential candidates for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of female candidates for the 2000 elections is
down from a boom in the mid-1990s, including 1992, which was dubbed
''The Year of the Woman'' after women made huge gains in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to say the sky is falling, but I think there is
reason to be concerned about the number of women running for office
and the rate and level of increase,'' said Debbie Walsh, associate
director of the Center for American Women and Politics.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in candidates may follow national trends of less
interest in politics because of the raging economy and good-paying
private-sector jobs, said George Dean, the co-chairman of the
Women's Campaign School.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there are fewer open seats in Congress this year than in
1992, and possible redistricting after the census scared some
candidates away from the 2000 race, Dean said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen R. Malcolm, president of the women's Democratic
fund-raising group EMILY's List, said that the numbers do not tell
the whole story and that women are in many of the hottest races
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think the number of women is as relevant as the
quality of women,'' Malcolm said. ''We see women for the most
competitive races being avidly recruited by the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the number of female candidates will likely jump in
2002, after redistricting creates open seats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh agreed that open seats are key to getting more women into
office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Beating incumbents just doesn't happen very often,'' Walsh
said.
</P>
<P>
   The women at the campaign school are far away from Congress.
Many are trying to get in on the ground floor of politics - on
school boards, county offices and city councils.
</P>
<P>
   Programs such as Yale's are important because these candidates
may move up into statewide or national office some day, Dean said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Naumann Blanchard wants to be elected to the Lafayette,
La. parish council and consult other women about how to run for
office. She was encouraged to attend the school on the
recommendation of a judge who had been through the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to get the tools to run an effective campaign,''
Blanchard said.
</P>
<P>
   J. Rebecca Goff of Hampton, N.J. has her sights set on the New
Jersey legislature.
</P>
<P>
   She said she got interested in politics after serving on a
governor's council to put teeth in state domestic violence laws.
She said the experience made her want to take part in making laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to learn how to speak effectively, how to boil down the
issues,'' Goff said.
</P>
<P>
   The five-day school also teaches women how to make the decision
to run for office, how to conduct research and polls, how to plan
and budget a campaign and raise money. They also learn how to get
their messages out in the media and how to craft an effective
message.
---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.rci.rutgers.edu/~cawp
</P>
<P>
   http://www.yale.edu/wcsyale
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-15-00 1846 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial forms show range of wealth in Congress  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Members of the House, like many of their
constituents, rode the high-tech sector of the stock market in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Saxton, R-Mount Holly, earned $16,000-$65,000 selling
shares of Net2Phone, a New Jersey-based Internet telephone company
headed by Clifford Sobel, the chief fund-raiser for the state GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema, R-Ridgewood, bought up to $15,000 worth of
stock in Cisco Systems last year, adding to a high-tech portfolio
that already included Intel Corp and Motorola Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Pallone, D-Long Branch, and his wife Sarah also
dabbled in high-tech stocks in 1999, buying shares of America
Online, Cisco Systems and Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Those glimpses into the private finances of public officials
were made possible by Thursday's release of financial disclosure
forms required annually of every member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rank-and-file members of Congress received salaries of $136,700
last year. The forms reveal assets and other sources of income,
plus any trips or gifts paid for by people or groups.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar estimates are not specific enough to give a sense of
someone's net worth, but they do indicate where members fall on the
range of wealth in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there can be little doubt about the wealthiest member of
the New Jersey House delegation: Rep. Rodney Frelinghuysen,
R-Harding, the latest in a line of Frelinghuysens to serve in
Congress. He holds millions of dollars worth of stock in Procter &AMP;
Gamble, Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. and IBM, among other companies. He also is
the beneficiary of six family trusts.
</P>
<P>
   Among other members:
</P>
<P>
   IBM was the stock of choice for Rep. Bill Pascrell, D-Paterson,
and his wife Elsie. They bought 100 shares last October.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Menendez, D-Union City, and his wife, Jane Jacobson,
bought shares in America Online and in Global Crossing, a
telecommunications company that is battling on Capitol Hill over
billions of dollars worth of radio spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Some members preferred funds over individual stock-picking. Rep.
Chris Smith, R-Robbinsville, and his wife Marie invested much of
their family's money in funds operated by Janus, Vanguard and
Scudder.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Rothman, D-Fair Lawn, had a bulging portfolio that
included nine individual retirement accounts and dozens of money
market and equity investment funds.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure forms showed that Rep. Donald Payne, D-Newark,
owns $1,000 to $15,000 worth of stock in Mail.com, an Internet
company that moved its offices last year from Manhattan to Jersey
City.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman came under fire earlier this year when it
was revealed that her husband, John, was on the board of Mail.com
at the time when the company applied for and received an incentive
grant from the state to move to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The forms also provide a summary of trips taken by members of
Congress and paid for by interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Franks, R-Berkeley Heights, the Republican nominee for
Senate in New Jersey this year, took a trip to Israel with his
wife, paid for by the American Israel Education Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Pascrell, sponsor of legislation to provide federal funding to
local fire departments, took trips funded by the Fire Department
Instructors Conference and the International Fire Chiefs
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Payne traveled to Beijing and Shanghai, paid for by the Aspen
Institute Conference on U.S.-China Relations, and to Berlin paid
for by the Aspen Institute Conference on U.S.-Russia Relations.
</P>
<P>
   He also traveled to the Canary Islands, paid for by the
Institute for Democratic Strategies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
