<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witness pleads for mercy for convicted killer in boy witness case  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - As 8-year-old Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr.
and his mother ran from a gunman they knew was going to kill them,
they must have felt ''fear, terror and abject psychological pain,''
a prosecutor said Thursday as he asked a jury to impose the death
penalty on the man convicted of engineering their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler's attorney asked the jury for mercy, saying
simply: ''There is some good in Russell Peeler.''
</P>
<P>
   The same jury that convicted Peeler in the murders of Leroy
''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother, Karen Clarke, will now decide
whether he gets life in prison or death.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is expected to begin deliberating Peeler's fate Friday
after receiving instructions from Judge G. Sarsfield Ford. Under
the state's death penalty law, the jury must weigh any mitigating
factors presented by the defense against aggravating factors
presented by prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In their closing arguments Thursday, prosecutors focused on the
horror of the crimes: an 8-year-old boy and his devoted mother,
gunned down in their home to stop the boy from testifying against
Peeler in an earlier murder case.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport State's Attorney Jonathan Benedict reviewed for the
jury the gruesome details of the crime, including B.J.'s anguished
cries of ''Mommy, Mommy, Mommy, Mommy!'' as the gunman fired at
them while they ran up the stairs of their Bridgeport home.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict told the jury they should consider the mother and son's
state of mind when Peeler's brother Adrian, the accused gunman,
allegedly started shooting. He argued that the murders were
committed ''in an especially heinous, cruel or depraved manner,''
an aggravating factor.
</P>
<P>
   ''What could she have been thinking? ... Other than he's going
to kill me, he's going to kill my baby,'' Benedict said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was screaming for his mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Peeler's attorney, William Koch, argued that Peeler did not
control how the murders were committed or suggest that any torture
be inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no evidence in this case that Mr. Peeler gave any
direction to the person that committed this offense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koch repeatedly told the jury that there is a difference between
convicting Peeler on certain evidence and sentencing him to death
based on the same evidence. H
</P>
<P>
   e noted the prosecution focused on Peeler's motive: that he
wanted B.J. silenced because he planned to testify against him in
the 1998 murder of his mother's boyfriend, Rudolph Snead Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ''Are you going to kill him because he had a motive?'' Koch
asked.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the jury to impose a life sentence, noting that Peeler
is already serving a life sentence in a federal drug case and will
die in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Koch also argued against the death penalty on moral grounds and
told the jury ''mistakes are made'' because the death penalty is
imposed by human beings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not right to kill somebody ... It's also not right that
the state - through you - turns around and executes him.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a power higher than the state of Connecticut that
should decide when, where and how this man dies.''
</P>
<P>
   But Benedict reminded the jury again and again of the utter
terror B.J. and his mother must have felt in the final moments of
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russell Peeler merits no more regard from you than he extended
to an 8-year-old boy and his mother,'' Benedict said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russell Peeler has - on his own - earned the forfeiture of his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Benedict said other aggravating factors the jury may consider
are Peeler's payments to accomplices in the killings. Josephine
Lee, who claimed she acted as a lookout for Adrian Peeler,
testified that Russell Peeler gave her a handful of crack cocaine
for her role. Gary Garner, the alleged driver of the getaway car,
received a bag full of money, according to testimony during the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Koch, however, argued that there was no evidence that Peeler
paid his brother, Adrian, to commit the murders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
