<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers compromise on transportation funding  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Key Republican leaders agreed Thursday to
funnel $3.75 billion over the next four years to continue a
statewide road and transportation building program.
</P>
<P>
   Differences between bills pending in the state Senate and
Assembly delayed any decision on how much the Transportation Trust
Fund would get and where the money would come from. Without
legislative approval, the fund would have expired in July.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers disagreed on the amount and the length of the funding
plan, with Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco, R-Union, wanting
$4 billion for the four years. Assembly Speaker Jack Collins had
backed the $3 billion version of the bill introduced in his house.
</P>
<P>
   Both leaders were split on how the state money should be
channeled into the fund, with DiFrancesco supporting plans to use
more of the state general revenue and dedicate a higher share of
the gasoline tax.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise bill features points from each version, including
an Assembly provision that requires lawmakers to vote on any new
highway and a Senate measure that caps salaries, operating expenses
and the amount the state can borrow.
</P>
<P>
   In its first year, the fund will provide a record $900 million
for improvements to state highways and public transportation. The
next three years will each be funded at $950 million.
</P>
<P>
   The latest bill caps state borrowing at $650 million each year.
The remaining money would be taken from a variety of sources,
including the state's general revenues, gasoline taxes and
dedicated sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The size of this program has to grow in order to meet the
demands of the infrastructure,'' DiFrancesco said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the state debt does not have to grow accordingly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have money in the budget that is readily available,'' he
said. ''We should use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman is committed to a program that provides
the transportation state residents need, said spokeswoman Jayne
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is obviously a very complicated bill, very technical. We
want to review it before commenting,'' O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Assembly Transportation Committee will vote to
approve the bill and send the compromise package onto the Senate,
said Assemblyman Alex DeCroce, R-Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will pass on Monday,'' said DeCroce, who chairs the
committee and sponsored the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The next available session for the Assembly to consider the bill
would be Thursday. If it is approved there, DiFrancesco said the
Senate could add its consent that day.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier version passed the Senate 33-3. But DiFrancesco's
companion bill for a constitutional amendment to permanently
earmark gas tax revenues to the trust fund failed to get enough
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats fought to include measures in the bill to prevent
suburban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   DeCroce said the requirement for legislative approval for new
highways ''takes the so-called sprawl issue out of the equation.''
</P>
<P>
   Testifying Thursday before the Assembly committee, Department of
Transportation Commissioner James W. Weinstein Jr. said he had
concerns with the caps on salaries and any ''fix-it-first''
language. Some lawmakers and environmental lobbyists have proposed
that the department be specifically directed to repair certain
roads and bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said such restrictions do not take into account the
realities of construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't make any sense to embody language that you can't
achieve,'' he said. ''You can't set theoretical goals for something
that has to happen in real time.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental activists criticized the measure, saying it gives
too much authority to the transportation department with little
oversight. They also challenged one section of the bill that would
allow new roadways to be built in environmentally sensitive areas.
The law would allow the new construction because it would extend
existing state roads.
</P>
<P>
   ''We realize the need of the trust fund, however, we believe
there should be accountability on the spending side. These are a
lot of tax dollars,'' said Marie Curtis of the New Jersey
Environmental Lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis also told the panel the roads needed to be tied into the
state plan to encourage redevelopment in existing urban and
suburban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe transportation projects should not be considered in
a vacuum,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Full text of bills available at the Office of Legislative
Services Web site located at http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-15-00 1907 </TRAILER>
