<HEADLINE> Monmouth prosecutor gets committee approval  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The Senate Judiciary Committee Thursday
approved the renomination of Monmouth County Prosecutor John Kaye,
but only after a grueling hearing in which his fitness for office
was roundly debated.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members cast a party-line 7-3 vote to advance Kaye's
six-year appointment to the full Senate for action. A vote is
scheduled for June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye, a Republican who has served since 1983, could not be
reached for comment after the committee vote.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the public who testified either demanded his ouster
or defended his law and order record.
</P>
<P>
   And in a committee first, one witness testified via long
distance conference call from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye, seeking his fourth term, has been acting in a holdover
capacity since his last term expired in October. Gov. Christie
Whitman finally renominated him in May.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting Kaye were members of the Monmouth County Human
Relations Council, Women's Center, and Chiefs of Police
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the prosecutor's side was William Thomas, whose
6-year-old granddaughter Amanda Wengert was murdered by a Manalapan
neighbor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But detractors pointed to three cases - two civil suits in which
Kaye was held liable and his prosecution of the man who sexually
assaulted Eddie Werner's killer - as reason to deny him another
term.
</P>
<P>
   Shamren Coleman-Fletcher of Maryland criticized Kaye for
sexually discriminating against her mother, Barbara Coleman.
Coleman, a sergeant in the Prosecutor's Office who has since died,
won $425,000 in damages plus legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye also lost a libel suit brought against him by a former
assistant county prosecutor, who won a $100,000 award.
</P>
<P>
   Nathanial J. Pallone, a Rutgers University psychology professor,
criticized Kaye for using Werner killer Sam Manzie to lure Manzie
molester Stephen Simmons. Instead, the prosecutor should have used
a police officer posing as Manzie, the professor said. Manzie
killed Werner after halting his cooperation in the Simmons
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Another critic, Theresa Castner of Keansburg, blamed Kaye's
office for lax enforcement of a drug dealer who supplied heroin to
her mother and uncle. Both Alice Castner and Robert Castner died of
overdose, Castner said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I do know is that there is a law that might have made a
difference but John Kaye opted to write it off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her aunt, Susan Castner also testified against Kaye via
conference call from her home in Japan - a committee first,
according to a committee aide.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Norman Robertson, R-Passiac, approved Kaye's nomination,
but admitted he had reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was not a slam dunk,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
