<HEADLINE> NRC discusses operations of Hope Creek, Salem nuclear plants  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOWER ALLOWAYS CREEK TOWNSHIP N.J. (AP) - Representatives of the
U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission met with officials from Public
Service Electric &AMP; Gas Co. and the public Thursday to discuss the
annual review of the company's nuclear generating stations in
southern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, in its review from April 1999 to April 2000,
said the Hope Creek Nuclear Plant and Salem Nuclear Generating
Stations all ''operated in a manner that preserved public health
and safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRC said that there had been problems with Hope Creek's
reactor core cooling system and with security on the property, but
that the troubles have been resolved. The commission said it
planned no additional inspections at Hope Creek beyond its normal
inspection program.
</P>
<P>
   At Salem Units 1 and 2, the NRC said it found that carbon
dioxide gas concentrations for fire suppression systems did not
reach and maintain the required levels during testing. PSE&AMP;G said
it would evaluate the cause of this by June 30 and would provide
the NRC with a schedule of corrective actions by July 15. The NRC
will reinspect the system, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1990s, both Salem reactors were plagued by a series
of mishaps and unscheduled shutdowns caused by mechanical failure
and human error. PSE&AMP;G was heavily fined and the NRC in 1997 placed
both reactors on its list of problem facilities requiring increased
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Located on the Delaware River about 35 miles south of
Philadelphia, the reactors supply power to parts of New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Delaware and Maryland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
