<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Courts Cos. on China Trade  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is turning to corporate
America for help in pressuring the Senate to vote quickly on the
China trade bill that has yet to be called up by Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be very unfortunate if this got caught up in the
everyday Washington politics that seems to slow everything else
down,'' White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   But on Capitol Hill, Lott spokesman John Czwartacki said that
the Mississippi Republican was still trying to bring the measure to
a vote -- and suggested that the decision on Thursday by Commerce
Secretary William Daley to resign to run Vice President Al Gore's
presidential campaign could complicate that effort.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not helpful,'' Czwartacki said.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors had hoped for a final vote before the Fourth of July
congressional recess. But Lott, who supports the bill, has had
difficulty finding a time for it and lining up enough bipartisan
support to move it through the Senate without time-consuming
amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Daley ''was the point man on it,'' Czwartacki said. ''I don't
think it will help the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met privately Thursday evening with members of the
Business Roundtable, an association of chief executives, apparently
to discuss how to persuade the Senate to vote before the July 4
holiday. The business group is a traditional ally of the Republican
Party, which controls the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said early this week he won't speed a vote on the trade
bill, saying it needs a full airing with members given the chance
to offer amendments if they want. He also said the Senate must give
higher priority to spending bills needed to keep the government in
operation in the new fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Lott supports the trade bill, and White House officials suspect
he has delayed the vote to gain leverage in the budget fight
between Congress and the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is meeting with business leaders ''to talk to them about
getting the Senate a little more energized about doing this
quickly,'' White House deputy press secretary Jake Siewert said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said, ''This is one of the most important votes the
Senate will take in a generation and we need to get to this as soon
as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade bill was approved by a 40-vote margin in the House
last month. It would grant China normal trade relations on a
permanent basis, rather than requiring an annual congressional
review of China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   Both major-party presidential candidates support the bill. But
it is being strongly opposed by organized labor, a key Democratic
constituency, and that could weigh in congressional races in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters assert the legislation will open China's vast markets
to U.S. businesses and help bring the nation of 1.2 billion people
-- the world's most populous -- into the world community. Labor
opposes it, criticizing China's human rights and worker protection
policies and suggesting the measure could cost American
manufacturing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The China trade bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House site: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO site: http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 1942 </TRAILER>
