<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Atlantic City registers ''remarkable'' drop in violent crime  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - Violent crime in this casino capital
plunged last year, with the number of reported rapes dropping to
pre-casino era levels, according to a report released Thursday by
police and prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The number of murders, rapes, robberies and aggravated assaults
dropped by 10 percent from 1998, while the total number of crimes
dipped by 0.8 percent, according to the report by Atlantic County
Prosecutor Jeffrey Blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a county that lays claim to a casino city where more than
35 million people visit 12 gaming halls each year, these numbers
are remarkable,'' said Blitz. He credited innovative city programs,
stepped-up cooperation between agencies and aggressive
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   The report was based on statistics released recently by the
State Police's Uniform Crime Reporting Unit and compared with
historical data for crime in the city and Atlantic County.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlantic City last year:
</P>
<P>
   -There were 640 violent crimes, down from 711 the previous year.
It was the lowest annual total in the city since 1978, when 656
violent crimes were reported and only one casino had opened.
</P>
<P>
   -There were 8,432 nonviolent crimes reported last year, four
fewer than in 1998. Those crimes are burglary, larceny, theft and
motor vehicle theft.
</P>
<P>
   -The number of reported rapes dropped to 27, from 33 in 1998,
the lowest number since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   -Two kinds of crime increased: aggravated assault was up
slightly (281, compared with 273 in 1998) and theft (7,338, up from
7,094 in 1998).
</P>
<P>
   -There were five murders in the city last year, compared with 14
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very pleased with the decrease in the crime statistics
and we will maintain our efforts and our operations toward the
continuing goal of reducing crime every year,'' said Police Chief
Arthur Snellbaker.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Atlantic City's streets, casinos and Boardwalk were
entirely safe places, either, though.
</P>
<P>
   One brazen bandit stole more than $60,000 in a rash of casino
robberies in April, May and June. Edmund Osei, 22, a part-time
dealer at Trump Taj Mahal, allegedly used a toy gun every time.
</P>
<P>
   In June, two German tourists complained about the smell in their
$36-a-night room at the Burgundy Motor Inn - only to learn, after
sleeping on it, that it contained the body of a murdered gambler.
Haila Gabr, 18, of Brooklyn, N.Y., is awaiting trial in the slaying
of Saul Hernandez, 64, of Queens, N.Y., whose body was stuffed into
a wooden frame that supported the mattress and box spring two days
before the couple checked in.
</P>
<P>
   In November, an off-duty Stafford Township police officer nearly
died after being stabbed during an altercation in a McDonald's
drive-thru. Herman Pharo, 24, survived stab wounds to the back and
chest in the incident. No arrests have been made.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Robert Bell, 46, of Atlantic City was shot to death
as he walked through the Stanley Holmes Village housing project.
Police say it was case of mistaken identity. Najee Marshall, 20, is
awaiting trial in the killing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
