<HEADLINE> 27 arrested for alleged crack, cocaine distribution  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - Twenty-seven people, including some of
Camden's top-level distributors of crack and cocaine, were arrested
in an early-morning raid Thursday, the U.S. Attorney's Office said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal, state, Camden County and local authorities made the
arrests, said U.S. Attorney Robert J. Cleary. More than 130 agents,
police officers and detectives carried out the raids. Most of the
suspects were arrested at their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Cleary said those arrested and some of their suppliers and
associates formed a network for distributing cocaine by the
kilogram in and around Camden. Some of the suspects also are
charged with distributing drugs in Pennsylvania and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests capped a 10-month investigation that included the
use of surveillance and wiretaps, Cleary said.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrested were among 34 people named in indictments that
were returned June 14 and unsealed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the suspects were charged with organizing the
distribution of or distributing more than five kilograms of cocaine
and more than 50 grams of crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Four were charged with distributing more than 500 grams of
cocaine, and three were charged with conspiring to possess and
distribute more than 500 grams of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, they face prison terms ranging from five years to
life, and fines up to $4 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
