<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Telemarketing Fraud, 206  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ELMIRA, N.Y. (AP) - A federal judge has shut down an Elmira
telemarketing company and given the Federal Trade Commission
permission to seize the company's records to investigate alleged
fraudulent practices.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC filed a civil lawsuit Monday in U.S. District Court in
Rochester against Navestar, owner Paul Navestad and Financial
Services Network USA Inc., a corporation doing business as
Borrowing Made Easier, Express Processing Center, FSN and Free Cash
Grants.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleges that the defendants misrepresented, through
mailings and Internet sites, how people can secure loans or grants
or receive refunds if they did not get the promised grants.
</P>
<P>
   Navestar reaches most of its clients through direct mailings.
</P>
<P>
   According to Financial Services Network USA Inc.'s Web site,
people can purchase a book for about $20 and learn how to obtain
grants and loans worth up to $95,000.
</P>
<P>
   Telesca's order said the defendants failed to comply with
federal telemarketing rules by receiving advance payment and
guaranteeing the buyer will receive the loan or extension of
credit.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Navestad said his client is merely selling books
over the internet and the judge's order squashes his First
Amendment right to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
