<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dispute Over Spanish TV, Olympics  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL FOY
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Olympic organizer Mitt Romney sought
Thursday to defuse a tiff with a Spanish-speaking television
station that offered to help recruit volunteers for the 2002 Winter
Games.
</P>
<P>
   John Terrell, president and general manager of Telemundo
stations in Salt Lake City and Ogden, said a Salt Lake Organizing
Committee executive told him, ''We only want (volunteers) who speak
English.''
</P>
<P>
   SLOC officials said they are looking for volunteers fluent in
more than one language, including English.
</P>
<P>
   ''I even offered to give them some advertising for free,''
Terrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Romney might take Terrell up on that. SLOC does most of its
advertising at NBC affiliate KSL-TV, an Olympic supplier that is
donating nearly $275,000 worth of advertising for the recruitment
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ''My understanding is they'd like to give us some free
advertising, just like KSL does. We're happy to run them,'' Romney
said of the Telemundo stations. ''But we are overwhelmingly focused
on value and keeping our costs down.''
</P>
<P>
   John Renteria, executive director of the Utah Hispanic Chamber
of Commerce, said Telemundo's Utah operation deserves a piece of
the SLOC advertising budget and that Romney's budget restraints
could be seen as discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   SLOC trustee Richard Velez said he will try to mediate the
dispute and has been working to organize a meeting of Olympic
officials and Hispanic media representatives
</P>
<P>
   Velez said SLOC's ''English-only'' rebuff was a
misunderstanding. Others say it could be a sign that
Mormon-dominated Utah is struggling to deal with diversity the
Olympics will bring.
</P>
<P>
   An early clash came over Utah's peculiar liquor laws. The
state's provincial image was burnished by Gov. Mike Leavitt's
latest appointment of a white male Mormon as state Olympic officer.
</P>
<P>
   SLOC's upper ranks include no minorities, and only three of 16
senior positions are held by women.
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt tapped another Mormon, Romney, to clean up the
organization after the Olympic bribery scandal broke with
revelations that Salt Lake bidders lavished cash, gifts, travel and
other inducements on International Olympic Committee members and
their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Telemundo's complaint recalled a mistake from the Atlanta
Olympics, when a New Mexico man was told foreigners couldn't buy
tickets for the 1996 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   When Wade Miller couldn't convince an Atlanta ticket agent that
New Mexico was part of the United States, he pleaded his case with
a supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told her I was calling from New Mexico and emphasized the
New,'' Miller said. ''She told me, 'Sir, New Mexico, old Mexico, it
doesn't matter. I understand it's a territory, but you still have
to go through your nation's Olympic committee.'''
</P>
<P>
   SLOC spokeswomen Caroline Shaw said the organization was
reaching out to Hispanic and other ethnic groups. One out of six
volunteers speak Spanish as a second language, she said.
</P>
<P>
   SLOC has enlisted 8,380 volunteers so far who speak a second
language besides English. Salt Lake will host 10 Spanish-speaking
nations in the Winter Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 2007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New search for clues in two decade-old Etan Patz case  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Police were searching for new evidence Thursday
in the case of a boy who vanished 21 years ago, and whose plight
thrust the issue of child disappearances to the forefront of
national consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Officers removed boxes, blue plastic barrels and large pieces of
metal from the former residence of the man suspected, but never
charged, in the 1979 disappearance of 6-year-old Etan Patz.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's a break in the case,'' said Stuart GraBois,
a former federal prosecutor who has remained deeply involved in the
investigation. ''I just think they're trying to see whether they
can come up with any piece of evidence that might further tie in
(Jose Antonio Ramos).''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, already in prison in Pennsylvania for sexually molesting
two boys in unrelated cases, has admitted he was with Etan the day
the boy vanished while walking from his parents' SoHo loft to a
school bus stop three blocks away. But prosecutors have never
collected enough evidence to charge him in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-eyed, shaggy-haired Etan's case helped put the faces of
missing kids on milk cartons and turned May 25 - the date Etan was
last seen - into National Missing Children's Day. His picture was
posted in 60 countries as part of a worldwide search.
</P>
<P>
   Police scoured for new clues Thursday in the basement of the
Lower East Side building where Ramos, a friend of a Patz baby
sitter, lived when Etan disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father, Stanley Patz, said he was contacted by police
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police are out there looking for forensic evidence,'' he
said in a brief telephone interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the search might help resolve his son's case, he
replied, ''I hope so. What else can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   GraBois, the former prosecutor, said he believes Etan is dead.
</P>
<P>
   A police official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said cops
hoped to find bone fragments or other DNA evidence that might tie
Ramos to Etan's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Another investigator said it appeared unlikely new evidence
would be found in the basement of the five-story building on East
Fourth Street and Avenue B.
</P>
<P>
   GraBois, who is now executive director of the New York District
Council of Carpenters Benefit Fund, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was still a federal prosecutor, we went down in the
basement and we searched as well,'' he said. ''I guess they want to
give it a shot again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
