<HEADLINE> Son follows Dad with a lifetime of perfect school attendance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   QUEENSBURY, N.Y. (AP) - Like father, like son.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from his dad, Jason Lanfair, 19, was honored
Wednesday after never missing a day of school from kindergarten
through 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Terry Lanfair, achieved a similar feat 33 years
earlier. Jason's achievement may have topped his father's, he
chided his dad, because the elder Lanfair lived within walking
distance of school, while Jason lived miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't get sick much,'' Jason told the Post Star of Glens
Falls. ''But perfect attendance is kind of a family tradition, and
I guess my father passed it down to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Attending each of 2,535 days of school over 14 years wasn't
easy, however, Jason recalled. Snowstorms and illness often
conspired to try to keep him out of school but Lanfair always found
a way to be in class.
</P>
<P>
   His academic career included one extra school year working
toward graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Excelling at woodworking in his Board of Cooperative Educational
Services curriculum, Jason has a job lined up at Manchester Wood
Inc. of Granville, which manufactures furniture and decorative
items for upscale retail enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Queensbury is 46 miles north of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
