<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court allows customers to sue GPU  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A state appeals court decided Wednesday
that businesses and residents can bring a class-action lawsuit
against GPU Energy to regain financial losses suffered during a
power outage last summer.
</P>
<P>
   About 100,000 customers were without power during a broiling
July Fourth weekend when two transformers at a Red Bank substation
failed.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruling means several hundred thousand plaintiffs
involved in the class-action suit can seek monetary damages in what
lawsuit attorney Frank Gaudio said is a ''precedent against utility
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In essence, what the court has said is that they can be held
liable for negligence, just like we can be held for negligence if
we are involved in an auto accident,'' said Gaudio, who is handling
the class-action suit. ''They are not immune from that kind of
claim.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his clients have losses ranging from $50 to $40,000.
Some clients include restaurant owners who were forced to throw
away spoiled food.
</P>
<P>
   It could take up to two years for the lawsuit to go before a
jury unless a settlement is reached, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gaudio said the outages were caused by the company's failure to
properly maintain its transformers and assess the amount of
electricity customers would need during the weekend when
temperatures hovered at and above 100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   GPU officials have said the two transformer failures were
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   GPU had argued that the Board of Public Utilities, the state
agency that set rates and regulates the industry, should hear the
customers' claims.
</P>
<P>
   The BPU conducted an investigation into the blackout, but said
its role is not to settle claims brought by individuals customers.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the Appellate Division of Superior Court
unanimously agreed with the BPU's decision because the agency
resolves only regulatory questions.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the utility customers should have their day in
court.
</P>
<P>
   ''The events in issue raise only ordinary questions of
negligence,'' states the decision written by Judge Michael Patrick
King and joined by Judges Philip Carchman and Steven Lefelt.
</P>
<P>
   When the case goes before a jury, it will have to determine
whether GPU acted reasonably and whether it breached its duty to
its customers. The appeals court said these issues are beyond the
BPU's scope.
</P>
<P>
   GPU spokesman Ron Morano said the BPU investigation found that
GPU provided safe and adequate service.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our point all around is that the board obtain primary
jurisdiction over this,'' Morano said. ''Although the board work is
done for the present, as the litigation goes forward, the parties
... should be mindful of additional areas that fall into the BPU's
expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   Morano would not reveal GPU's next move, but added: ''We are
continuing to study the opinion. It's an opinion that has many
points to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some 100,000 customers were affected by the power
outage last July Fourth weekend, a judged ruled in October that all
GPU customers in New Jersey could be members of the class-action
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Some 480,000 plaintiffs are members of the lawsuit, Gaudio said.
</P>
<P>
   GPU had already settled with Red Bank for money the borough lost
from labor costs responding to the power outages. Some 17,000 Red
Bank customers were affected in Red Bank during the blackout.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the GPU issued a report critical of the GPU and
other utility companies for creating mass confusion by not promptly
informing officials and customers of when and where blackouts would
occur.
</P>
<P>
   GPU officials have said the company will invest tens of millions
of dollars over the next two to three years to speed up new
projects and better withstand record demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-15-00 2025 </TRAILER>
