<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drunken Driving Standards Set  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate voted Thursday to set the
first-ever national blood alcohol standard for drunken driving and
to block administration attempts to reduce the hours truckers can
spend driving per day.
</P>
<P>
   The $54.7 billion spending bill to fund highway, rail, aviation
and Coast Guard programs in fiscal year 2001 would require states
to adopt a 0.08 percent blood alcohol content level as their legal
intoxication standard. Those failing to do so by 2004 would begin
losing part of their highway trust fund money.
</P>
<P>
   Currently 18 states and the District of Columbia have 0.08
limits for being legally drunk, while 32 states have less stringent
0.10 limits. The White House supports the 0.08 standard and has
urged Congress to make it federal policy.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton congratulated the Senate for passing the
measure, and strongly urged Congress to approve a final
transportation bill that includes it.
</P>
<P>
   ''This reasonable standard will save hundreds of lives and
prevent countless injuries each year and it should be put in place
across the country without further delay,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill, which passed 99-0, must still be reconciled
with the House transportation spending bill that passed last month.
The House bill does not contain the drunken driving provision, nor
the ban on proposed regulations that would revise 60-year-old rules
on trucker and bus driver operating hours.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, unlike its Senate counterpart, has language
barring the Transportation Department from studying whether it
should raise fuel efficiency standards for cars, light trucks and
sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., and Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
after urging the Senate to oppose the House ban, worked out a
compromise position with Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., and others
concerned about the effects of raised standards on the auto
industry.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed that in negotiations with the House, the Senate
position will be that the Transportation Department and the
National Academy of Sciences study fuel efficiency standards and
related issues such as vehicle safety, but that no new standards
will be promulgated without the approval of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The House, backed by the auto industry, has succeeded in
including the ban in the transportation bill since 1995, but Gorton
argued that with gas prices reaching record levels and the fuel
economy of new vehicles at the lowest point in two decades, it was
time to seriously study the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Congress in 1975 set the corporate average fuel economy, or
CAFE, standard, at 27.5 miles per gallon on new passenger cars and
20.7 mpg for light trucks. But with new fuel efficiency technology
and the popularity of SUVs, which must only meet the lower light
truck standards, there has been pressure from consumer groups and
the administration for a revision in the standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate attached the 0.08 drunken driving level to a highway
bill in 1998 but it didn't survive negotiations with the House. The
national standard is opposed by the restaurant and beverage
industries, which argue that drunken drivers involved in crashes
have an average blood alcohol content of 0.17, and a 0.08 law would
shift focus away from problem drinkers and toward social drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   But Mothers Against Drunk Driving (MADD), which has pushed for
the national law, say the risk of a fatal crash is 11 times greater
for a person with 0.08 blood alcohol content than for a
non-drinking driver.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., who has led the 0.08 campaign,
said the tougher standard would save 500 to 700 lives a year.
''We're talking about a life-saving opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department's proposed rules on trucking
operations would allow long-distance operators no more than 12
hours of driving in a 24-hour period, with a two-hour break within
the period. Current rules, adopted more than 60 years ago, say
drivers can be behind the wheel no more than 10 hours in a day,
followed by an eight-hour rest. But they can then drive the
remaining six hours in the day, adding up to 16 hours in a 24-hour
period.
</P>
<P>
   American Trucking Associations' senior Vice President Jim
Whittinghill said truckers support an update in the rules but
believe Transportation's plan would make the roads less safe
because they would force companies to hire more novice drivers and
operate during daylight hours when the roads are most crowded.
</P>
<P>
   ''The proposed rule just will not work in the real world,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Mackintosh of Advocates for Highway and Auto Safety said
his group feels the rules don't go far enough to help the 1,000
people expected to be killed this summer in large truck crashes --
one-third involving fatigued truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But to freeze the rule-making process ''and place it in
suspended animation for a year is not the right way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration, in a statement, said it ''strongly objects''
to the ban on rule making. ''We cannot reduce motor carrier
fatalities without addressing the problem of operator fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill also contains language barring the
administration from issuing any rollover safety rules for SUVs
until the National Academy of Sciences completes a proposed
nine-month study of alleged SUV rollover tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   The only person who didn't vote on the bill was Sen. Jay
Rockefeller, D-W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is S. 2720.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: MADD: http://www.madd.org
</P>
<P>
   American Beverage Institute: http://www.abionline.org
</P>
<P>
   American Truckers Associations: www.truckline.com
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for Highway and Auto Safety: http://www.saferoads.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 2033 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury awards $1.2 million to black officers transferred to 70th precinct </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A federal jury awarded $1.2 million in damages
Thursday to 22 city police officers and two sergeants, finding the
city failed to prove it had to transfer black officers to a
Brooklyn precinct to maintain peace after an officer tortured Abner
Louima.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Shira A. Scheindlin told the racially mixed
jury after the verdict was announced that the three-week trial had
featured a ''very important case'' and she was sure the verdict
would ''have very important consequences in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict provides for all 24 police employees in the case to
receive $50,000 for emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're quite surprised,'' said Lorna Goodman, a spokeswoman for
the city law office. She said the city had not yet decided whether
to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a lot of money out of the taxpayer's pocket for an
initiative that was meant to make the situation better and to
comply with the request of the community. In the end, the taxpayers
have to pay this,'' Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the police Commissioner Howard Safir's 1997 decision to
send black police employees to the 70th precinct in Brooklyn after
Louima was sodomized with a broken broomstick by a police officer
''was really a well meaning decision ... not a discriminatory
act.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict had possible ramifications for police departments
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Williams, president of the Police Foundation in
Washington, testified at the trial that the black skin of an
officer could be a resource at the disposal of police commissioners
during an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers and the police employees praised the Manhattan
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ''This sends a message to the police department that you can't
transfer people due to their race,'' said George Cerrone, an
attorney for the Sergeants Benevolent Association, a plaintiff in
the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In its closing argument earlier in the week, the city conceded
that the police employees were chosen by their skin color.
</P>
<P>
   City lawyer James Lemonedes told jurors the attack on Louima was
an event that ''was extraordinary, that was remarkable, that
definitely caused outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Safir responded to cries from the community for a police
force that better reflects the largely minority population.
</P>
<P>
   ''Race was a factor. We admit it,'' Lemonedes said. ''We
announce it. We proclaim it. That's exactly what was the primary
factor in these transfers, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the law permits such a transfer if there is a compelling
government interest and if the move fulfills a legal requirement to
be ''narrowly tailored'' to address the need.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was instrumental to there being no deaths, no bodily
injury, no property damage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Blessinger, a lawyer for two police sergeants who were
transferred to the precinct, said his clients were ''treated based
on their skin color and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Their skills were not factored into this employment
decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blessinger said one of his clients was subdued after the
transfer, but the other ''complained ... he was being treated as a
commodity''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall D. Trager, another PBA lawyer, said in his closing
argument that the officers and sergeants were subjected to insults
when they were sent to Brooklyn, both by fellow officers who
suspected they were sent to spy on them and by members of the
community who called them sellouts and ''Uncle Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   Trager said the case was ''simply a microcosm of a larger
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What's apparent from the defense in this case is that there
are still people, there are still municipalities who just don't get
it when it comes to racial issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said those municipalities promise prospective employees that
they do not discriminate and they follow all federal and state
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''They lead people to believe it's not about race. But then,
when the chips are down, you find out it is about race and suddenly
there are exceptions to the rule and race does matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
