<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Open Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Sergio Garcia didn't expect to be
the only guy wearing knickers Thursday in the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   After Payne Stewart was killed last year, Garcia and about four
or five other European players discussed wearing the old-style
pants to honor Stewart in the first round at Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   But the 20-year-old Spaniard was the only one who followed
through.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if they felt embarrassed or something,'' Garcia
said. ''I guess it shows the kind of people they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who wore knickers and tam o'shanter caps on the PGA
Tour, died along with five others in an October plane crash, about
four months after winning his second U.S. Open title.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was among the 40 players who attended a Wednesday morning
tribute to Stewart, hitting golf balls into the Pacific from the
18th fairway. Afterward, the youngster broke down in tears while
hugging Stewart's widow, Tracey.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did this because Payne was my friend,'' said Garcia, who
wore blue knickers and matching stockings. ''This is the least I
can do for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Garcia, the traditional garb didn't help his
game. He shot a 4-over 75, leaving himself 10 shots behind leader
Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The knickers) played well,'' Garcia said. ''I played bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   TIGER'S BALL: Maybe it's the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Woods shot a 6-under 65 in the opening round of the U.S. Open --
his first tournament since formally switching to the Nike Tour
Accuracy ball.
</P>
<P>
   Woods tested the ball during a tournament in Germany, finishing
third, and won the Memorial by five strokes when he used the ball
again. Afterward, he announced he would go with the Nike Tour
Accuracy for good, beginning at Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement ended a marketing conflict between Woods top
two golf sponsors -- Nike and Titleist -- that began last year when
Nike entered the ball market.
</P>
<P>
   Most players would be reluctant to change equipment before a
major tournament. Then again, Woods is not the normal player.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have to say that would be a mistake under normal
circumstances,'' Colin Montgomerie told reporters. ''Before you
write that down, let me finish. The 'under normal circumstances'
was the bit I was trying to get at. I believe Tiger won the
Memorial with that ball. Well, he's tested it, hasn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   SUTTON'S WILD RIDE: Hal Sutton pondered a visit to the
aquarium in nearby Monterey. Maybe he was trying to find a little
calm after a wild opening round at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton started off with an eagle at No. 1, holing an 8-iron from
136 yards, and birdied two of the next three holes as well.
</P>
<P>
   After three more birdies, countered by a lone bogey, he arrived
at the par-5 14th with a 6-under score. Unfortunately for Sutton,
his fortunes were about to change dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   His third shot, a pitching wedge from 120 yards, shot through
the green into the back rough, ''a horrendous lie,'' Sutton said.
His chip scooted off the other side of the green, forcing him to
chip again to within 6 feet of the cup. But he two-putted for a
double-bogey 7.
</P>
<P>
   ''What a weird day,'' he said. ''A lot of good, a lot of bad. I
guess that's U.S. Open stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton was asked about his plans for the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ''I may take my little girls to the aquarium,'' he said. ''I
think that would be a good thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   MICKELSON'S SAVE: Phil Mickelson, who lost last year's Open on
the 72nd hole, was on the verge of falling from contention in the
opening round this time.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson was at 3 over through 12 holes but wound up with an
even-par 71 after birdies on three of the last six. He was six
shots behind leader Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ''The way I played, an even-par score is very good,'' Mickelson
said. ''I was struggling to make birdies. I had a tough time
getting close enough to make many putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's got to catch a Tiger if he wants to win his first
major championship.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got to go out and shoot under par tomorrow,'' Mickelson
said. ''Tiger is playing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   OLLIE'S COMEBACK: Jose Maria Olazabal won't be punching any
walls at this year's U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time Masters champion fired a 1-under 70 in the opening
round at Pebble Beach, putting himself in position to make a run
for another major title.
</P>
<P>
   ''The course is difficult, but I played quite well today,'' said
Olazabal, who closed his round with a birdie putt at 18. ''I didn't
play extraordinarily well, but I kept it in the fairway most of the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after shooting a 5-over 75 in the first round of the
Open at Pinehurst, N.C., an irate Olazabal took a swing at a hotel
wall and wound up breaking his right hand. He was forced to
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   His hand healed, Olazabal put memories of that episode behind
him. These days, he's more concerned with a shaky driver.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't been hitting many fairways,'' he said. ''I played
quite well today, but I've got to improve on that. I need more
consistency off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   JESPER'S SHIRT: Jesper Parnevik, known for wearing flashy
colors, was easily visible Thursday -- even as a thick fog covered
Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish golfer wore a bright orange shirt on his way to an
opening-round 73.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was noticeable out there,'' said Tiger Woods, who played in
the same group. ''You could see him in the fog, that's for sure.
He's our beacon, so no one would hit into us.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how bright was Parnevik's shirt? He could be seen from the
fifth tee while standing on the seventh tee -- about 500 yards away
-- as the fog rolled in from Stillwater Cove.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   WOODS ON PAYNE: Saying he didn't want to dwell in the past,
Tiger Woods explained his absence from a tribute to the late Payne
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 golfers took part in an early morning ceremony
Wednesday, hitting balls into Carmel Bay in a scene reminiscent of
a 21-gun salute. But Woods and good friend Mark O'Meara decided to
practice instead.
</P>
<P>
   ''It all depends on how you are personally,'' Woods said. ''If
that's how you want to put closure to it, that's how you want to
put closure to it. I handle things a little differently.''
</P>
<P>
   After Stewart was killed in an October plane crash, Woods
attended a memorial service in Orlando, Fla., but was among the
players who declined to wear knickers at the final round of the
Tour Championship in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ''I figured I've gone all through it with the memorial
service,'' Woods said. ''I felt by going (to Wednesday's ceremony),
it would be more of a deterrent for me during the tournament,
because I don't want to be thinking about what transpired.
</P>
<P>
   ''Plus, Mark O'Meara is one of my best friends, and we both went
out and played. And he's known Payne longer. He felt the same way.
He felt that we've gone through it all before, and we don't need to
keep bringing it up, especially during a big week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
