<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protesters Battle Toronto Police  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Hurling paint and clumps of dirt, hundreds of
people protesting against poverty clashed with riot police outside
the Ontario legislature in downtown Toronto on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Several demonstrators and at least three police officers were
injured in the violence that lasted almost an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters tossed aside steel barricades shielding the front of
the legislature and a Molotov cocktail exploded in fire on the
building's steps, prompting riot police to charge the
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   As police -- some mounted on horseback -- tried to push back the
crowd, protesters heaved bricks, dirt, crumpled placards and cans
of paint at them. Some police officers clubbed protesters who
refused to move.
</P>
<P>
   One demonstrator was hospitalized with a head injury and others
sustained cuts, bruises and other minor injuries. The three
policemen had minor injuries. More than a dozen people were
detained.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, from a loose coalition that defends the rights
of the homeless and opposes cuts in social spending by the Ontario
government, had warned of possible violence before the
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter to Ontario Premier Mike Harris in March, the
Coalition Against Poverty said it would march on the legislature on
June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ''We intend to see mobilization against you and all you stand
for taken to a level that is powerful and disruptive enough that
your hateful government can no longer proceed with its agenda,''
the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, some protesters wore goggles or cardboard gas
masks, and others quickly grabbed any projectile available to hurl
at police when the clashes began.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy police chief Michael Boyd blamed the protesters for the
violence, saying: ''It's clear ... that there was a plan by some
people not to demonstrate peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   The protest began with a festive mood at a downtown park with
homeless people dancing, chanting and listening to speeches
critical of Ontario Premier Mike Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers blamed the Harris government for cutting spending on
social programs and marginalizing the poor to generate tax cuts for
the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today we came to resist and to fight, and to say what we want
now is housing,'' said Gaetan Heroux, a spokesman for the Ontario
Coalition Against Poverty. ''When we ask for more housing, they
build more jails.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
