<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private garages sue state over auto emissions test  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A group of private garages that invested
large sums to purchase enhanced auto emissions testing equipment
sued the state Thursday, alleging state officials are letting the
state's contractor off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor, Parsons Infrastructure and Technology, is being
allowed to use the state's old tailpipe test to measure car
emissions at select auto inspection stations to alleviate long
lines at stations that use the enhanced test.
</P>
<P>
   The private garages say Gov. Christie Whitman, and the
Departments of Transportation and Environmental Protection denied
their constitutional rights by forcing them to pay for and use the
more expensive enhanced equipment while letting Parsons off easy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor, DOT and DEP in January changed the rules of the
game for its contractor Parsons but not for the private inspection
facilities,'' Belleville garage owner Enzo Olivieri said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gordon, a lawyer representing the 200 garages that filed
suit, said they each invested about $50,000 in new equipment to
offer the enhanced test, which is designed to more accurately
measure pollutants to bring New Jersey in line with federal clean
air regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman in January scaled back the enhanced test at some of the
Parsons stations after the system suffered chronic problems, long
lines and faulty equipment following its start-up in December.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said the private garages have suffered a 7 percent loss
in business since some of the Parsons stations started offering the
easier test.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the group is seeking a public hearing on the
changeover, which it says is required by the 1995 state law that
ushered in the enhanced test.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report blamed the Whitman administration for looking
the other way in the months prior to the launching of Parsons' $500
million contract. The report said some state officials ignored or
squelched warnings that the contractor bungled the new system.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Commissioner James Weinstein Thursday said the
garage owners' lawsuit is misguided.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the garages that invested in the new
equipment are doing more tests than they did during a comparable
period last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We obviously disagree with these folks. If we go to court,
we're on firm ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a related note, Weinstein said that the federal Environmental
Protection Agency recently granted the state another month to
comply with clean air regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The state needed the extra time, until Aug. 1, to hire more
workers and establish appointment schedules for motorists to
decrease waiting times before completely changing over to the
enhanced test.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
