<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
War Breaks Out in Canadian Alliance Ranks Over Quebec
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- A battle royal has broken out in the Canadian
Alliance ranks over leadership candidate Tom Long's success in
Quebec, with some of Long's provincial organizers there accusing
rivals of intolerance toward Quebecers.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions exploded Thursday following reports that Long, an
Ontario Tory organizer, had signed up a whopping 2,800 members in
Quebec's Gaspe region -- currently held by a Bloc Quebecois MP.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers have been openly questioned by supporters of Long's
fellow candidates, with some privately suggesting memberships were
paid for.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jean Chretien and the federal Tories in the House
of Commons also took the opportunity to ridicule the Alliance over
the feat.
</P>
<P>
   Long's Quebec staff say they feel unfairly targeted by Canadian
Alliance officials, and are questioning whether they'll remain in a
party which they say shows open hostility toward Quebecers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a bit unfortunate that some people in the Alliance have
chosen to suggest that if we recruit in Quebec, there's always
something crooked about it,'' said organizer Frederic Loiselle.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Anti-Abortion Group set To Endorse Day For Leadership
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- One of Canada's largest anti-abortion groups is
preparing to endorse former Alberta treasurer Stockwell Day as
leader of the Canadian Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hughes, president of the Campaign for Life, said Thursday
that in response to many requests from members he will advise they
support Day.
</P>
<P>
   ''This'll be unusual for us, but there's a cry asking 'Just who
do we support here,' '' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'll tell members to choose Day first and former Reform
leader Preston Manning second.
</P>
<P>
   Day is vocal about his pro-life stance, and earlier this week
lashed out at two of his leadership rivals for shying away from the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Chenard Challenges Quebec's Language Laws
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Alain Chenard says he feels as if he lives in a
dictatorship because the Quebec government won't let his children
attend an English school.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to ensure his children can speak English, Chenard
and his wife joined 10 other predominantly francophone families
Thursday in a court challenge against sections of Quebec's language
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Court challenges against the language laws are usually by
anglophones seeking to protect their English rights.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether parents who have received the majority of
their schooling in French can send their children to Quebec's
English schools, which is prevented under the law.
</P>
<P>
   Children of anglophone parents educated in English in Quebec or
anywhere in Canada have access to English schools.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Chretien Defends Human Resources Minister Stewart
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Prime Minister Jean Chretien defended Human
Resources Minister Jane Stewart and her department Thursday in the
face of suggestions that he is thinking of demoting her and
breaking up the department.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the minister of human resources has done a great
job,'' Chretien told opposition MPs who taunted him in the Commons.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will keep defending the programs that have been put in
place by this government to help the poor, the people who need help
in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither Chretien in the House, nor Stewart in a later
interview with The Canadian Press, quite shut the door on a rumored
reorganization at Human Resources.
</P>
<P>
   A Liberal-dominated Commons committee recommended two weeks ago
that the problem-plagued department be split into three pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien has acknowledged the government is thinking about
whether to implement the recommendations but has also indicated
that, no matter what, Stewart will be at the cabinet table.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Report: More Workers Needed For the Environment
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- There may be fewer Fs this year, but the
environmental record of the provinces and federal government
shouldn't make anyone proud, says the Sierra Club of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report card, the watchdog group says environmental
protection isn't a priority across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The ability of Ottawa and the provinces to do anything has
declined because there are fewer staff to monitor and enforce laws
and do basic scientific research, said John Bennett, the
organization's director on energy and atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Ontario needs the most work, says the report. It failed in
biodiversity and climate change, mostly because it lacks
commitment, and budgets have been slashed, says Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   The provincial Ministry of Natural Resources was cut $85 million
this year alone, said the report card, and the Environment
Department budget is about 40 per cent to 50 per cent of what it
was five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate category, Nova Scotia got an F for efforts to
clean up the Sydney Tar Ponds, said the Sierra Club. The properties
border the former Sydney Steel coke ovens site, a blighted
landscape where toxins ooze from the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
