<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minnesota Wild To Play At 'The X'  </HEADLINE>
By ARNIE STAPLETON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Anaheim has The Pond. Minnesota now has
''The X.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL expansion Minnesota Wild said Thursday that their
multipurpose sports and entertainment arena will be named Xcel
Energy Center as part of a 25-year deal reportedly worth between
$75 million and $80 million with utility company Xcel Energy Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity for our company,''
said Jim Howard, president and CEO of Minneapolis-based Northern
States Power, which is merging with New Century Energies, of
Denver, to form Xcel Energy Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would reveal terms, but Xcel is expected to pay
about $3 million a year in cash and services to place its name on
the new $130 million arena.
</P>
<P>
   The entire fee for the naming rights will go directly to the
Wild, helping offset $3.5 million in annual rent the team is
required to pay to help the city and state recoup public funds used
to build the 18,600-seat arena, part of the RiverCentre complex.
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes a sweeping advertising partnership,
electricity costs, luxury suites and tickets.
</P>
<P>
   NSP and NCE announced merger plans last year with headquarters
in Minneapolis. Final approval of the merger is expected in July.
The new utility company will serve electric and gas customers in 12
states.
</P>
<P>
   The Xcel arrangement doesn't affect a 10-year, $2.25 million
naming rights deal struck last year between the RiverCentre and an
Xcel competitor, Touchstone Energy, the nation's largest consortium
of rural electrical cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
   The city provided $65 million in bonds to build the 18,600-seat
arena, and the state funded the other half of construction costs
with a $48 million interest-free loan and a $17 million grant made
in exchange for the Wild opening the arena for public events,
including the state high school hockey tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Wild begins play in the Northwest Division of the NHL's
Western Conference in October. The team is preparing for next
week's expansion and entry drafts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 2113 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
