<DOCNO> APW20000615.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Says Plan Would Ensure Coverage  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans said Thursday their plan for
prescription drug insurance for the elderly envisions federal
financial incentives to insurance companies to make sure coverage
is available nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've tried to allow as much flexibility with this ... to
accommodate any scenario that we might be able to run into,'' said
Rep. Richard Burr, R-N.C., among the architects of the GOP plan.
</P>
<P>
   A new draft summary of Republican legislation being prepared for
House action -- possibly as soon as next week -- offered no details
about how much such incentive payments might cost. But Burr and
other authors of the bill said they believed private coverage could
be guaranteed everywhere in the country within the $40 billion
Republicans have budgeted over five years to create a new Medicare
drug benefit for retirees.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials were unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you say that you're going to hold out resources until plans
come in ... it becomes a highly expensive, extremely inefficient
way to provide coverage,'' said White House health care adviser
Chris Jennings. ''And most importantly ... it certainly doesn't
ensure affordability to the beneficiary.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has proposed a standard drug benefit under
Medicare, adding prescriptions to other health care services
covered by the program if retirees choose to pay an additional
monthly premium -- about $50 a month once coverage is fully phased
in.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, House Republicans would enlist private insurers to
sell government-subsidized and approved prescription drug insurance
policies to Medicare beneficiaries -- in much the same way as the
program now contracts with HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has questioned how the Republican plan would guarantee
that insurance companies would step up to offer the new drug
policies -- especially in rural areas with low populations -- and
keep them affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry leaders also say that drug-only insurance
policies for the elderly, who have the highest medicine costs of
any age group, might not be workable.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have promised that the government would act as the
''insurer of last resort'' if insurance companies did not come on
board. New details of their plan, released Thursday, explained that
to mean that the government would provide incentive payments, in
effect taking on some of the companies' financial risks, if
necessary, to attract them.
</P>
<P>
   The incentive payments would be on top of a standard government
subsidy that all participating insurance companies would get.
</P>
<P>
   Under the emerging GOP plan, costs paid by senior citizens would
vary, but insurance companies would have to provide drug benefits
of at least the same value as a standard plan set by law.
</P>
<P>
   The standard plan would have a $250 deductible, then 50-percent
copayments for the first $2,100 in total prescriptions annually. At
that point, coverage would end for the year unless total drug costs
surpassed $6,000. Then, ''catastrophic'' coverage would kick in,
paying all remaining bills for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Talking points distributed to the House Republican rank and file
by party leaders this week show they intend to try to draw several
distinctions between their approach and Clinton's. Among these:
</P>
<P>
   --The GOP plan will not be ''one-size-fits all,'' the talking
points said. ''We give seniors more options to choose the drug
coverage that best fits their needs, rather than just one
government-administered benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   --Also, all private drug insurance policies under the GOP plan
would have to have catastrophic coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Democrats have said they want to add a similar
feature to their plan, but it currently calls for benefits capped
at $2,500 annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 2115 </TRAILER>
