<DOCNO> APW20000615.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Neil Simon Hits Featured  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- No need to travel to Bucks County, Ogunquit,
Cape Cod or other once-famous stops along the East Coast
summer-theater circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Lightweight, hot-weather fare, the kind of comedy once known as
''frothy,'' lives right in Manhattan, where the Roundabout Theater
Company is presenting ''Hotel Suite,'' a collection of Neil Simon's
greatest hits.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the evening is a compilation of one-acts from each of
Simon's ''Suite'' plays -- ''Plaza Suite,'' ''California Suite'' and
''London Suite.'' And ''frothy'' may be too kind an adjective to
apply to these Simon snippets, some of which haven't worn
particularly well, particularly in this skimpy and undercast
production.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the evening's four sketches are from ''California
Suite,'' which originally opened on Broadway in 1976. The
curtain-raiser concerns Diana, a boozy British actress in Los
Angeles for the Academy Awards, and her gay husband Sidney, who
works as an antique dealer in London.
</P>
<P>
   The playlet consists mostly of snide comments about the Oscars --
from the clothes the women wear to the morose, deadly behavior of
the losers after the ceremony. Between the caustic observations,
Diana and Sidney snipe at each other, particularly about Sidney's
sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Carey and Leigh Lawson don't have an easy time with the
banter, which often misfires. It doesn't help that the characters
are vaguely unpleasant, too.
</P>
<P>
   Diana and Sidney make another appearance in Act 2, this time in
a scene from ''London Suite,'' originally done off-Broadway in
1995. By now, Diana is a hugely successful television star with her
own hit series and Sidney is living on a Greek island with his male
lover. Their animosity and affection for each other are still
there, only now Diana has the upper hand as Sidney comes to ask a
favor.
</P>
<P>
   The two performers do better in this more sober, somber section.
Their characters are more fully developed, and the laughs come out
of the people, not Simon's eagerness to crack another joke.
</P>
<P>
   The two remaining plays are out-and-out farces. In the second of
the two ''California Suite'' pieces, a Philadelphia businessman
wakes up to find himself in bed with a nearly comatose prostitute.
With his wife arriving any minute, the man must do something to
hide this raunchy sleeping beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Orbach has the desperation down exactly right as the
more-than-harried husband, and Randy Graff comically nails the
wife's justified outrage.
</P>
<P>
   The actors are less successful in the evening's final offering,
the last section of ''Plaza Suite,'' which originally opened on
Broadway in 1968. In it, Orbach and Graff play frantic parents
whose daughter locks herself in the bathroom of a hotel room --
right before the wedding -- and refuses to come out. They do
everything except dynamite the door to get her back to the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Farce is a delicate commodity. It can't be forced. In this
sketch, the actors push too hard, straining for laughs that lose
their effectiveness when the audience sees them sweat -- and mug.
</P>
<P>
   Director John Tillinger keeps thing moving at a reasonable clip,
although he should have hired a better decorator for this parade of
expensive guest rooms. Designer James Noone's meager settings look
more bargain-basement than high-end luxury, not the kind of
accommodations one would expect for people used to staying in
''Hotel Suites.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 2138 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
