<HEADLINE> Utility will pay for puppy's surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MONTICELLO, N.Y. (AP) - After a wave of support for an injured
puppy, New York State Electric and Gas has agreed to pay for hip
surgery for the dog hit by one of the utility company's vehicles
last week.
</P>
<P>
   After the accident, NYSEG said it would pay the $666 medical
bill plus $700 for the original cost of the German shepherd puppy
and whatever it would cost to put her to sleep. It declined to pick
up what was originally estimated at $2,500 for hip surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Carol McEneaney refused the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sabine, the Liberty area NYSEG representative, called
McEneaney Wednesday, saying the company had reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
   The puppy's plight gained national attention. A Binghamton TV
station interviewed Carol McEneaney and Inside Edition offered to
film Thursday's trip to Oradell, an animal hospital in New Jersey.
A Monticello lawyer volunteered his services if the McEneaney's
decided to sue the utility.
</P>
<P>
   Callers across the country told the McEneaneys they would
contact NYSEG and tell it to reconsider. Many callers offered to
donate money for Shera's vet bills, if NYSEG still refused.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine called McEneaney yesterday morning, offering to
personally deliver a check for the surgery. He called back later,
saying NYSEG would pay her $1,600, which was the fee the hospital
quoted, McEneaney said. NYSEG will also pick up her travel costs.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-month-old dog was hit last Wednesday by the meter reader's
truck as it left the family's driveway.
</P>
<P>
   McEneaney said she had opened the garage door to get out toys
for her two small daughters when her two dogs ran out to the truck.
The puppy didn't make it past the vehicle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
