<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ's Gomez Named Top NHL Rookie  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Scott Gomez, who led all first-year players in
points and helped the New Jersey Devils win the Stanley Cup, won
the Calder Trophy as the NHL's outstanding rookie Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, 20, the first NHL player from Alaska, had 70 points (19
goals, 51 assists). He was New Jersey's second choice, 27th
overall, in the 1998 draft and moved up from juniors to a regular
spot with the Devils this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was an amazing script,'' said Gomez. ''I couldn't have
imagined it any better in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez was given his award by actor Christopher Reeve, who is
paralyzed, and Reeve's 8-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an honor to be up here with Mr. Reeve and his son, he
shows what courage is about,'' said Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez is the second Devil to win the Calder. Goaltender Martin
Brodeur won it in 1994 in voting by members of the Professional
Hockey Writers' Association.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have won the Calder three of the last four years.
Colorado's Chris Drury got it last year and Bryan Berard got it in
1997, when he was with the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh wing Jaromir Jagr, the league's leading scorer, won
his second straight Lester B. Pearson award from the NHL Players'
Association as the top player. He also was a finalist for the Hart
Trophy, to be awarded later Thursday night to the league's most
valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Pronger of the St. Louis Blues won the Norris Trophy as
best defenseman, while his boss, Joel Quenneville, took the Adams
as top coach.
</P>
<P>
   Pronger, at 25 the youngest winner in 15 years, succeeded
teammate Al MacInnis in winning the Norris. They are the only two
Blues to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ''A special thanks to Al MacInnis, who helped guide my career
when it looked like it was going nowhere,'' said Pronger, who led
the league in plus-minus raings at plus-52.
</P>
<P>
   The Adams, given by the NHL Broadcaster's Association, went to
Quenneville after he led the Blues to a league-best 51-20-11-1
record. The Blues also allowed a league-low 165 goals.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Steve Yzerman, whose transformation from sharpshooter
to complete player helped the Detroit Red Wings win the Stanley Cup
in 1997 and 1998, won the Selke Trophy as the NHL's best defensive
forward. Yzerman twice scored more than 60 goals in a season, and
five times had more than 50, but Detroit didn't win until he
committed equal effort to both ends of the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Ken Daneyko, who has appeared in every one of New
Jersey's postseason games, took the Masterton Trophy for
perserverance and dedication to hockey. Daneyko has overcome an
alchohol problem to appear in 1,000 NHL games.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hockey has been the one constant in my life. That's what I'm
most proud of,'' he said. ''I never expected this, but it certainly
caps off a nice year after winning the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto goalie Curtis Joseph was given the King Clancy Memorial
Trophy in honor of his humanitarian work. Joseph started a program
called Cujo's Kids that helps critically ill children at the
Hospital for Sick Children.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis forward Pavol Demitra got the Lady Byng Trophy for
gentlemanly play.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr, Yzerman and Pronger made the 2000 All-Star Team, along
with Detroit winger Brendan Shanahan and Red Wings defenseman
Nicklas Lidstrom, and Washington goalie Olaf Kolzig.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Turek of St. Louis, not Kolzig, was the Jennings Trophy
winner for lowest goals-against average. And Florida's Pavel Bure
received the Maurice Richard Trophy for most goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 2141 </TRAILER>
