<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ambassador in Peru Clarifies Remark  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- The United States still considers Peru's
presidential election ''profoundly defective,'' U.S. Ambassador
John Hamilton said late Thursday, clarifying comments he made
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto Fujimori was re-elected for a third, five-year
term May 28 after his challenger dropped out, claiming the
balloting was tainted.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we have said repeatedly, we continue to consider the
elections profoundly defective. The electoral process did not meet
international standards of transparency and democracy,'' Hamilton
said in a statement sent to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton told reporters at a trade show earlier Thursday that
Washington would respect the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe it is the position of our government to respect the
decisions of national authorities and our expectation, of course,
is that the president will be sworn in on July 28,'' he told the
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   That comment appeared to represent a shift from the stated U.S.
position -- that it would reserve judgment on the validity of
Fujimori's victory.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamilton's later clarification reaffirmed that the Clinton
administration still did not accept the victory.
</P>
<P>
   In his clarification, he said Washington will decide whether to
recognize Fujimori's win after it sees how he responds to a mission
from the Organization of American States, which is due to arrive
here at the end of the month to work on strengthening Peru's
democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Administration has said it has not ruled out
sanctions against Peru after the OAS rebuffed Washington's call to
question Fujimori's victory and consider collective action against
the Andean nation.
</P>
<P>
   Former presidential candidate Alejandro Toledo boycotted the May
28 presidential runoff, saying it was rigged, and has vowed to
prevent Fujimori's inauguration before Congress with massive street
protests.
</P>
<P>
   During his 10-year presidency, Fujimori has become Washington's
strongest regional ally in fighting narcotics trafficking. Peru
currently receives $177 million in military, anti-narcotics and
humanitarian aid, according to the U.S. Embassy in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   But relations with the authoritarian leader were strained by an
election campaign riddled with irregularities and allegations of
government fraud.
</P>
<P>
   A delegation from the OAS refused to monitor the May 28 vote,
saying the election was ''far from what could be considered free or
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The OAS agreed to send its secretary general, Cesar Gaviria, and
Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy to Peru to work
with Fujimori's government to improve its democratic institutions.
They are scheduled to arrive June 27.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
