<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Seeks Congo Peacekeepers  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. envoy to Congo asked the Security
Council on Thursday to send 250 peacekeepers to a Congolese city to
fill a void left by the withdrawal of Rwandan and Ugandan forces.
</P>
<P>
   Kamel Morjane said his appeal was a ''specific and exceptional
measure'' to allow U.N. peacekeepers to provide security after the
pullout of the two rival armies, which turned their guns on each
other in the city of Kisangani earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any vacuum could be very dangerous, especially for the future
of the whole process -- not only for Kisangani,'' Morjane told a
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda entered Congo's war nearly two years ago, as
allies supporting rebels who wanted to topple President Laurent
Kabila from power. They say they are in Congo to protect their
borders from their own rebels, which they say have used Congo as a
base.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came as the council hosted Congo's warring parties
at the start of a two-day meeting originally meant to move the
country's peace process forward. Instead, the focus has turned to
negotiations over keeping the peace in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no excuse for what happened in Kisangani,'' U.S.
Ambassador Richard Holbrooke told the council, which included the
foreign ministers of Rwanda, Uganda and Congo -- as well as
representatives from the country's main rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Rwandan and Ugandan forces fought pitched
battles in Kisangani, even after agreeing to U.N. cease-fires and a
withdrawal from the strategic city. The fighting left as many as
300 people dead, U.N. officials and diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting ended Sunday after Rwandan forces drove the
Ugandans out of the city's northern sector and let unarmed U.N.
military observers deploy between the two former allies.
</P>
<P>
   Morjane said even 200 more observers couldn't maintain security
in Kisangani and that a full-fledged battalion of armed
peacekeepers -- of about 700 soldiers -- would be required for the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the difficulty in rounding up troop contributions, he
appealed for at least two companies of about 120 soldiers apiece to
be sent to Kisangani quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction from the 15-member council noted that a significant
troop increase for Kisangani had been envisaged previously.
However, a draft resolution being negotiated on the sidelines of
the two-day Congo meetings wouldn't contain any new mandate
requirements for the U.N. force.
</P>
<P>
   The council already considering a draft resolution demanding
that Rwanda and Uganda immediately withdraw from Kisangani and
eventually from the rest of the country, and for other foreign
forces to also leave. Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia have backed
Kabila in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   France, which holds the presidency of the Security Council this
month and is hosting the Congo parties, hopes the resolution will
be adopted by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal of the foreign forces from Congo is supposed to
be supervised by a 5,537-strong U.N. force of observers and troops
to protect them. So far, just 228 members of the force have been
deployed in Congo and in liaison offices in neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   In a report earlier this week, Secretary-General Kofi Annan said
none of the conditions had been met for the U.N. deployment to go
ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 2150 </TRAILER>
