<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CHRO to investigate Virginia prison  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Members of the state Commission on Human
Rights and Opportunities voted Thursday to investigate allegations
that Connecticut inmates held at a Virginia prison have been
subjected to mistreatment and racism.
</P>
<P>
   In an official complaint to be filed with the Connecticut
Department of Corrections, the CHRO said it would investigate
allegations that the overwhelmingly white prison staff has hurled
racial insults at inmates, beat them, and denied access to lawyers
and religious services.
</P>
<P>
   The probe could include a visit to Wallens Ridge prison and the
issuing of subpoenas, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issue is one of courage,'' said Roger Vann, a commissioner
who is also president of the state chapter of the NAACP. ''We as an
agency need to stand up for human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission also voted to force Virginia officials to comply
with Connecticut's contract compliance laws if the prison transfer
contract is renewed.
</P>
<P>
   CHRO staff last fall had approved the exemption from
Connecticut's contract compliance laws, saying the move was routine
for an out of state service. But one commissioner, Benjamin Rhodes,
said the exemption approval appeared to be done in a ''hush-hush''
manner.
</P>
<P>
   Those laws would require Virginia authorities to send reports on
the racial makeup of its staff to Connecticut officials.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Andrew Norton, sided with a staff report that said
an investigation would be premature. He said reports of
discrimination have not been substantiated, and that allegations of
mistreatment frequently arise in prisons.
</P>
<P>
   The worst incident, he said, involved the suicide in April of
David Tracy, a white prisoner. That happened just weeks after three
Connecticut inmates were wounded by guards who shot them with
rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the inmates, including Tracy's siblings, spoke
against the prison before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the commission heard evidence from Connecticut
Corrections Commissioner John Armstrong, who said the racial makeup
of the prisoner group sent to Wallens Ridge, reflected the racial
makeup of Connecticut's overall prison population.
</P>
<P>
   Correction Department spokeswoman Capt. Heather Ziemba said the
department would cooperate with the CHRO investigation. But she
said some of the issues being raised were answered by Armstrong
during his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the commissioner put it very well when he explained
that the pool of possible staff down there are limited as far as
racial diversity because of the nature of the people that live in
the area,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Pagani, Gov. John G. Rowland's spokesman, said CHRO was
entitled to conduct its own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Connecticut Department of Corrections regularly monitors
conditions at the Wallens Ridge facility and feels that the
facility meets all standards,'' Pagani said. ''The commissioner of
corrections would never have signed a contract if he had any
question in his mind that the inmates would be put at risk in any
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach officials with the Virginia Department of
Corrections were not successful. Messages were left for department
spokesman Larry Traylor at his home and office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
