<HEADLINE> Earthquake Jolts Southern Japan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A strong earthquake shook southern Japan Thursday
night, but there were no immediate reports of damage or injuries,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The 5.7-magnitude temblor was centered in the Pacific sea bed
east of Amami Oshima island, about 800 miles southwest of Tokyo,
the Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no danger of tsunami, powerful waves stirred up by
undersea disturbances such as earthquakes, it said.
</P>
<P>
   A magnitude 5-level quake can cause damage to homes if it occurs
in a residential area. Japan is one of the world's most
earthquake-prone countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
