<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arsenal gets howitzer deal from Navy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATERVLIET, N.Y. (AP) - The nation's oldest active maker of big
guns has won a multimillion dollar contract from the U.S. Navy to
build more than 700 howitzers over the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The Watervliet Arsenal faced an uncertain future and potential
job cuts before the contract to produce 723, 155mm cannons was
awarded. By winning the contract, as many as 139 jobs will be
retained, U.S. Sen. Charles E. Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   The contract to build the 723 guns is worth about $1 billion but
a spokesman for Schumer said the arsenal's portion of the job would
be worth ''in the tens of millions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The arsenal built during the War of 1812 employs about 670
people. It competed against an arsenal in Kentucky to win the bid.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without this contract, the arsenal would not have survived,''
Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an important first step in building a bright future
for the Watervliet Arsenal,'' said U.S. Rep. Michael McNulty,
D-Green Island. ''Hopefully, this will be followed by good news
with regard to the joint venture by General Dynamics, United
Defense Limited Partnership and British Aerospace.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, those three defense companies made an unsolicited
proposal to take over the gun plant. Army officials have begun
negotiations with the companies.
</P>
<P>
   The arsenal had about 4,000 workers in 1989. Because the arsenal
isn't supported with tax dollars, it must survive on what it sells
- and the country isn't using as many big guns as it used to.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the guns made there are currently sold to allies.
Work orders there have dropped from $164 million in 1994 to about
$86 million in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
