<HEADLINE> Japan's Empress Dowager in Coma  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Empress dowager Nagako, the elderly widow of
Japan's late Emperor Hirohito, fell into a coma Friday after
suffering from breathing difficulties, the Imperial Household
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Toshio Yuasa, vice grand steward of the Imperial Household, said
Nagako, 97, fell into a coma Friday morning after her blood
pressure dropped. She had been suffering from breathing problems
since early Thursday and was using an oxygen mask.
</P>
<P>
   Nagako was being treated at a medical facility on the grounds of
the Imperial Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Television footage showed Emperor Akihito, Nagako's eldest son,
Empress Michiko, Crown Prince Naruhito and Crown Princess Masako
arriving at the building where she was being treated.
</P>
<P>
   Nagako married Hirohito in 1924, and they had seven children.
Hirohito, who began his reign in 1926, died on January 7, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Nagako became Japan's longest-living empress dowager in 1995,
surpassing Empress Kanshi, who died in 1127.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
