<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela State Low on Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A Venezuelan state devastated by
mudslides in December must freeze its reconstruction efforts due to
insufficient funding, the state's governor said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on local radio, Alfredo Laya said his state government
had ''collapsed'' from lack of money from the central government.
</P>
<P>
   The statement came six months after the Dec. 15 disaster, in
which intense rains sent avalanches of earth, rocks and water onto
northern coastal towns along the Caribbean Sea, killing thousands
of people.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Vargas bore the brunt of the damage. Government
figures released this week revealed that 15,000 people in Vargas
disappeared in the slides, and are presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in Caracas Thursday, President Hugo Chavez
defended the government's progress in Vargas and disputed Laya's
claim that there were insufficient resources to continue
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not let this (the rebuilding) stop,'' Chavez said,
adding that it's been ''impossible'' to work with Laya or ''to
coordinate any type of action.'' Laya's political party, Fatherland
For All, recently broke away from Chavez's leftist governing
coalition in a highly publicized dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said most inhabitants of Vargas already have access to
schools, sports fields, ample food and medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Laya said the construction stoppage would leave 10,000 people in
temporary camps without permanent housing.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 people were left homeless by December's
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, who assumed power 16 months ago promising a ''social
revolution,'' announced in March a dlrs 1.2 billion dollar program
to rebuild roads, schools, tourist centers and other facilities in
Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, much of Vargas remains in disarray. The
government has built few new homes and has barely begun work on a
key coastal highway destroyed by the mudslides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
