<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks Activate Stottlemyre  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Todd Stottlemyre, activated from the disabled
list Thursday, gave up a pair of home runs and a double during his
first six pitches in Arizona's game against Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hollandsworth, playing for the first time since missing 10
games with a strained hamstring, homered to left-center on
Stottlemyre's first pitch of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek doubled two pitches later and Gary Sheffield
followed with a homer to center field on a 1-1 delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre hadn't pitched since May 29 against St. Louis, when
he was forced out of the game after 5 1-3 innings because of
tendinitis in his right elbow and placed on the disabled list for
the fourth time in his 13-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre entered Thursday's game with an 8-3 record and a
4.38 ERA. It was his 21st start since a significant tear in his
rotator cuff last May.
</P>
<P>
   To make room, the Diamondbacks optioned slumping outfielder
Turner Ward to Triple-A Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, 35, hit .173 in 15 games with four RBIs for the
Diamondbacks, his fifth major league team.
</P>
<P>
   After spending two months in the minors last season rehabbing
from an injured right knee, the 11-year veteran switch-hitter was
recalled in September and hit three pinch home runs -- including
two-run shot in Game 3 of the division series against the New York
Mets.
</P>
</TEXT>
