<HEADLINE> Mexican Candidate Withdraws  </HEADLINE>
By TRACI CARL
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- One of Mexico's six presidential candidates
formally withdrew from the race Thursday, throwing his support
behind the leading opposition candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Porfirio Munoz Ledo came as the campaign continued
to heat up ahead of the July 2 election, with opposition candidates
accusing the party that has governed for 71 years of pressuring
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Most polls show Vicente Fox of the opposition National Action
Party and Francisco Labastida of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, in one of the tightest races in
Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz Ledo, a former president of both the PRI and the leftist
Democratic Revolution Party, had been the candidate of the small
Authentic Party of the Mexican Revolution, or PARM.
</P>
<P>
   He had already infuriated that party's leaders by calling for a
united front against the PRI behind Fox and asking prosecutors to
investigate drug allegations against his own party's president.
</P>
<P>
   The Authentic party voted last month to ask him to step down,
and on Thursday he presented a formal resignation to the Federal
Electoral Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz Ledo has agreed to serve on Fox's transition team if the
National Action candidate is elected.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed the Mexican people were ready for change,
and he encouraged PARM supporters to vote for Fox instead. ''If
everyone does this, the Mexican transition would be much easier,
faster and efficient,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While officials say the current election will be the fairest in
Mexican history, and the first run by an independent electoral
agency, complaints have mounted about PRI pressure on voters.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the candidate running a distant third, Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas, said the vote should be annulled if it is not free and
fair. Many Mexicans believe Cardenas was cheated out of the
presidency by widespread fraud in the 1988 election.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, however, rejected the possibility of a second
election, insisting that the system is ''fraud-proof.''
</P>
<P>
   In two states, opposition parties say they have found PRI
warehouses stocked with pre-election gifts such as bicycles and
sewing machines.
</P>
<P>
   Some also have accused the PRI of collecting voting credential
numbers at the same time the government dispenses aid.
</P>
<P>
   Civic Alliance, a nonpartisan group that campaigns for fair
elections, distributed copies of a letter allegedly written by an
official in the southern state of Chiapas ordering government
employees to attend ruling-party campaign rallies and paying for
the bus to get them there.
</P>
<P>
   The government and PRI have repeatedly denied pressuring voters
or offering bribes.
</P>
<P>
   Two other candidates, Manuel Camacho of the Democratic Center
Party and Gilberto Rincon Gallardo of the Social Democratic Party,
are also contesting the election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 2240 </TRAILER>
