<HEADLINE> Authorities seize drugs from Wyeth distribution center  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) - Federal authorities seized a small
quantity of vaccines and antihistamines Thursday from a
Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories' distribution center because of problems
with the way they were made.
</P>
<P>
   The quantity of drugs seized by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration at the company's distribution center in Vonore,
Tenn., would fill less than a pallet, said Doug Petkus, a spokesman
for the Philadelphia-based company.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers supporting a warrant for the seizure said Wyeth's
operations could not assure the drugs met safety requirements in
strength, quality and purity.
</P>
<P>
   Seized were vaccines for tetanus and diphtheria, and two
antihistamines - Dimenhydrinate for motion sickness and Phenergan
to treat allergies.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs were produced at the company's Marietta, Pa.,
facility, which has been ''undergoing substantial improvements for
several months in response to FDA concerns,'' Petkus said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is important to note (the plant) ... has not been
manufacturing any product for shipment during that time,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   FDA spokeswoman Susan Cruzan said the company was warned last
year and again after an inspection this year of ''good practice
violations.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories is a division of Madison, N.J.-based
American Home Products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
