<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Sees Two Cities in One  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton took a tale-of-two-cities
tour of Washington on Thursday and found signs of hope in each.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the poorest neighborhoods, where barbed wire stands
guard around empty lots, Clinton celebrated the growth of an
after-school learning center called the U.S. Dream Academy where
children, some with parents in prison, use the Internet to connect
with knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ''What you do for these children, someone should do for every
child in the United States,'' Clinton told parents, administrators
and some excited but restless youngsters. ''This works.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was on to a neighborhood beyond most people's dreams,
and a great stone home where people contributed at least $10,000
each to rub shoulders briefly with him and other luminaries in a
fund-raising event for Mayor Anthony Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love this place,'' Clinton said of the city so many
politicians disparage as the antithesis of real America -- and the
one he will leave when his presidency is over.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've seen it at its best and worst and in between.''
</P>
<P>
   He was speaking not of his evening's travels in his motorcade
but historically. As a college student here, he witnessed the riots
in the aftermath of Martin Luther King's assassination, a period
followed by many tough years and now at least a tentative sense
that the city is picking up under its low-key Democratic mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The event was held two years before Williams is up for
re-election, at the mansion of Beth Dozoretz, former finance
chairman of the Democratic National Committee. Some of the city's
most influential Democratic and Republican political leaders paid
$2,000 and raised at least $8,000 to attend, testifying to
bipartisan support for the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Bob Dole, the former Republican senator and
Clinton's opponent in the last presidential election. It was the
second time in a week Dole and Clinton had appeared together at
Democratic fund-raising events; the last was for another Dole
friend, Sen. Christopher Dodd of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, a Washington resident since 1973, said he voted for
Williams' Republican opponent but ''that's all history now.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I see a lot of changes for the better now,'' he said, a point
echoed by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But Dole noted the city has been having a problem with exploding
manhole covers.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Williams raked in some $862,000 and made the large
boast that in the last four months, no one has had to wait more
than 20 minutes at the Department of Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Before, he said, ''you had to book a hotel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
