<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Sox 12, Yankees 3  </HEADLINE>
By BEN WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Chuck Knoblauch made three more throwing errors
and the Chicago White Sox took advantage, pounding the New York
Yankees 12-3 Thursday night in a matchup of teams with the AL's
best records.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Konerko and Brook Fordyce each had three hits and three
RBIs as Chicago, coming off a three-game sweep at Cleveland, won
for the 13th time in 15 games. Magglio Ordonez added a two-run
homer.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox, who have the league's top mark at 41-24, lead the
AL Central by 5{ games -- their biggest edge since the end of the
1993 season.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, a Gold Glove winner in 1997, made three errors in a
game for the first time in his career and they led to two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's third error came in the sixth, and when the Yankees
made a pitching change later in the inning, he stood motionless at
his position -- hands on his hips and staring straight ahead. The
other New York infielders gathered behind the mound while the
outfielders talked in dead center.
</P>
<P>
   When the inning ended, Knoblauch trotted in to the dugout and
headed toward a tunnel leading to the clubhouse. He appeared to
motion to manager Joe Torre, who followed him.
</P>
<P>
   Torre came back alone moments later, and Knoblauch left the
game. Knoblauch has missed several games this year because of a
sore left forearm.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a taped scoreboard quiz that was to feature Knoblauch was
scrapped. Instead, one showing Tino Martinez was substituted.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch has 12 errors this season after making a
league-leading 26 last year. Recently, he said he might retire if
his throwing problems persisted.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch became the first Yankees player to make three errors
in a game since third baseman Scott Brosius on Aug. 4, 1998. The
last Yankees second baseman to commit three was Mariano Duncan on
May 1, 1996, according to the Elias Sports Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox have made an AL-leading 63 errors, but this time
found a team that had more trouble in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sirotka (6-5) won despite giving up 10 hits in 5 2-3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte (6-3), pitching on his 28th birthday, had won four
straight starts. He also had been 6-0 against the White Sox at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch made a wild throw that did not hurt New York in the
third. Konerko's solo homer in the fourth put Chicago ahead 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Konerko hit a two-run double in the fifth for a 4-3 lead and he
scored on Knoblauch's bad throw with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch threw away a double-play relay in the sixth that would
have ended the inning, and Chicago scored again for a 6-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Fordyce had an RBI single in the seventh and a two-run double in
the eighth. Ordonez homered in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Yankees put Roger Clemens on the 15-day disabled list
because of a strained right groin. Reliever Darrell Einertson was
called up from Triple-A Columbus, and gave up two runs. ... Chicago
has won 11 of its last 12 road games. ... Frank Thomas hit an RBI
single, walked three times and nearly grounded into a triple play.
He beat Knoblauch's one-hop relay in the third. ... Chicago led the
AL with 136 errors last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
