<DOCNO> APW20000615.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies Have Bottomed Out  </HEADLINE>
By ROB MAADDI
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- This was supposed to be the year the
rebuilding ended for the Philadelphia Phillies. After 63 games,
however, the team has hit rock bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies, at 24-39, have the second-worst record in the
majors and are 16 games behind first-place Atlanta, which opens a
four-game series at Veterans Stadium on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one could've ever imagined this,'' said Curt Schilling, the
struggling ace who admits he's ''part of the problem, not the
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   After six straight losing seasons and 12 of 13, the Phillies
entered spring training with playoff aspirations following the
offseason acquisitions of Andy Ashby, a legitimate No. 2 starter,
and Mike Jackson, the top free-agent closer on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Philadelphia was 15{ games behind the Braves and out of
the pennant race by Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had high expectations going into the season. I definitely
wouldn't have thought we'd be in the position we're in now,''
catcher Mike Lieberthal said.
</P>
<P>
   The offense, considered to be the team's bright spot, has been a
major disappointment. The team is last in the NL in hitting (.245),
runs scored (258) and homers (63). The Phillies have scored two or
fewer runs in exactly one-third of their games, 21, winning one.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Phillies ranked fourth in the league in average
(.275) and sixth in runs (841).
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't explain it really. Guys are going out there every day,
trying to work it out,'' Lieberthal said. ''I don't know what it
is. I don't know if it's contagious or not. We're not scoring runs.
We're not getting hits with runners in scoring position. We're not
putting rallies together to where we put pressure on the pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Management, often criticized for having a small-market mentality
in a big-market city, opened their wallets and increased the
payroll from just under $30 million to over $45 million in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   But the moves failed miserably.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson did not throw a pitch for the Phillies, had shoulder
surgery and is out for the year. Ashby, a two-time All-Star, is 2-7
with a 6.16 ERA and has already indicated he doesn't want to
re-sign here after his contract runs out at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, Ashby and Paul Byrd, All-Stars last season, are a
combined 4-16. Byrd was exiled to Triple-A Scranton Wilkes-Barre on
June 2.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not pleased with where we are. Nobody is. A lot of things
have certainly not gone the way we planned. Our record is one of
them,'' manager Terry Francona said. ''But you don't throw in the
towel, you don't whine, you don't pout. If anything, you try and
work harder. It's the only option.''
</P>
<P>
   Francona took over in 1997 and led the team to a last-place
finish and two straight third-place finishes. After topping out at
13 games over .500 last Aug. 6, the Phillies lost 37 of their last
53 games and are 40-76 overall since.
</P>
<P>
   Still, general manager Ed Wade insists Francona's job is safe,
and the players continue to support their manager.
</P>
<P>
   ''Terry Francona is the last guy in the world responsible for
what's happening to us now,'' Schilling said. ''We're just not
performing. We're not hitting. We're not pitching. We're not
playing solid, fundamental baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're playing as hard as we can play, but that's irrelevant in
the big leagues. It's all about results.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Person, who has emerged as the team's ace, agrees with
Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see any way anybody can blame the manager,'' said
Person, who is 5-2 with a 3.25 ERA. ''He's not out there hitting.
He's not doing the pitching. It's not his fault. He puts the best
lineup he can out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies have shown some spurts. Earlier in the season, they
won two of three from the New York Mets and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   They swept the then-AL East leading Boston Red Sox at the start
of this month, but have since lost two of three to Tampa Bay,
Baltimore and Florida, who had a combined record of 27 games under
.500 entering Thursday.	   Despite what seems like a hopeless situation,
Francona won't say
the season is lost.
</P>
<P>
   ''Save the season? It's the middle of June,'' he said. ''We have
to show up Friday and try to win. That's what you're supposed to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashby thinks the team can turn it around just as easily.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main thing is to stay positive,'' he said. ''We have tons
of talent. We're scuffling, but you never know when it will change.
It can change Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.phillies.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
