<HEADLINE> Ecuador Strike Marked by Violence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Police fired tear gas to disperse about
100 protesters Thursday during a national strike that failed to
gather widespread support.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, business went on as usual in Ecuador's main
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The leftist-led Patriotic Front -- an umbrella organization
representing unions, student groups and grassroots organizations --
had hoped to paralyze this small Andean nation to protest the
switch to the U.S. dollar as the official currency.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross spokesman Cristian Rivera told The Associated Press
that three people, including a police officer, were wounded by
shotgun pellets during sporadic clashes between demonstrators and
authorities in various parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not immediately release information on the number of
arrests made.
</P>
<P>
   ''The strike does not merit our support,'' said Jose Ormaza, a
leader of informal merchants in Quito. ''We have to work every day
to earn our keep.''
</P>
<P>
   Small groups of protesters tried block provincial highways and
city avenues throughout the nation, but were dispersed by police
and soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   In Quito, students hijacked a bus, beat up the driver and set
the vehicle ablaze. And in coastal Guayaquil, protesters detonated
a small bomb that shattered the windows of a Citibank branch, with
no injuries reported.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 teachers held a peaceful rally in Quito. Ecuador's
23,000 public schools have been shut since mid-May when some
140,000 teachers refused to report to work, demanding salary
increases.
</P>
<P>
   The government is in the process of replacing the national
currency, the sucre, with the U.S. greenback. President Gustavo
Noboa hopes the move will stabilize the economy, promote business
investment and end Latin America's highest inflation, now running
at nearly 100 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue the dollar plan will hurt the poor by causing
prices to rise to international levels. Currently many basic food
products and services are subsidized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
