<HEADLINE> Former Chile Police Chief Dies  </HEADLINE>
By EVA VERGARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Retired Gen. Humberto Gordon Rubio, a
former junta member and ex-chief of dictator Augusto Pinochet's
secret police, died Thursday night while under house arrest, his
spokesman said. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon -- a trusted confidante of Pinochet during the dictator's
1973-90 rule -- was facing prosecution for human rights abuses at
the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's spokesman, lawyer Fernando Uribe Echeverria, said the
retired general died of a heart attack at his home in an exclusive
Santiago suburb. He added that Gordon's health had been
deteriorating as he defended himself against the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''This whole traumatic situation ... evidently had to have taken
its toll,'' said Uribe Echeverria, speaking of Gordon's indictment
and ongoing prosecution in connection with the 1982 death of a
prominent labor leader. He said Gordon had recently spent some time
in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, like some 40 former military officers, was being brought
to task by a newly emboldened judiciary that followed the
restoration of democracy and the end of 17 years of military rule
in 1990. He steadfastly maintained his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   After spending years as chief of Pinochet's feared secret
police, Gordon became a member of the dictator's ruling junta.
According to an official report, 3,190 people were killed under
Pinochet's regime, and more than 1,000 remain unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was facing prosecution by a judge in connection with the
1982 death of labor leader Tucapel Jimenez. The activist's body was
recovered in February 1982 in his car. His throat was cut and face
disfigured by five bullet wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Some 21 people, including other top military officers, are being
prosecuted in connection with that case.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's death was certain to deal another blow to Pinochet, the
ailing 84-year-old former strongman who last month was stripped of
his immunity from prosecution by a Santiago court amid moves to
prosecute the former dictator.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's lawyers have appealed to Chile's supreme court. The
lower court ruling, if allowed to stand, would allow Pinochet to
face trial on human rights charges including the disappearance of
opponents of his regime soon after the bloody 1973 coup that
toppled elected Marxist president Salvador Allende.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, as a senator for life, had previously enjoyed immunity
from prosecution and he also has proclaimed he did nothing wrong
during his rule. Some 113 criminal complaints have been filed
against him for alleged abuses stemming from his regime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 2305 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Savard, Mullen, Bush in Hockey Hall  </HEADLINE>
By IRA PODELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   Denis Savard and Joe Mullen have strong ties to Original Six
cities. The paths for the newest selections to the Hockey Hall of
Fame, though, were somewhat different.
</P>
<P>
   Savard, a Quebec native who starred in the Montreal junior
leagues, and Mullen, a New York City native whose father worked on
the Madison Square Garden ice for over 30 years, were chosen
Thursday to enter the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Walter L. Bush Jr., president of USA Hockey and a vice-president
of the International Ice Hockey Federation, will also be inducted
to the Toronto museum on Nov. 13, in the builders' category.
</P>
<P>
   Savard, 39, scored 473 goals and added 865 assists in a 17-year
career spent mostly with Chicago. He played three seasons with
Montreal, winning his only Stanley Cup there in 1993, and just over
one season with Tampa Bay before returning to the Blackhawks for
his final two-plus seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a surprise,'' Savard said of being chosen in his first
year of eligibility. ''It's probably one of the toughest halls to
get into in sports. As far as my profession is concerned, it's the
greatest thing to happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullen learned the game late, growing up in the Hell's Kitchen
area of New York City. He didn't don skates for the first time
until he was 10 years old and credits roller hockey for his
development.
</P>
<P>
   ''We definitely had more concrete than ice,'' said Mullen, who
had 502 goals and 561 assists in 17 seasons with St. Louis,
Calgary, Pittsburgh and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, having his father working at Madison Square Garden and
bringing home sticks from Rangers players and their opponents
didn't hurt his pursuit of a hockey career.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never had to sneak in,'' Mullen said. ''I never got to skate
in the old Madison Square Garden but I could look out my window and
see it. I was always busy playing roller hockey myself anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullen, who also enters in the first year he is eligible after a
mandatory three-year waiting period, was the first American-born
player to reach 500 goals and 1,000 points.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never looked at those accomplishments as being an American
thing,'' Mullen said. ''I looked at them as a milestone that's
great to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ''But being the first at anything always adds some flavor to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullen, 43, was a member of the 1989 Calgary Flames who won the
Stanley Cup. He also played with Pittsburgh when they won
consecutive titles in 1991 and '92.
</P>
<P>
   He had career highs with 51 goals and 110 points in 1989 and led
playoff scorers with 16 goals. Mullen also had five other seasons
in which he scored at least 40 goals.
</P>
<P>
   Savard had to leave the Blackhawks to get his only championship.
He was dealt to the Canadiens on June 29, 1990 for Chris Chelios.
</P>
<P>
   ''Montreal is a great hockey town and a great organization,''
said Savard, who finished in the top 10 in scoring five times --
including a career-high 131 points in 1987-88. ''I knew that when I
went there I had a great chance to win one.''
</P>
<P>
   Savard hoped to play for Montreal coming into the NHL, but those
plans were dashed when the Canadiens passed over him in the draft.
Montreal chose Doug Wickenheiser with the top pick, leaving Savard
to the Blackhawks at No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chicago was a special place for me,'' Savard said. ''I played
13 of my 17 years here. I'm still in Chicago and hopefully I'll be
here forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-10 native of Pointe Gatineau, Quebec, was known as a
great playmaker, but did have three straight years of at least 40
goals from 1985-86 through 1987-88. His 1,338 points rank 17th on
the NHL's career list. Savard retired in 1997 to become an
assistant coach with Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both Denis and I came into the league and got out at the same
time,'' Mullen said. ''To watch Denis on the ice and see him do his
thing was definitely worth the price of admission.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullen, despite his 5-9 frame, was able to fight to get in front
of the net to score.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing I remember the most is he was a great two-way
player,'' Savard said of Mullen, who was not drafted after a
four-year career at Boston College. ''He paid the price and was the
kind of player that never shied away from anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The 18-member selection committee consists of former players
Bobby Orr, Serge Savard, Stan Mikita and Marty Pavelich, NHL
vice-president Jim Gregory, general managers Pat Quinn of Toronto
and Harry Sinden of Boston, Tampa Bay Lightning consultant Cliff
Fletcher, and Emile Francis, the former NHL player, coach and
manager. Serge Savard and Denis Savard are not related.
</P>
<P>
   The media is represented on the committee by Red Fisher of the
Montreal Gazette, Jim Proudfoot of the Toronto Star and Bert
Raymond of The Montreal Journal, and broadcasters Dick Irvin, Frank
Selke and John Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Chynoweth of Edmonton, a director of the WHL junior league,
Washington Capitals president Richard Patrick and former referee
Frank Udvari make up the rest of the selectors.
</P>
<P>
   There are 319 members of the Hall, including 218 players, 14
referees and linesmen, and 87 builders.
</P>
<P>
   Rules stipulate that only those selected can be talked about by
the committee. Dale Hawerchuk and Glenn Anderson were thought to be
potential selections but were not chosen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 2309 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000615.0253 </DOCNO>
