<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Urged To Return Kuwait's Stuff  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan urged Iraq to
return government archives, museum pieces and military equipment
seized from Kuwait after its 1990 invasion.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to the Security Council Thursday, Annan agreed with
his special coordinator, retired Russian ambassador Yuli Vorontsov,
that while Iraq has returned ''a substantial quantity of
property,'' it has an obligation to return many more items to
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait maintains that during Iraq's seven-month occupation, it
took valuable pieces from the Islamic and National Museums,
archives from the foreign ministry, prime minister's office and
other government departments, and a significant quantity of
military hardware. Iraqi forces were routed from Kuwait by a
U.S.-led allied coalition during the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   A Security Council resolution adopted Dec. 17 outlined a new
Iraq policy, primarily aimed at returning weapons inspectors to
Iraq. But it also reiterated Iraq's obligation under the 1991
resolution that ended the Gulf War to return all looted Kuwaiti
property and account for over 600 missing Kuwaitis and called for
the appointment of a high-level coordinator to try to settle these
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is considered Iraq's strongest ally on the U.N. Security
Council, and Vorontsov's appointment in February to deal with both
the looted property and missing Kuwaitis issues was seen as a
serious new effort to bring them to closure after nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Annan reiterated in his first report to the council on efforts
to return Kuwaiti property that while Vorontsov's mandate comes
from the Dec. 17 resolution, ''understanding and goodwill are of
critical importance for the success of his mission.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is accompanied by a list of military equipment which
Kuwait says has not been returned including eight Mirage fighter
planes, 335 armored personnel carriers, 669 SAM surface-to-air
missiles, and over 3,700 TOW anti-tank missiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-15-00 2321 </TRAILER>
