<HEADLINE> Campfire Wilderness Rules Eased  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DULUTH, Minn. (AP) -- A ban on campfires in some of the nation's
most popular wilderness area is being eased after recent cold, wet
weather, federal officials announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Campfires had been banned for several weeks in more than a third
of the 1.1 million acre Boundary Waters Canoe Area, where a severe
windstorm last July 4 knocked down millions of trees.
</P>
<P>
   But after a recent cold weather spell, officials decided to
allow campfires in the area between 7 p.m. and midnight, Superior
National Forest spokeswoman Kris Reichenbach said. The midnight
cutoff will allow campfires to cool before morning, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The BWCA covers over 1,000 lakes and streams and draws more than
200,000 adventurers from around the world every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
