<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solomon Islands Police Can Return  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- Rebels who have seized the
capital said Thursday that they would allow police to return to
their jobs, but didn't say whether they would give them back their
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The well-armed rebels, who forced the leader of this South
Pacific nation to resign on Wednesday, said police would be
responsible for security in the capital city. But without the
weapons, which rebels looted from police headquarters last week,
the militants would continue to be the real enforcers.
</P>
<P>
   Police, who asked not to be identified, said late Thursday that
they still did not have their weapons and could not effectively
patrol the streets without them.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel statement said the police would work together with the
militants ''to ensure that there is a smooth transition to normal
policing in Honiara.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was signed by rebel leader Andrew Nori and Deputy
Commissioner of Police Wilfred Akao, who joined the rebels' drive
to oust Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign that the dispute was easing, some fighters from
the warring factions put down their weapons and shared food and
hugs Friday at a frontline checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   However, after about an hour, the fighters took up their guns
again and vowed not to disarm until a peace deal has been reached.
</P>
<P>
   In another development Friday, a group of about 70 women --
frustrated that men haven't brought peace -- approached the warring
groups with a simple message: Stop fighting and talk peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think as mothers, they are our sons. We brought them here
in our wombs and we love them and we want them to lay down their
guns,'' said Margaret Aihunu, a teacher who joined the women at a
rally in Honiara before leaving to meet the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict revolves around land. The indigenous residents of
the main island of Guadalcanal, known as Isatabus, have been
forcing out migrants from the nearby island of Malaita. About
20,000 Malaitans have been expelled over the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Angry they have not been compensated for lost land and homes,
Malaitans raided an armory, took over the capital and demanded a
change in government. The Isatabus retreated to the countryside,
where they own most of the land. Both sides have been honoring an
unwritten cease-fire that expires next week.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the prime minister resigned and announced a
12-member committee made up of government and opposition leaders
would try to arrange peace talks with the warring parties.
Ulufa'alu said he hoped a deal could be reached within two weeks,
allowing parliament to elect a new leader without the intimidation
of rebels.
</P>
<P>
   An Australian ship off the nation's coast may be used as a
neutral venue for the peace talks or for parliament, the Australian
Defense Department said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
