<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-15 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pirro as pure as Ivory soap, attorney says  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - Albert Pirro, husband of the
Westchester County district attorney, is 99.9 percent pure, ''like
the old Ivory Soap commercial,'' his lawyer said Thursday in
closing arguments at Pirro's tax evasion trial.
</P>
<P>
   But a prosecutor compared Pirro to Richard Nixon, prompting the
defense attorney to demand a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   In the second and final day of his summation, defense attorney
Gustave Newman tried to convince the federal jury that Pirro was
simply running his business affairs informally, treating all his
various companies as part of his household, when he used corporate
checks to buy personal items ranging from a guitar string to a
Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if the funds were going ''from Al Pirro's left pocket
to Al Pirro's right pocket,'' Newman said, with District Attorney
Jeanine Pirro in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Pirro and his accountant, his brother Anthony, are
accused of conspiring to evade taxes on $1.2 million of Albert
Pirro's income by disguising personal spending as deductible
business expenses. After a four-week trial, the jury is scheduled
to begin deliberating on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But first, Judge Barrington Parker will rule on Newman's demand
for a mistrial, which was prompted by prosecutor Cathy Seibel's
rebuttal. She noted that Nixon was driven from the presidency by
his own tape recordings and that many of the documents used against
the Pirros were their own canceled checks and records.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Nixon's case it was power that drove him and in this case
it was money that drove Albert Pirro, but sometimes people keep
very damaging information around,'' Seibel said.
</P>
<P>
   Newman objected strenuously, saying the remark was ''venomous
and could poison the jury.'' The judge allowed Seibel to continue
and reserved decision on the mistrial motion.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Newman told the jurors that Pirro, a real estate
developer and one of the state's top lobbyists, was ''indifferent''
to his bookkeeping. ''He was preoccupied with building business,
his irons in the fire,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a tiny line on a pie chart for the jury, Newman claimed
that only one-tenth of 1 percent of Pirro's corporate deductions
were being questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like the old Ivory Soap commercial, he's 99.9 percent pure,''
Newman said. The advertising slogan was actually ''99-44/100%
Pure.''
</P>
<P>
   Without saying so, Newman seemed to shift the blame for improper
deductions to Anthony Pirro, noting that when Albert Pirro signed
his tax returns, they had already been filled out and signed by his
brother and gave him no reason to be suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   But Roger Stavis, Anthony Pirro's lawyer, said a lack of
communication between the brothers - as well as some admittedly
sloppy work by Anthony - was the cause of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirro brothers ''did not have a particularly close
relationship,'' he said, and even counting social occasions, they
saw each other only a few times a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''What kind of a conspiracy is this?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Both defense attorneys took offense at Seibel's characterization
of the Pirro brothers as ''crooks.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Assistant U.S. attorneys are not supposed to call names like
that,'' Stavis said.
</P>
<P>
   Seibel laughed off some of the defense contentions, and said
Albert Pirro was resorting to ''the old blame-it-on-the-accountant
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the government's case was circumstantial,
Seibel said the evidence was nevertheless clear that ''what they
did only makes sense as a tax fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, Pirro said the final arguments brought
him ''one step closer to the end of a terrible ordeal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
