<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Teachers Inducted In Hall of Fame  </HEADLINE>
By LIB QUAID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Leslie Revis began her education in a home
that didn't have television or radio but did have grandparents and
great-grandparents with a proud Hispanic heritage and hours upon
hours of stories.
</P>
<P>
   ''I come from a long line of educators, some with certificates,
some without,'' said Revis, who was inducted along with four other
teachers Thursday into the National Teachers Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   As lead teacher in the foreign language department at Beaufort
High School in St. Helena Islands, S.C., Revis stepped in when
another teacher left her job with six months to go in the school
year. She added five classes to the six she was already teaching,
Revis said, and she was six months pregnant at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Berry, a principal and teacher at Columbia Elementary
School in Logansport, Ind., explained how she never wants kids to
feel embarrassed. So rather than nagging when chairs are pulled out
from tables, or closet doors left ajar, she developed an imaginary
allergy to disorder, sneezing or coughing to help students
remember.
</P>
<P>
   In her classroom, Charlotte the imaginary elephant steps on the
toes of rude children, and Mikey the imaginary bald eagle pecks the
nose of anyone who doesn't watch a classroom speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ''Children love it,'' Berry said. ''It's an atmosphere of
loving. My children learn loving -- I mean, love learning. None of
you would be here if not for your teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Also inducted were Susie Haas, who teaches kindergarten at John
Adams Elementary School in Riverside, Calif.; Debi Barrett-Hayes,
an art teacher at Florida State University School in Tallahassee,
Fla.; and Sandra Worsham, a retired English teacher from
Milledgeville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Located in Emporia, Kan., the Hall of Fame inducted its first
five teachers in 1992. Last year's honorees included Jaime
Escalante, the retired math teacher who gained national attention
after helping a group of low-income East Los Angeles students pass
the tough Advanced Placement calculus exam. His story was the basis
of the 1987 film ''Stand and Deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of fame officials work closely with Emporia State
University's Teachers College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
