<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislation passed to raise PINS age to 18  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state Assembly approved a measure that
would allow parents to retain legal control of disobedient
teen-agers until they reach 18 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the bill approved late Thursday would revise the
current ''Person in Need of Supervision'' by raising the cutoff age
from 16 to 18. The chamber overwhelmingly passed the bill, 142-1.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation now goes to Gov. George Pataki for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Under current state law, a person in need of supervision, or
PIN, is defined as a male under the age of 16 or a female under the
age of 18 who does not attend school, is in frequent trouble with
police or is beyond parental control. Runaways can be returned by
authorities to their homes if they fall under the PINS age.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, the distinction between the ages of boys and girls in
the PINS law was declared unconstitutional, and since then the
state's Family Courts have used 16 to be the cutoff PINS age across
the board.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled state Senate has in previous years
passed the bill to raise the PINS age and did so again in May. But
the measure never made it out of committee in the Democrat-led
Assembly until this year.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Stephen Kaufman, a Bronx Democrat and sponsor of the
bill, said a ''confluence'' of factors, including strong support
among parents as well as other Assembly members, enabled the
passage of the bill in his chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill undoes an injustice,'' Kaufman said. ''This will
give parents the ability to reunify themselves with their
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Helene Weinstein, who voted in favor of the bill,
cautioned that raising the PINS age would also mean the need for
more resources for Family Courts and other social service agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''By passing this bill without providing resources, we'll be
flooding an already overfilled family court. It's critical that we
need to dramatically increase (those resources),'' the Brooklyn
Democrat said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said at an Albany news conference earlier Thursday that
he hasn't seen the PINS legislation and added that ''we'll be glad
to take a look at it'' when the bill is sent to his office.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by Pataki, the law would take effect Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who lobbied for passage of the bill during the past week
in the state Capitol monitored Assembly proceedings late into
Thursday night. They applauded when the chamber finally approved
the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Reed said there was ''absolutely nothing we could do''
three years ago when her then 17-year-old son ran away from their
suburban Syracuse home. She said raising the PINS age to 18 would
have allowed police to bring her son back and given her more time
to discipline the teen.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd have another year to try to work with him, to work with
any program that he was in,'' Reed said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
